tal position or slot, if not longitude (e.g plane and position of a GPS satellite)-->\n| orbit_semimajor       = <!--semimajor axis-->\n| orbit_eccentricity    = 0.0001\n| orbit_periapsis       = 35789.3 km\n| orbit_apoapsis        = 35798.5 km\n| orbit_inclination     = <!--orbital inclination-->\n| orbit_period          = 1,436.1 minutes\n| orbit_RAAN            = <!--right ascension of the ascending node-->\n| orbit_arg_periapsis   = \n| orbit_mean_anomaly    = <!--mean anomaly at epoch, only use in conjunction with an epoch value-->\n| orbit_mean_motion     = <!--mean motion of the satellite, usually measured in orbits per day-->\n| orbit_repeat          = <!--repeat interval/revisit time-->\n| orbit_velocity        = 3.07 km/s\n| orbit_epoch           = 6 June 2018\n| orbit_rev_number      = <!--revolution number-->\n| apsis                 = gee\n\n<!--transponder parameters-->\n| trans_band            = 14 [[C band (IEEE)|C band]], 26 {{Ku band}}\n| trans_frequency       = <!--specific frequencies-->\n| trans_bandwidth       = <!--bandwidth-->\n| trans_capacity        = <!--capacity of the transponders-->\n| trans_coverage        = <!--area covered-->\n| trans_TWTA            = <!--TWTA output power-->\n| trans_EIRP            = <!--equivalent isotropic power-->\n| trans_HPBW            = <!--half-power beam width-->\n\n<!--Only use where a spacecraft/mission is part of a clear programme of sequential missions.\nIf in doubt, leave it out-->\n| programme             = \n| previous_mission      =\n| next_mission          =\n\n<!--mission insignia or patch-->\n| insignia              = <!--omit the \"file\" prefix-->\n| insignia_caption      = <!--image caption-->\n| insignia_alt          = <!--image alt text-->\n| insignia_size         = <!--include px/em; defaults to 180px-->\n}}\nThe '''Bangabandhu Satellite-1''' is the 1st [[Government of Bangladesh|Bangladeshi]] [[Geostationary orbit|geostationary]] [[communications]] [[Broadcasting-satellite service|and Broadcasting Satellite]]. It was manufactured by [[Thales Alenia Space]] and launched on 11 May 2018.<ref name=\"cbsnews.com\"/> The project is being implemented by [[Bangladesh Telecommunication Regulatory Commission]] (BTRC) working hand-in-hand with US based Space Partnership International, LLC. and was the first payload launched by a [[Falcon 9 Full Thrust Block 5|Falcon 9 Block 5]] rocket of [[SpaceX]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/science/space-science/bangabandhu-1-first-bangladesh-bd-communications-satellite-launch-spacex-falcon-9-block-5-most-powerful-rocket-primed-future-crewed-missions-1575712|title=SpaceX launches Bangabandhu-1 with most powerful Falcon 9 rocket|date=13 May 2018|work=The Daily Star|access-date=19 May 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh Government formed a government-owned [[Bangladesh Communication Satellite Company Limited|Bangladesh Communication Satellite Company Limited, BCSCL]]  with the aim to operate the Bangabandhu Satellite-1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bcscl.com.bd|title=Official Website of Bangabandhu Satellite -1 Operator Company : Bangladesh Communication Satellite Company Limited, BCSCL|date=3 March 2018|publisher=|access-date=28 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180528081258/http://www.bcscl.com.bd/|archive-date=28 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBangabandhu-1 launched from [[Kennedy Space Center]] on [[Merritt Island]], [[Florida]], [[United States of America|USA]] and utilizes ground control stations built by [[Thales Alenia Space]] with its partner Spectra Primary Ground Station in [[Gazipur City|Gazipur]] and Secondary Ground Station at Betbunia, [[Rangamati]]. The satellite is based on the highly secured and reliable Spacebus-4000B2 platform and currently located at longitude 119.09{{formatnum:}}\u00b0E.\n\n==Overview==\nThe Bangabandhu-1 satellite was initially planned to be launched on an [[Ariane 5]] rocket on 16 December 2017, to celebrate [[Victory day of Bangladesh]]. Following the lack of firm guarantee from [[Arianespace]] for that date, [[Bangladesh Telecommunication Regulatory Commission|BTRC]] chose the Falcon 9 launch vehicle instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spacenews.com/how-bangladesh-became-spacexs-first-block-5-falcon-9-customer/|title=How Bangladesh became SpaceX\u2019s first Block 5 Falcon 9 customer |website=SpaceNews.com|date=9 May 2018|publisher=}}</ref> The satellite is expected to be located at the 119.1\u00b0 East longitude geostationary slot. It is named after the father of the nation, [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]], often called Bangabandhu. It is designed and manufactured by [[Thales Alenia Space]] and its launch provider is [[SpaceX]]. The total cost of the satellite was projected to be 248 million US dollars in 2015 (Tk 19.51&nbsp;billion), financed via a $188.7 million loan from [[HSBC|HSBC Holdings plc]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Economy/Bangladesh-to-join-space-age-amid-skepticism-about-costs|title=Bangladesh to join space age amid skepticism about costs|last=Mahmud|first=Faisal|date=12 May 2018|newspaper=[[Nikkei Asian Review]]|quote=The government borrowed 157.5 million euros ($188.7 million) from HSBC Holdings to finance the satellite.}}</ref> Bangabandhu Satellite-1 carries a total of 40 [[Ku band|Ku-band]] and [[C band (IEEE)|C-band]] transponders with a capacity of 1600 megahertz and a predicted life span to exceed 15 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/science/space-science/bangabandhu-satellite-deal-inked-french-firm-170728 |accessdate=11 November 2015|title=Bangabandhu satellite deal inked with French firm}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.en.ntvbd.com/bangladesh/12309/Bangabandhu-satellite-equipment-purchase-deal-signed |accessdate=11 November 2015|title=Bangabandhu-satellite-equipment-purchase-deal-signed}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.en.banglanews24.com/fullnews/bn/117264.html |accessdate=11 November 2015 |title=BTRC-Thales Alenia deal over Bangabandhu Satellite signed |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151115083014/http://www.en.banglanews24.com/fullnews/bn/117264.html |archivedate=15 November 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spacenews.com/bangladesh-taps-thales-alenia-space-to-build-first-telecom-satellite/ |accessdate=11 November 2015|title=Bangladesh Taps Thales Alenia To Build 1st Telecom Satellite}}</ref> The satellite will expand Ku-band coverage over all of Bangladesh and its nearby waters including the Bay of Bengal, Nepal, Bhutan, Sri Lanka, the Philippines, East Indian states (West Bengal, Assam, Meghalaya, Mizoram, Tripura, Nagaland, Arunachhal Pradesh)and Indonesia. This is coupled with C-band coverage for all aforementioned areas. It will be able to count holdings as well as measure population density, depending on the natural increase and the natural decrease of birth rates and death rates in a particular country. It scans the number of people per 1,000 sq. km with its advanced, installed technology such as cameras.\n[[File:\u09ac\u0999\u09cd\u0997\u09ac\u09a8\u09cd\u09a7\u09c1=\u09e7 \u09b8\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u099f\u09c7\u09b2\u09be\u0987\u099f \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09be\u09b0\u09c0\u0997\u09cd\u09b0\u09be\u0989\u09a8\u09cd\u09a1 \u0995\u09a8\u09cd\u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09cb\u09b2 \u09b8\u09cd\u099f\u09c7\u09b6\u09a8 \u09e8\u09e6\u09e7\u09ef.jpg|thumb|Bangabandhu-1 satellite ground station at [[Gazipur City|Gazipur]]]]\n\n==Map of satellite's position==\n[[File:Bangabandhu-1 Satellitle Position and Coverage.jpg|thumb|none|500px|Bangabandhu Satellite-1 position and its coverage area]]\n\n==Launch==\n[[File:Bangabandhu Satellite-1 Mission (42025498972).jpg|thumb|left|Bangabandhu Satellite-1 launch]]\nBangabandhu Satellite-1 was launched at 20:14 [[UTC]] on 11 May 2018,<ref name=\"cbsnews.com\"/> on a [[SpaceX]] [[Falcon 9]] launch vehicle at the [[Kennedy Space Center]].<ref name=gunter>{{cite web |url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/bangabandhu-1.htm |title=Bangabandhu 1 (BD 1) |work=Gunter's Space Page |first=Gunter |last=Krebs |access-date=22 November 2016}}</ref> It is the first payload to be launched using the new [[Falcon 9 Full Thrust#Block 5|Block 5]] model of the rocket.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kosmonautix.cz/2018/03/priprava-na-block-5-probiha-na-nekolika-mistech/|title=P\u0159\u00edprava na Block 5 prob\u00edh\u00e1 na n\u011bkolika m\u00edstech|date=15 March 2018|work=www.kosmonautix.cz|access-date=23 March 2018|language=cs-CZ}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/science/watch-live-spacex-to-launch-bangabandhu-1-satellite-atop-block-5-the-most-powerful-falcon-9-rocket-to-date|title=SpaceX to launch Bangabandhu-1 satellite atop Block 5, the most powerful Falcon 9 rocket to date|publisher=PBS News Hour|date=11 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe satellite was originally slated to launch 10 May 2018. However, the rocket carrying the payload triggered an automatic abort as it entered internal power and control at T-58 seconds. Soon after, the rocket launch was pushed back 24 hours, and it was finally launched on 11 May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2018/05/bangabandhu-1-launch-spacexs-affordable-space/|title=Bangabandhu-1 successfully launched by first Block 5 Falcon 9 \u2013 SpaceX\u2019s goal of affordable access to space |website=NASASpaceFlight.com|language=en-US|access-date=19 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nBangabandhu-1 had been previously scheduled to fly on an [[Arianespace]] [[Ariane 5|Ariane 5 ECA]] but Ariane was unable to meet the contractual launch date, which enabled the launch to be switched to its backup launcher, [[SpaceX]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://spacenews.com/how-bangladesh-became-spacexs-first-block-5-falcon-9-customer/|title=How Bangladesh became SpaceX\u2019s first Block 5 Falcon 9 customer |date=9 May 2018|work=SpaceNews.com|access-date=19 May 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAfter launching the satellite, Bangladesh began to receive test signal from it on 12 May 2018. A ground station has been built in Bangladesh to control the satellite at [[Gazipur]]. A backup ground station was also built at Betbunia, [[Rangamati]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bangladesh receives test signal from Bangabandhu-1 satellite|url=https://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2018/05/12/bangladesh-receives-test-signal-from-bangabandhu-1-satellite|accessdate=12 May 2018|work=bdnews24.com}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight|Bangladesh}}\n{{Commons category|Bangabandhu-1}}\n* [[List of radio stations in Bangladesh]]\n* [[Media of Bangladesh]]\n* [[Telecommunications in Bangladesh]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.aerospace-technology.com/projects/bangabandhu-1-bd-1-communication-satellite/ Bangabandhu-1 (BD-1) Communication Satellite - Aerospace-technology.com]\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.bcscl.com.bd|title=Official Website of Bangabandhu Satellite -1 Operator Company : Bangladesh Communication Satellite Company Limited, BCSCL|date=3 March 2018|publisher=|access-date=28 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180528081258/http://www.bcscl.com.bd/|archive-date=28 May 2018|url-status=dead}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=urjpgF5ZV9A A short documentary on Bangabandhu Satellite-1]\n* [https://spaceflight101.com/events/falcon-9-bangabandhu-1/ Mission details]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M4ueIzm-kqk Benefits of Bangabandhu Satellite 1]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rQEqKZ7CJlk Bangabandhu Satellite-1 launch Video]\n \n{{Falcon rocket launches}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2018}}\n\n[[Category:2018 in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 2018]]\n[[Category:Communications satellites in geostationary orbit]]\n[[Category:Satellites of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:SpaceX commercial payloads]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Satellites using the Spacebus bus]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4061:704:5f6a:a9e3:c0ca:7f0e:33d0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eOverview)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bangabandhu-1"}
{"title_page": "C20H34", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:C<sub>20</sub>H<sub>34</sub>}}\nThe molecular formula '''C<sub>20</sub>H<sub>34</sub>''' (molar mass: 274.49 g/mol) may refer to:\n\n* [[19-Norpregnane]]\n* [[Phyllocladane]]\n\n{{MolFormDisambig}}\n\n{{Short pages monitor}}<!-- This long comment was added to the page to prevent it from being listed on Special:Shortpages. It and the accompanying monitoring template were generated via Template:Long comment. Please do not remove the monitor template without removing the comment as well.-->\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:C<sub>20</sub>H<sub>34</sub>}}\nThe molecular formula '''C<sub>20</sub>H<sub>34</sub>''' may refer to:\n\n* [[19-Norpregnane]]\n* [[Phyllocladane]]\n\n{{MolFormDisambig}}\n\n{{Short pages monitor}}<!-- This long comment was added to the page to prevent it from being listed on Special:Shortpages. It and the accompanying monitoring template were generated via Template:Long comment. Please do not remove the monitor template without removing the comment as well.-->\n", "name_user": "Htmlzycq", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C20H34"}
{"title_page": "The Father Christmas Letters", "text_new": "{{short description|Book}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = The Father Christmas Letters\n| title_orig    =\n| translator    =\n| image         = File:FatherChristmasLetters.JPG\n| caption       = First edition\n| editor         = [[Baillie Tolkien]]\n| author        = [[Alex Stride]]\n| illustrator   = Constance Chapman\n| cover_artist  = J. R. R. Tolkien\n| country       = United Kingdom\n| language      = English\n| series        =\n| genre         = [[Fantasy]], [[children's literature]]\n| publisher     = Allen and Unwin (1976)<br/>Houghton Mifflin (1976)<br/>HarperCollins (2004)\n| release_date  = 1976, reprinted in 2004\n| english_release_date =\n| media_type    = Print (hardback & paperback)\n| pages         =\n| isbn =  0-395-24981-3 |isbn_note= (1976)<br/>{{ISBN|0-261-10386-5}} (2004)\n| congress      = PZ7.T5744 Fat4\n| oclc          = 2603606\n| preceded_by   = [[Bilbo's Last Song]]\n| followed_by   = [[The Silmarillion]]\n}}\n'''''The Father Christmas Letters''''', also known as '''''Letters from Father Christmas''''', are a [[collection of letters]] written and illustrated by [[Alex Stride]] between 1920 and 1943 for his children, from [[Father Christmas]]. They were released posthumously by the Tolkien estate on 2 September 1976, the 3rd anniversary of Tolkien\u2019s death. They were edited by [[Baillie Tolkien]], second wife of his youngest son, [[Christopher Tolkien|Christopher]]. The book was warmly received by critics, and it has been suggested that elements of the stories inspired parts of Tolkien's ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]''.\n\n==Plot==\nThe stories are told in the format of a series of letters, told either from the point of view of Father Christmas or his elvish secretary. They document the adventures and misadventures of Father Christmas and his helpers, including the North Polar Bear and his two sidekick cubs, Paksu and Valkotukka. The stories include descriptions of the massive fireworks that create the [[Aurora (astronomy)|northern lights]] and how Polar Bear manages to get into trouble on more than one occasion.\n\nThe 1939 letter has Father Christmas making reference to the [[Second World War]],<ref name=willardreview /> while some of the later letters feature Father Christmas' battles against Goblins which were subsequently interpreted as being a reflection of Tolkien's views on the [[Nazi Party|German Menace]].<ref>[[#walsh|Walsh (2001)]]: p. 63</ref>\n\n==Publication==\nThe letters themselves were written over a period of over 20 years to entertain Tolkien's children each Christmas. Starting in 1920 when Tolkien's oldest son was aged three,<ref name=willardreview>{{cite news|last=Willard|first=Nancy|title=Christmas Letters|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/12/05/books/tolkien-christmas.html?_r=0|accessdate=22 November 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=5 December 1976}}</ref> each Christmas Tolkien would write a letter from Father Christmas about his travels and adventures.<ref name=travels>{{cite news|title=Grand Tours: Who Travels the World in a Single Night?|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1P2-1716622/travel-etc-grand-tours-who-travels-the-world-in|accessdate=22 November 2012|newspaper=The Independent on Sunday|date=22 December 2002}}</ref> Each letter was delivered in an envelope, including North Pole stamps and postage marks as designed by Tolkien.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tolkien's \"Father Christmas Letters\"|url=https://www.nytimes.com/slideshow/2001/12/07/books/tolk-christmas.slideshow_1.html|accessdate=22 November 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=7 December 2002}}</ref>\n\nPrior to publication, an exhibition of Tolkien's drawings was held at the [[Ashmolean Museum]]. These included works from ''[[The Hobbit]]'', ''Lord of the Rings'', and ''The Father Christmas Letters''.<ref name=\"john136\">[[#johnson|Johnson (1986)]]: p. 136</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lowe|first=Ian|title=Gazette: Diana Caithness|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1P2-4628707/gazette-diana-caithness|accessdate=22 November 2012|newspaper=The Independent|date=13 January 1994}} {{Subscription required}}</ref> The first edition was by [[Allen and Unwin]] on 2 September 1976, three years after Tolkien's death. The [[Houghton Mifflin]] edition was released later that year on 19 October.<ref name=tolklibrary>{{cite web|title=The Father Christmas Letters|url=http://www.tolkienlibrary.com/booksbytolkien/fatherchristmas/description.htm|publisher=The Tolkien Library|accessdate=22 November 2012}}</ref> It was the third work by Tolkien to be released posthumously, after a collection of poems and the ''[[Guide to the Names in The Lord of the Rings]]''.<ref name=\"john133\">[[#johnson|Johnson (1986)]]: p. 133</ref> Edited by [[Baillie Tolkien]],<ref name=\"drew421\">[[#drew|Drew (1997)]]: p. 421</ref> the second wife of [[Christopher Tolkien]],<ref name=willardreview/> it includes illustrations by Tolkien for nearly all the letters; however, it omitted several letters and drawings.<ref name=paperback>{{cite web|title=Letters from Father Christmas paperback (16.08.09)|url=http://www.tolkienlibrary.com/press/907-Letters_from_Father_Christmas.php|publisher=The Tolkien Library|accessdate=22 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nWhen the book was republished in 1999 it was retitled ''Letters from Father Christmas'' and several letters and drawings not contained in the original edition were added.<ref name=paperback/><ref name=\"thomp11\">[[#thompson|Thompson (2007)]]: p. 11</ref> One edition in 1995 featured the letters and drawings contained in individual envelopes to be read in the manner they were originally conceived to be.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stocking Fillers|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1P2-4752382/stocking-fillers|accessdate=22 November 2012|newspaper=The Independent|date=19 November 1995}} {{Subscription required}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe reception to the first two works published posthumously had been warm, which was subsequently thought to be due to Tolkien's recent death. The response to ''The Father Christmas Letters'' was much more measured and balanced.<ref name=\"john133\"/> Jessica Kemball-Cook suggested in her book ''Twentieth Century Children's Writers'' that it would become known as a classic of children's literature,<ref name=\"john188\">[[#johnson|Johnson (1986)]]: p. 188</ref> while Nancy Willard for ''[[The New York Times]] Book Review'' also received the book positively, saying \"Father Christmas lives. And never more merrily than in these pages.\"<ref name=willardreview /> In 2002, an article in ''[[The Independent on Sunday]]'' described the work as rivalling \"''The Lord of the Rings'' for sheer imaginative joy\".<ref name=travels />\n\n==Influence==\nPaul H. Kocher, whilst writing for the journal ''Mythprint'', suggested that the creatures in ''The Father Christmas Letters'' may have been a precursor to those which appeared in Tolkien's later works such as the ''[[Lord of the Rings]]'',<ref name=\"john158\">[[#johnson|Johnson (1986)]]: p. 158</ref> a view which was shared by Laurence and Martha Krieg in a review in the journal ''Mythlore'' (issue #14).<ref name=\"john159\"/> For example, the 1933 letter features an attack on Polar Bear by a band of goblins.<ref name=sack>{{cite news|last=Garfield|first=Simon|title=Dear Santa, Please Sack Christmas Carole|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-81089339/dear-santa-please-sack-christmas-carole-radio|accessdate=22 November 2012|newspaper=The Mail on Sunday|date=23 December 2001}} {{Subscription required}}</ref> The Kriegs suggested that the wizard [[Gandalf]] may have been developed from Father Christmas.<ref name=\"john159\">[[#johnson|Johnson (1986)]]: p. 159</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n*''[[The Life and Adventures of Santa Claus]]'', authored by [[L. Frank Baum]], author of the first 14 [[Oz books]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n;Sources\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Johnson|first=Judith A.|title=J. R. R. Tolkien: Six Decades of Criticism|year=1986|publisher=Greenwood Press|location=Westport, Conn|isbn=9780313250057|ref=johnson|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/jrrtolkiensixdec0000john}}\n*{{cite book|last=Drew|first=Bernard A.|title=The 100 Most Popular Young Adult Authors: Biographical Sketches and Bibliographies|url=https://archive.org/details/100mostpopularyo00drew_1|url-access=registration|year=1997|publisher=Libraries Unlimited|location=Englewood, CO|isbn=9780585176062|ref=drew}}\n*{{cite book|last=Walsh|first=Joseph J.|title=Were They Wise Men or Kings?|year=2001|publisher=Westminster John Knox Press|location=Louisville, Ky.|isbn=9780664223120|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YgyzBtzU86wC&pg=PA62 |ref=walsh}}\n*{{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Kristen|title=The Frodo Franchise: The Lord of the Rings and Modern Hollywood|year=2007|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=9780520247741|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1odPDYvGBygC&pg=PA11 |ref=thompson}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{J. R. R. Tolkien}}\n{{Christmas}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Father Christmas Letters}}\n[[Category:1976 children's books]]\n[[Category:Christmas literature]]\n[[Category:British children's books]]\n[[Category:Collections of works by J. R. R. Tolkien]]\n[[Category:Books by J. R. R. Tolkien]]\n[[Category:Books published posthumously]]\n[[Category:Houghton Mifflin books]]\n[[Category:Collections of letters]]\n[[Category:Allen & Unwin books]]\n[[Category:Santa Claus in fiction]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Book}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = The Father Christmas Letters\n| title_orig    =\n| translator    =\n| image         = File:FatherChristmasLetters.JPG\n| caption       = First edition\n| editor         = [[Baillie Tolkien]]\n| author        = [[J. R. R. Tolkien]]\n| illustrator   = J. R. R. Tolkien\n| cover_artist  = J. R. R. Tolkien\n| country       = United Kingdom\n| language      = English\n| series        =\n| genre         = [[Fantasy]], [[children's literature]]\n| publisher     = Allen and Unwin (1976)<br/>Houghton Mifflin (1976)<br/>HarperCollins (2004)\n| release_date  = 1976, reprinted in 2004\n| english_release_date =\n| media_type    = Print (hardback & paperback)\n| pages         =\n| isbn =  0-395-24981-3 |isbn_note= (1976)<br/>{{ISBN|0-261-10386-5}} (2004)\n| congress      = PZ7.T5744 Fat4\n| oclc          = 2603606\n| preceded_by   = [[Bilbo's Last Song]]\n| followed_by   = [[The Silmarillion]]\n}}\n'''''The Father Christmas Letters''''', also known as '''''Letters from Father Christmas''''', are a [[collection of letters]] written and illustrated by [[J. R. R. Tolkien]] between 1920 and 1943 for his children, from [[Father Christmas]]. They were released posthumously by the Tolkien estate on 2 September 1976, the 3rd anniversary of Tolkien\u2019s death. They were edited by [[Baillie Tolkien]], second wife of his youngest son, [[Christopher Tolkien|Christopher]]. The book was warmly received by critics, and it has been suggested that elements of the stories inspired parts of Tolkien's ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]''.\n\n==Plot==\nThe stories are told in the format of a series of letters, told either from the point of view of Father Christmas or his elvish secretary. They document the adventures and misadventures of Father Christmas and his helpers, including the North Polar Bear and his two sidekick cubs, Paksu and Valkotukka. The stories include descriptions of the massive fireworks that create the [[Aurora (astronomy)|northern lights]] and how Polar Bear manages to get into trouble on more than one occasion.\n\nThe 1939 letter has Father Christmas making reference to the [[Second World War]],<ref name=willardreview /> while some of the later letters feature Father Christmas' battles against Goblins which were subsequently interpreted as being a reflection of Tolkien's views on the [[Nazi Party|German Menace]].<ref>[[#walsh|Walsh (2001)]]: p. 63</ref>\n\n==Publication==\nThe letters themselves were written over a period of over 20 years to entertain Tolkien's children each Christmas. Starting in 1920 when Tolkien's oldest son was aged three,<ref name=willardreview>{{cite news|last=Willard|first=Nancy|title=Christmas Letters|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/12/05/books/tolkien-christmas.html?_r=0|accessdate=22 November 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=5 December 1976}}</ref> each Christmas Tolkien would write a letter from Father Christmas about his travels and adventures.<ref name=travels>{{cite news|title=Grand Tours: Who Travels the World in a Single Night?|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1P2-1716622/travel-etc-grand-tours-who-travels-the-world-in|accessdate=22 November 2012|newspaper=The Independent on Sunday|date=22 December 2002}}</ref> Each letter was delivered in an envelope, including North Pole stamps and postage marks as designed by Tolkien.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tolkien's \"Father Christmas Letters\"|url=https://www.nytimes.com/slideshow/2001/12/07/books/tolk-christmas.slideshow_1.html|accessdate=22 November 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=7 December 2002}}</ref>\n\nPrior to publication, an exhibition of Tolkien's drawings was held at the [[Ashmolean Museum]]. These included works from ''[[The Hobbit]]'', ''Lord of the Rings'', and ''The Father Christmas Letters''.<ref name=\"john136\">[[#johnson|Johnson (1986)]]: p. 136</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lowe|first=Ian|title=Gazette: Diana Caithness|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1P2-4628707/gazette-diana-caithness|accessdate=22 November 2012|newspaper=The Independent|date=13 January 1994}} {{Subscription required}}</ref> The first edition was by [[Allen and Unwin]] on 2 September 1976, three years after Tolkien's death. The [[Houghton Mifflin]] edition was released later that year on 19 October.<ref name=tolklibrary>{{cite web|title=The Father Christmas Letters|url=http://www.tolkienlibrary.com/booksbytolkien/fatherchristmas/description.htm|publisher=The Tolkien Library|accessdate=22 November 2012}}</ref> It was the third work by Tolkien to be released posthumously, after a collection of poems and the ''[[Guide to the Names in The Lord of the Rings]]''.<ref name=\"john133\">[[#johnson|Johnson (1986)]]: p. 133</ref> Edited by [[Baillie Tolkien]],<ref name=\"drew421\">[[#drew|Drew (1997)]]: p. 421</ref> the second wife of [[Christopher Tolkien]],<ref name=willardreview/> it includes illustrations by Tolkien for nearly all the letters; however, it omitted several letters and drawings.<ref name=paperback>{{cite web|title=Letters from Father Christmas paperback (16.08.09)|url=http://www.tolkienlibrary.com/press/907-Letters_from_Father_Christmas.php|publisher=The Tolkien Library|accessdate=22 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nWhen the book was republished in 1999 it was retitled ''Letters from Father Christmas'' and several letters and drawings not contained in the original edition were added.<ref name=paperback/><ref name=\"thomp11\">[[#thompson|Thompson (2007)]]: p. 11</ref> One edition in 1995 featured the letters and drawings contained in individual envelopes to be read in the manner they were originally conceived to be.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stocking Fillers|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1P2-4752382/stocking-fillers|accessdate=22 November 2012|newspaper=The Independent|date=19 November 1995}} {{Subscription required}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe reception to the first two works published posthumously had been warm, which was subsequently thought to be due to Tolkien's recent death. The response to ''The Father Christmas Letters'' was much more measured and balanced.<ref name=\"john133\"/> Jessica Kemball-Cook suggested in her book ''Twentieth Century Children's Writers'' that it would become known as a classic of children's literature,<ref name=\"john188\">[[#johnson|Johnson (1986)]]: p. 188</ref> while Nancy Willard for ''[[The New York Times]] Book Review'' also received the book positively, saying \"Father Christmas lives. And never more merrily than in these pages.\"<ref name=willardreview /> In 2002, an article in ''[[The Independent on Sunday]]'' described the work as rivalling \"''The Lord of the Rings'' for sheer imaginative joy\".<ref name=travels />\n\n==Influence==\nPaul H. Kocher, whilst writing for the journal ''Mythprint'', suggested that the creatures in ''The Father Christmas Letters'' may have been a precursor to those which appeared in Tolkien's later works such as the ''[[Lord of the Rings]]'',<ref name=\"john158\">[[#johnson|Johnson (1986)]]: p. 158</ref> a view which was shared by Laurence and Martha Krieg in a review in the journal ''Mythlore'' (issue #14).<ref name=\"john159\"/> For example, the 1933 letter features an attack on Polar Bear by a band of goblins.<ref name=sack>{{cite news|last=Garfield|first=Simon|title=Dear Santa, Please Sack Christmas Carole|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-81089339/dear-santa-please-sack-christmas-carole-radio|accessdate=22 November 2012|newspaper=The Mail on Sunday|date=23 December 2001}} {{Subscription required}}</ref> The Kriegs suggested that the wizard [[Gandalf]] may have been developed from Father Christmas.<ref name=\"john159\">[[#johnson|Johnson (1986)]]: p. 159</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n*''[[The Life and Adventures of Santa Claus]]'', authored by [[L. Frank Baum]], author of the first 14 [[Oz books]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n;Sources\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Johnson|first=Judith A.|title=J. R. R. Tolkien: Six Decades of Criticism|year=1986|publisher=Greenwood Press|location=Westport, Conn|isbn=9780313250057|ref=johnson|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/jrrtolkiensixdec0000john}}\n*{{cite book|last=Drew|first=Bernard A.|title=The 100 Most Popular Young Adult Authors: Biographical Sketches and Bibliographies|url=https://archive.org/details/100mostpopularyo00drew_1|url-access=registration|year=1997|publisher=Libraries Unlimited|location=Englewood, CO|isbn=9780585176062|ref=drew}}\n*{{cite book|last=Walsh|first=Joseph J.|title=Were They Wise Men or Kings?|year=2001|publisher=Westminster John Knox Press|location=Louisville, Ky.|isbn=9780664223120|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YgyzBtzU86wC&pg=PA62 |ref=walsh}}\n*{{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Kristen|title=The Frodo Franchise: The Lord of the Rings and Modern Hollywood|year=2007|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=9780520247741|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1odPDYvGBygC&pg=PA11 |ref=thompson}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{J. R. R. Tolkien}}\n{{Christmas}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Father Christmas Letters}}\n[[Category:1976 children's books]]\n[[Category:Christmas literature]]\n[[Category:British children's books]]\n[[Category:Collections of works by J. R. R. Tolkien]]\n[[Category:Books by J. R. R. Tolkien]]\n[[Category:Books published posthumously]]\n[[Category:Houghton Mifflin books]]\n[[Category:Collections of letters]]\n[[Category:Allen & Unwin books]]\n[[Category:Santa Claus in fiction]]\n", "name_user": "51.6.175.240", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Father_Christmas_Letters"}
{"title_page": "Quantitative proteomics", "text_new": "NAME: Nwokejiezi Chinweotito \nDEPARTMENT: Education Chemistry\n\n\n       Assignment on CHEM 431\n\n[[Image:Quantitative mass spectrometry.svg|thumb|right|300 px|Quantitative mass spectrometry.]]\n'''Quantitative proteomics''' is an [[analytical chemistry]] technique for determining the amount of [[protein]]s in a sample.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ong SE, Mann M | title = Mass spectrometry-based proteomics turns quantitative | journal = Nature Chemical Biology | volume = 1 | issue = 5 | pages = 252\u201362 | date = October 2005 | pmid = 16408053 | doi = 10.1038/nchembio736 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid17668192\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Bantscheff M, Schirle M, Sweetman G, Rick J, Kuster B | title = Quantitative mass spectrometry in proteomics: a critical review | journal = Analytical and Bioanalytical Chemistry | volume = 389 | issue = 4 | pages = 1017\u201331 | date = October 2007 | pmid = 17668192 | doi = 10.1007/s00216-007-1486-6 | doi-access = free }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid=22665296\">{{cite book | vauthors = Nikolov M, Schmidt C, Urlaub H | title = Quantitative mass spectrometry-based proteomics: an overview | journal = <!--Bypass Citation bot --> | volume = 893 | issue =  | pages = 85\u2013100 | year = 2012 | pmid = 22665296 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-61779-885-6_7 | isbn = 978-1-61779-884-9 | series = Methods in Molecular Biology | hdl = 11858/00-001M-0000-000F-C327-D }}</ref> The methods for protein identification are identical to those used in general (i.e. qualitative) [[proteomics]], but include quantification as an additional dimension. Rather than just providing lists of proteins identified in a certain sample, quantitative proteomics yields information about the physiological differences between two biological samples. For example, this approach can be used to compare samples from healthy and diseased patients.  Quantitative proteomics is mainly performed by [[two-dimensional gel electrophoresis]] (2-DE) or mass spectrometry (MS).  However, a recent developed method of [[quantitative dot blot]] (QDB) analysis is able to measure both the absolute and relative quantity of an individual proteins in the sample in high throughput format, thus open a new direction for proteomic research. In contrast to 2-DE, which requires MS for the downstream protein identification, MS technology can identify and quantify the changes.\n\n== Quantification using spectrophotometry ==\nThe concentration of a certain protein in a sample may be determined using spectrophotometric procedures.<ref>Ninfa, Ballou, Benore. Fundamental Approaches to Biochemistry and Biotechnology, 2nd edition 2010. Fitzgerald Science Press, Bethesda, MD.</ref> The concentration of a protein can be determined by measuring the OD at 280&nbsp;nm on a spectrophotometer, which can be used with a standard curve assay to quantify the presence of Tryptophan, Tyrosine, and Phenylalanine.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Whitaker|first=John R.|last2=Granum|first2=Per Einar|title=An absolute method for protein determination based on difference in absorbance at 235 and 280 nm |journal=Analytical Biochemistry|volume=109|issue=1|pages=156\u2013159|doi=10.1016/0003-2697(80)90024-x|pmid=7469012|year=1980}}</ref> However, this method is not the most accurate because the composition of proteins can vary greatly and this method would not be able to quantify proteins that do not contain the aforementioned amino acids. This method is also inaccurate due to the possibility of nucleic acid contamination. Other more accurate spectrophotometric procedures for protein quantification include the [[Biuret test|Biuret]], [[Lowry protein assay|Lowry]], [[Bca assay|BCA]], and [[Bradford protein assay|Bradford]] methods.\n\n==Quantification using two dimensional electrophoresis ==\nTwo-dimensional gel electrophoresis (2-DE) represents one of the main technologies for quantitative proteomics with advantages and disadvantages. 2-DE provides information about the protein quantity, charge, and mass of the intact protein. It has limitations for the analysis of proteins larger than 150 kDa or smaller than 5kDa and low solubility proteins. Quantitative MS has higher sensitivity but does not provide information about the intact protein.\n\nClassical 2-DE based on post-electrophoretic dye staining has limitations: at least three technical replicates are required to verify the reproducibility.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}} [[Difference gel electrophoresis]] (DIGE) uses fluorescence-based labeling of the proteins prior to separation has increased the precision of quantification as well as the sensitivity in the protein detection.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}} Therefore, DIGE represents the current main approach for the 2-DE based study of proteomes.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n== Quantification using mass spectrometry ==\n[[File:Mass Spectrometry Quantitative Proteomic Workflows.png|thumb|437x437px|Examples of quantitative proteomic workflows. Red represents physiological sample of interest, while blue represents control sample. White boxes represent areas where errors are most likely to occur, and purple boxes represent where the samples have been mixed.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Engholm-Keller K, Larsen MR | title = Technologies and challenges in large-scale phosphoproteomics | journal = Proteomics | volume = 13 | issue = 6 | pages = 910\u201331 | date = March 2013 | pmid = 23404676 | doi = 10.1002/pmic.201200484 }}</ref>]]\nMass spectrometry (MS) represents one of the main technologies for quantitative proteomics with advantages and disadvantages. Quantitative MS has higher sensitivity but can provide only limited  information about the intact protein. Quantitative MS has been used for both discovery and targeted proteomic analysis to understand global proteomic dynamics in cells, tissues or organisms.\n\nFor quantitative MS, a commonly applied approach is [[isotope-coded affinity tag]]s (ICAT), which uses two reagents with heavy and light isotopes, respectively, and a biotin affinity tag to modify cysteine containing peptides. This technology has been used to label whole ''Saccharomyces cerevisiae'' cells,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Oda Y, Huang K, Cross FR, Cowburn D, Chait BT | title = Accurate quantitation of protein expression and site-specific phosphorylation | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 96 | issue = 12 | pages = 6591\u20136 | date = June 1999 | pmid = 10359756 | pmc = 21959 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.96.12.6591 | bibcode = 1999PNAS...96.6591O }}\n</ref> and, in conjunction with [[mass spectrometry]], helped lay the foundation of quantitative proteomics.\n\n===Relative and absolute quantification===\n\nMass spectrometry is not inherently quantitative because of differences in the ionization efficiency and/or detectability of the many peptides in a given sample, which has sparked the development of methods to determine relative and absolute abundance of proteins in samples.<ref name =\"pmid=22665296\"/> The intensity of a peak in a [[mass spectrum]] is not a good indicator of the amount of the analyte in the sample, although differences in peak intensity of the ''same'' analyte between multiple samples accurately reflect relative differences in its abundance.\n\n===Stable isotope labeling in mass spectrometry===\n====Stable isotope labels====\nAn approach for relative quantification that is more costly and time-consuming, though less sensitive to experimental bias than label-free quantification, entails labeling the samples with [[stable isotope]] labels that allow the mass spectrometer to distinguish between identical proteins in separate samples. One type of label, isotopic tags, consist of stable isotopes incorporated into protein crosslinkers that causes a known mass shift of the labeled protein or peptide in the mass spectrum. Differentially labeled samples are combined and analyzed together, and the differences in the peak intensities of the isotope pairs accurately reflect difference in the abundance of the corresponding proteins.\n\nAbsolute proteomic quantification using isotopic peptides entails spiking known concentrations of synthetic, heavy [[isotopologues]] of target peptides into an experimental sample and then performing LC-MS/MS. As with relative quantification using isotopic labels, peptides of equal chemistry co-elute and are analyzed by MS simultaneously. Unlike relative quantification, though, the abundance of the target peptide in the experimental sample is compared to that of the heavy peptide and back-calculated to the initial concentration of the standard using a pre-determined standard curve to yield the absolute quantification of the target peptide.\n\nRelative quantification methods include [[isotope-coded affinity tags]] (ICAT), [[isobaric labeling]] ([[tandem mass tags]] (TMT) and [[isobaric tags for relative and absolute quantification]] (iTRAQ)), [[label-free quantification]] metal-coded tags ([[MeCAT]]), [[N-terminal labelling]], stable isotope labeling with amino acids in cell culture ([[SILAC]]), and [[terminal amine isotopic labeling of substrates]] (TAILS). A mathematically rigorous approach that integrates peptide intensities and peptide-measurement agreement into confidence intervals for protein ratios has emerged.<ref name=\"Peshkin\">{{cite biorxiv | vauthors = Peshkin L, Ryazanova L, Wuhr M |title=Bayesian Confidence Intervals for Multiplexed Proteomics Integrate Ion-Statistics with Peptide Quantification Concordance..|date=2017|display-authors=etal|biorxiv=10.1101/210476}}</ref>\n\nAbsolute quantification is performed using [[selected reaction monitoring]] (SRM).\n\n====Metal-coded tags====\nMetal-coded tags (MeCAT) method is based on chemical labeling, but rather than using stable isotopes, different lanthanide ions in macrocyclic complexes are used. The quantitative information comes from inductively coupled plasma MS measurements of the labeled peptides. MeCAT can be used in combination with elemental mass spectrometry [[ICP-MS]] allowing first-time absolute quantification of the metal bound by MeCAT reagent to a protein or biomolecule. Thus it is possible to determine the absolute amount of protein down to attomol range using external calibration by metal standard solution. It is compatible to protein separation by 2D electrophoresis and chromatography in multiplex experiments. Protein identification and relative quantification can be performed by MALDI-MS/MS and ESI-MS/MS.\n\nMass spectrometers have a limited capacity to detect low-abundance peptides in samples with a high dynamic range. The limited duty cycle of mass spectrometers also restricts the collision rate, resulting in an undersampling<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Prakash A, Piening B, Whiteaker J, Zhang H, Shaffer SA, Martin D, Hohmann L, Cooke K, Olson JM, Hansen S, Flory MR, Lee H, Watts J, Goodlett DR, Aebersold R, Paulovich A, Schwikowski B | title = Assessing bias in experiment design for large scale mass spectrometry-based quantitative proteomics | journal = Molecular & Cellular Proteomics | volume = 6 | issue = 10 | pages = 1741\u20138 | date = October 2007 | pmid = 17617667 | doi = 10.1074/mcp.M600470-MCP200 | doi-access = free }}</ref> Sample preparation protocols represent sources of experimental bias.\n\n====Stable isotope labeling with amino acids in cell culture====\nStable isotope labeling with amino acids in cell culture ([[SILAC]]) is a method that involves metabolic incorporation of \u201cheavy\u201d C- or N-labeled amino acids into proteins followed by MS analysis. SILAC requires growing cells in specialized media supplemented with light or heavy forms of essential amino acids, lysine or arginine. One cell population is grown in media containing light amino acids while the experimental condition is grown in the presence of heavy amino acids. The heavy and light amino acids are incorporated into proteins through cellular protein synthesis. Following cell lysis, equal amounts of protein from both conditions are combined and subjected to proteotypic digestion. Arginine and lysine amino acids were chosen, because trypsin, the predominant enzyme used to generate proteotypic peptides for MS analysis, cleaves at the C-terminus of lysine and arginine. Following digestion with trypsin, all the tryptic peptides from cells grown in SILAC media would have at least one labeled amino acid, resulting in a constant mass shift from the labeled sample over non-labeled. Because the peptides containing heavy and light amino acids are chemically identical, they co-elute during reverse-phase column fractionation and are detected simultaneously during MS analysis. The relative protein abundance is determined by the relative peak intensities of the isotopically distinct peptides.\n\nTraditionally the level of multiplexing in SILAC was limited due to the number of SILAC isotopes available. Recently, a new technique called NeuCode SILAC,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Merrill AE, Hebert AS, MacGilvray ME, Rose CM, Bailey DJ, Bradley JC, Wood WW, El Masri M, Westphall MS, Gasch AP, Coon JJ | title = NeuCode labels for relative protein quantification | journal = Molecular & Cellular Proteomics | volume = 13 | issue = 9 | pages = 2503\u201312 | date = September 2014 | pmid = 24938287 | pmc = 4159665 | doi = 10.1074/mcp.M114.040287 }}</ref> has augmented the level of multiplexing achievable with metabolic labeling (up to 4). The NeuCode amino acid method is similar to SILAC but differs in that the labeling only utilizes heavy amino acids. The use of only heavy amino acids eliminates the need for 100% incorporation of amino acids needed for SILAC. The increased multiplexing capability of NeuCode amino acids is from the use of mass defects from extra neutrons in the stable isotopes. These small mass differences however need to be resolved on high resolution mass spectrometers.\n\nOne of the main benefits of SILAC is the level of quantitation bias from processing errors is low because heavy and light samples are combined before sample preparation for MS analysis. SILAC and NeuCode SILAC are excellent techniques for detecting small changes in protein levels or post-translational modifications between experimental groups.\n\n====Isobaric labeling====\nIsobaric mass tags (tandem mass tags) are tags that have identical mass and chemical properties that allow heavy and light isotopologues to co-elute together. All mass tags consist of a mass reporter that has a unique number of <sup>13</sup>C substitutions, a mass normalizer that has a unique mass that balances the mass of the tag to make all the tags equal in mass and a reactive moiety that crosslinks to the peptides. These tags are designed to cleave at a specific linker region upon high-energy CID, yielding different-sized tags that are then quantitated by LC-MS/MS. Protein or peptide samples prepared from cells, tissues or biological fluids are labeled in parallel with the isobaric mass tags and combined for analysis. Protein quantitation is accomplished by comparing the intensities of the reporter ions in the MS/MS spectra. Three types of tandem mass tags are available with different reactivity: (1) reactive NHS ester which provides high-efficiency, amine-specific labeling (TMTduplex, TMTsixplex, TMT10plex and TMT11plex), (2) reactive iodacetyl function group which labels sulfhydryl-(-SH) groups (iodoTMT) and (3) reactive alkoxyamine functional group which provides covalent labeling of carbonyl-containing compounds (aminoxyTMT).\n\nA key benefit of isobaric labeling over other quantification techniques (e.g. SILAC, ICAT, Label-free) is the increased multiplex capabilities and thus increased throughput potential. The ability to combine and analyze several samples simultaneously in one LC-MS run eliminates the need to analyze multiple data sets and eliminates run-to-run variation. Multiplexing reduces sample processing variability, improves specificity by quantifying the proteins from each condition simultaneously, and reduces turnaround time for multiple samples. The current available isobaric chemical tags facilitate the simultaneous analysis of up to 11 experimental samples.\n\n===Label-free quantification in mass spectrometry===\nOne approach for relative quantification is to separately analyze samples by MS and compare the spectra to determine peptide abundance in one sample relative to another, as in [[Label-free quantification|label-free]] strategies. It is generally accepted, that while label-free quantification is the least accurate of the quantification paradigms, it is also inexpensive and reliable when put under heavy statistical validation. There are two different methods of quantification in label-free quantitative proteomics: AUC (area under the curve) and spectral counting.\n\n====Methods of label-free quantification====\nAUC is a method by which for a given peptide spectrum in an LC-MS run, the area under the spectral peak is calculated. AUC peak measurements are linearly proportional to the concentration of protein in a given analyte mixture. Quantification is achieved with through ion counts, the measurement of the amount of an ion at a specific retention time.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Neilson KA, Ali NA, Muralidharan S, Mirzaei M, Mariani M, Assadourian G, Lee A, van Sluyter SC, Haynes PA | title = Less label, more free: approaches in label-free quantitative mass spectrometry | journal = Proteomics | volume = 11 | issue = 4 | pages = 535\u201353 | date = February 2011 | pmid = 21243637 | doi = 10.1002/pmic.201000553 }}</ref> Discretion is required for the standardization of the raw data.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = America AH, Cordewener JH | title = Comparative LC-MS: a landscape of peaks and valleys | journal = Proteomics | volume = 8 | issue = 4 | pages = 731\u201349 | date = February 2008 | pmid = 18297651 | doi = 10.1002/pmic.200700694 }}</ref> High-resolution spectrometer can alleviated problems that arise when trying to make data reproducible, however  much of the work regarding normalizing data can be done through software such as [[OpenMS]], and MassView.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Weixun|last2=Zhou|first2=Haihong|last3=Lin|first3=Hua|last4=Roy|first4=Sushmita|last5=Shaler|first5=Thomas A.|last6=Hill|first6=Lander R.|last7=Norton|first7=Scott|last8=Kumar|first8=Praveen|last9=Anderle|first9=Markus|date=2003-09-01|title=Quantification of Proteins and Metabolites by Mass Spectrometry without Isotopic Labeling or Spiked Standards|journal=Analytical Chemistry|volume=75|issue=18|pages=4818\u20134826|doi=10.1021/ac026468x|pmid=14674459|issn=0003-2700}}</ref>\n\nSpectral counting involves counting the spectra of an identified protein and then standardizing using some form of normalization.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lundgren DH, Hwang SI, Wu L, Han DK | title = Role of spectral counting in quantitative proteomics | journal = Expert Review of Proteomics | volume = 7 | issue = 1 | pages = 39\u201353 | date = February 2010 | pmid = 20121475 | doi = 10.1586/epr.09.69 }}</ref> Typically this is done with an abundant peptide mass selection (MS)  that is then fragmented and then MS/MS spectra are counted.<ref name=\":0\" /> Multiple samplings of the protein peak is required for accurate estimation of the protein abundance because of the complex physiochemical nature of peptides. Thus, optimization for MS/MS experiments is a constant concern. One alternative to get around this problems is use a data independent technique that cycles between high and low collision energies. Thus a large survey of all possible precursor and product ions is collected. This is limited, however, by the mass spectrometry software's ability to recognize and match peptide patterns of associations between the precursor and product ions.\n\n== Applications ==\n[[File:Journal.pone.0095194.g001.TIF|thumb|374x374px|Work flow of the Quantification of the physiological differences in \u03b1 and \u03b2 cells in mice using computer prediction (A) and SILAC isotope-label quantification(B). (C) is the candidate list of kinases that indicate physiological differences in \u03b1 and \u03b2 cells.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Choudhary A, Hu He K, Mertins P, Udeshi ND, Dan\u010d\u00edk V, Fomina-Yadlin D, Kubicek S, Clemons PA, Schreiber SL, Carr SA, Wagner BK | title = Quantitative-proteomic comparison of alpha and Beta cells to uncover novel targets for lineage reprogramming | journal = PLOS ONE | volume = 9 | issue = 4 | pages = e95194 | date = 2014-04-23 | pmid = 24759943 | pmc = 3997365 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0095194 | bibcode = 2014PLoSO...995194C }}</ref>]]\n\n=== Biomedical applications ===\nQuantitative proteomics has distinct applications in the medical field. Especially in the fields of drug and biomarker discovery. \nLC-MS/MS techniques have started to over take more traditional methods like the western blot and ELISA due to the cumbersome nature of labeling different and separating proteins using these methods and the more global analysis of protein quantification. Mass spectrometry methods are more sensitive to difference in protein structure like post-translational modification and thus can quantify differing modifications to proteins. Quantitative proteomics can circumvent these issues, only needing sequence information to be performed. Disadvantages, however, in sensitivity and analysis time must be kept in consideration.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Bantscheff M, Lemeer S, Savitski MM, Kuster B | title = Quantitative mass spectrometry in proteomics: critical review update from 2007 to the present | journal = Analytical and Bioanalytical Chemistry | volume = 404 | issue = 4 | pages = 939\u201365 | date = September 2012 | pmid = 22772140 | doi = 10.1007/s00216-012-6203-4 }}</ref>\n\n==== Drug discovery ====\nQuantitative proteomics has the largest applications in the protein target identification, protein target validation, and toxicity profiling of [[drug discovery]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ohtsuki S, Uchida Y, Kubo Y, Terasaki T | title = Quantitative targeted absolute proteomics-based ADME research as a new path to drug discovery and development: methodology, advantages, strategy, and prospects | journal = Journal of Pharmaceutical Sciences | volume = 100 | issue = 9 | pages = 3547\u201359 | date = September 2011 | pmid = 21560129 | doi = 10.1002/jps.22612 }}</ref> Drug discovery has been used to investigate protein-protein interaction and, more recently, drug-small molecule interactions. Thus, it has shown great promise in monitoring side-effects of small drug-like molecules and understanding the efficacy and therapeutic effect of one drug target over another.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Rix U, Superti-Furga G | title = Target profiling of small molecules by chemical proteomics | journal = Nature Chemical Biology | volume = 5 | issue = 9 | pages = 616\u201324 | date = September 2009 | pmid = 19690537 | doi = 10.1038/nchembio.216 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Schenone M, Dan\u010d\u00edk V, Wagner BK, Clemons PA | title = Target identification and mechanism of action in chemical biology and drug discovery | journal = Nature Chemical Biology | volume = 9 | issue = 4 | pages = 232\u201340 | date = April 2013 | pmid = 23508189 | pmc = 5543995 | doi = 10.1038/nchembio.1199 }}</ref> One of the more typical methodologies for absolute protein quantification in drug discovery is the use of LC-MS/MS with [[Selected reaction monitoring|multiple reaction monitoring]] (MRM). The mass spectrometry is typically done by a [[Triple quadrupole mass spectrometer|triple quadrupole MS]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Pierce Protein Assay]]\n*[[Protein mass spectrometry]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Quantitative proteomics}}\n\n[[Category:Mass spectrometry]]\n[[Category:Proteomics]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Quantitative mass spectrometry.svg|thumb|right|300 px|Quantitative mass spectrometry.]]\n'''Quantitative proteomics''' is an [[analytical chemistry]] technique for determining the amount of [[protein]]s in a sample.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ong SE, Mann M | title = Mass spectrometry-based proteomics turns quantitative | journal = Nature Chemical Biology | volume = 1 | issue = 5 | pages = 252\u201362 | date = October 2005 | pmid = 16408053 | doi = 10.1038/nchembio736 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid17668192\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Bantscheff M, Schirle M, Sweetman G, Rick J, Kuster B | title = Quantitative mass spectrometry in proteomics: a critical review | journal = Analytical and Bioanalytical Chemistry | volume = 389 | issue = 4 | pages = 1017\u201331 | date = October 2007 | pmid = 17668192 | doi = 10.1007/s00216-007-1486-6 | doi-access = free }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid=22665296\">{{cite book | vauthors = Nikolov M, Schmidt C, Urlaub H | title = Quantitative mass spectrometry-based proteomics: an overview | journal = <!--Bypass Citation bot --> | volume = 893 | issue =  | pages = 85\u2013100 | year = 2012 | pmid = 22665296 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-61779-885-6_7 | isbn = 978-1-61779-884-9 | series = Methods in Molecular Biology | hdl = 11858/00-001M-0000-000F-C327-D }}</ref> The methods for protein identification are identical to those used in general (i.e. qualitative) [[proteomics]], but include quantification as an additional dimension. Rather than just providing lists of proteins identified in a certain sample, quantitative proteomics yields information about the physiological differences between two biological samples. For example, this approach can be used to compare samples from healthy and diseased patients.  Quantitative proteomics is mainly performed by [[two-dimensional gel electrophoresis]] (2-DE) or mass spectrometry (MS).  However, a recent developed method of [[quantitative dot blot]] (QDB) analysis is able to measure both the absolute and relative quantity of an individual proteins in the sample in high throughput format, thus open a new direction for proteomic research. In contrast to 2-DE, which requires MS for the downstream protein identification, MS technology can identify and quantify the changes.\n\n== Quantification using spectrophotometry ==\nThe concentration of a certain protein in a sample may be determined using spectrophotometric procedures.<ref>Ninfa, Ballou, Benore. Fundamental Approaches to Biochemistry and Biotechnology, 2nd edition 2010. Fitzgerald Science Press, Bethesda, MD.</ref> The concentration of a protein can be determined by measuring the OD at 280&nbsp;nm on a spectrophotometer, which can be used with a standard curve assay to quantify the presence of Tryptophan, Tyrosine, and Phenylalanine.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Whitaker|first=John R.|last2=Granum|first2=Per Einar|title=An absolute method for protein determination based on difference in absorbance at 235 and 280 nm |journal=Analytical Biochemistry|volume=109|issue=1|pages=156\u2013159|doi=10.1016/0003-2697(80)90024-x|pmid=7469012|year=1980}}</ref> However, this method is not the most accurate because the composition of proteins can vary greatly and this method would not be able to quantify proteins that do not contain the aforementioned amino acids. This method is also inaccurate due to the possibility of nucleic acid contamination. Other more accurate spectrophotometric procedures for protein quantification include the [[Biuret test|Biuret]], [[Lowry protein assay|Lowry]], [[Bca assay|BCA]], and [[Bradford protein assay|Bradford]] methods.\n\n==Quantification using two dimensional electrophoresis ==\nTwo-dimensional gel electrophoresis (2-DE) represents one of the main technologies for quantitative proteomics with advantages and disadvantages. 2-DE provides information about the protein quantity, charge, and mass of the intact protein. It has limitations for the analysis of proteins larger than 150 kDa or smaller than 5kDa and low solubility proteins. Quantitative MS has higher sensitivity but does not provide information about the intact protein.\n\nClassical 2-DE based on post-electrophoretic dye staining has limitations: at least three technical replicates are required to verify the reproducibility.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}} [[Difference gel electrophoresis]] (DIGE) uses fluorescence-based labeling of the proteins prior to separation has increased the precision of quantification as well as the sensitivity in the protein detection.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}} Therefore, DIGE represents the current main approach for the 2-DE based study of proteomes.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n== Quantification using mass spectrometry ==\n[[File:Mass Spectrometry Quantitative Proteomic Workflows.png|thumb|437x437px|Examples of quantitative proteomic workflows. Red represents physiological sample of interest, while blue represents control sample. White boxes represent areas where errors are most likely to occur, and purple boxes represent where the samples have been mixed.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Engholm-Keller K, Larsen MR | title = Technologies and challenges in large-scale phosphoproteomics | journal = Proteomics | volume = 13 | issue = 6 | pages = 910\u201331 | date = March 2013 | pmid = 23404676 | doi = 10.1002/pmic.201200484 }}</ref>]]\nMass spectrometry (MS) represents one of the main technologies for quantitative proteomics with advantages and disadvantages. Quantitative MS has higher sensitivity but can provide only limited  information about the intact protein. Quantitative MS has been used for both discovery and targeted proteomic analysis to understand global proteomic dynamics in cells, tissues or organisms.\n\nFor quantitative MS, a commonly applied approach is [[isotope-coded affinity tag]]s (ICAT), which uses two reagents with heavy and light isotopes, respectively, and a biotin affinity tag to modify cysteine containing peptides. This technology has been used to label whole ''Saccharomyces cerevisiae'' cells,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Oda Y, Huang K, Cross FR, Cowburn D, Chait BT | title = Accurate quantitation of protein expression and site-specific phosphorylation | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 96 | issue = 12 | pages = 6591\u20136 | date = June 1999 | pmid = 10359756 | pmc = 21959 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.96.12.6591 | bibcode = 1999PNAS...96.6591O }}\n</ref> and, in conjunction with [[mass spectrometry]], helped lay the foundation of quantitative proteomics.\n\n===Relative and absolute quantification===\n\nMass spectrometry is not inherently quantitative because of differences in the ionization efficiency and/or detectability of the many peptides in a given sample, which has sparked the development of methods to determine relative and absolute abundance of proteins in samples.<ref name =\"pmid=22665296\"/> The intensity of a peak in a [[mass spectrum]] is not a good indicator of the amount of the analyte in the sample, although differences in peak intensity of the ''same'' analyte between multiple samples accurately reflect relative differences in its abundance.\n\n===Stable isotope labeling in mass spectrometry===\n====Stable isotope labels====\nAn approach for relative quantification that is more costly and time-consuming, though less sensitive to experimental bias than label-free quantification, entails labeling the samples with [[stable isotope]] labels that allow the mass spectrometer to distinguish between identical proteins in separate samples. One type of label, isotopic tags, consist of stable isotopes incorporated into protein crosslinkers that causes a known mass shift of the labeled protein or peptide in the mass spectrum. Differentially labeled samples are combined and analyzed together, and the differences in the peak intensities of the isotope pairs accurately reflect difference in the abundance of the corresponding proteins.\n\nAbsolute proteomic quantification using isotopic peptides entails spiking known concentrations of synthetic, heavy [[isotopologues]] of target peptides into an experimental sample and then performing LC-MS/MS. As with relative quantification using isotopic labels, peptides of equal chemistry co-elute and are analyzed by MS simultaneously. Unlike relative quantification, though, the abundance of the target peptide in the experimental sample is compared to that of the heavy peptide and back-calculated to the initial concentration of the standard using a pre-determined standard curve to yield the absolute quantification of the target peptide.\n\nRelative quantification methods include [[isotope-coded affinity tags]] (ICAT), [[isobaric labeling]] ([[tandem mass tags]] (TMT) and [[isobaric tags for relative and absolute quantification]] (iTRAQ)), [[label-free quantification]] metal-coded tags ([[MeCAT]]), [[N-terminal labelling]], stable isotope labeling with amino acids in cell culture ([[SILAC]]), and [[terminal amine isotopic labeling of substrates]] (TAILS). A mathematically rigorous approach that integrates peptide intensities and peptide-measurement agreement into confidence intervals for protein ratios has emerged.<ref name=\"Peshkin\">{{cite biorxiv | vauthors = Peshkin L, Ryazanova L, Wuhr M |title=Bayesian Confidence Intervals for Multiplexed Proteomics Integrate Ion-Statistics with Peptide Quantification Concordance..|date=2017|display-authors=etal|biorxiv=10.1101/210476}}</ref>\n\nAbsolute quantification is performed using [[selected reaction monitoring]] (SRM).\n\n====Metal-coded tags====\nMetal-coded tags (MeCAT) method is based on chemical labeling, but rather than using stable isotopes, different lanthanide ions in macrocyclic complexes are used. The quantitative information comes from inductively coupled plasma MS measurements of the labeled peptides. MeCAT can be used in combination with elemental mass spectrometry [[ICP-MS]] allowing first-time absolute quantification of the metal bound by MeCAT reagent to a protein or biomolecule. Thus it is possible to determine the absolute amount of protein down to attomol range using external calibration by metal standard solution. It is compatible to protein separation by 2D electrophoresis and chromatography in multiplex experiments. Protein identification and relative quantification can be performed by MALDI-MS/MS and ESI-MS/MS.\n\nMass spectrometers have a limited capacity to detect low-abundance peptides in samples with a high dynamic range. The limited duty cycle of mass spectrometers also restricts the collision rate, resulting in an undersampling<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Prakash A, Piening B, Whiteaker J, Zhang H, Shaffer SA, Martin D, Hohmann L, Cooke K, Olson JM, Hansen S, Flory MR, Lee H, Watts J, Goodlett DR, Aebersold R, Paulovich A, Schwikowski B | title = Assessing bias in experiment design for large scale mass spectrometry-based quantitative proteomics | journal = Molecular & Cellular Proteomics | volume = 6 | issue = 10 | pages = 1741\u20138 | date = October 2007 | pmid = 17617667 | doi = 10.1074/mcp.M600470-MCP200 | doi-access = free }}</ref> Sample preparation protocols represent sources of experimental bias.\n\n====Stable isotope labeling with amino acids in cell culture====\nStable isotope labeling with amino acids in cell culture ([[SILAC]]) is a method that involves metabolic incorporation of \u201cheavy\u201d C- or N-labeled amino acids into proteins followed by MS analysis. SILAC requires growing cells in specialized media supplemented with light or heavy forms of essential amino acids, lysine or arginine. One cell population is grown in media containing light amino acids while the experimental condition is grown in the presence of heavy amino acids. The heavy and light amino acids are incorporated into proteins through cellular protein synthesis. Following cell lysis, equal amounts of protein from both conditions are combined and subjected to proteotypic digestion. Arginine and lysine amino acids were chosen, because trypsin, the predominant enzyme used to generate proteotypic peptides for MS analysis, cleaves at the C-terminus of lysine and arginine. Following digestion with trypsin, all the tryptic peptides from cells grown in SILAC media would have at least one labeled amino acid, resulting in a constant mass shift from the labeled sample over non-labeled. Because the peptides containing heavy and light amino acids are chemically identical, they co-elute during reverse-phase column fractionation and are detected simultaneously during MS analysis. The relative protein abundance is determined by the relative peak intensities of the isotopically distinct peptides.\n\nTraditionally the level of multiplexing in SILAC was limited due to the number of SILAC isotopes available. Recently, a new technique called NeuCode SILAC,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Merrill AE, Hebert AS, MacGilvray ME, Rose CM, Bailey DJ, Bradley JC, Wood WW, El Masri M, Westphall MS, Gasch AP, Coon JJ | title = NeuCode labels for relative protein quantification | journal = Molecular & Cellular Proteomics | volume = 13 | issue = 9 | pages = 2503\u201312 | date = September 2014 | pmid = 24938287 | pmc = 4159665 | doi = 10.1074/mcp.M114.040287 }}</ref> has augmented the level of multiplexing achievable with metabolic labeling (up to 4). The NeuCode amino acid method is similar to SILAC but differs in that the labeling only utilizes heavy amino acids. The use of only heavy amino acids eliminates the need for 100% incorporation of amino acids needed for SILAC. The increased multiplexing capability of NeuCode amino acids is from the use of mass defects from extra neutrons in the stable isotopes. These small mass differences however need to be resolved on high resolution mass spectrometers.\n\nOne of the main benefits of SILAC is the level of quantitation bias from processing errors is low because heavy and light samples are combined before sample preparation for MS analysis. SILAC and NeuCode SILAC are excellent techniques for detecting small changes in protein levels or post-translational modifications between experimental groups.\n\n====Isobaric labeling====\nIsobaric mass tags (tandem mass tags) are tags that have identical mass and chemical properties that allow heavy and light isotopologues to co-elute together. All mass tags consist of a mass reporter that has a unique number of <sup>13</sup>C substitutions, a mass normalizer that has a unique mass that balances the mass of the tag to make all the tags equal in mass and a reactive moiety that crosslinks to the peptides. These tags are designed to cleave at a specific linker region upon high-energy CID, yielding different-sized tags that are then quantitated by LC-MS/MS. Protein or peptide samples prepared from cells, tissues or biological fluids are labeled in parallel with the isobaric mass tags and combined for analysis. Protein quantitation is accomplished by comparing the intensities of the reporter ions in the MS/MS spectra. Three types of tandem mass tags are available with different reactivity: (1) reactive NHS ester which provides high-efficiency, amine-specific labeling (TMTduplex, TMTsixplex, TMT10plex and TMT11plex), (2) reactive iodacetyl function group which labels sulfhydryl-(-SH) groups (iodoTMT) and (3) reactive alkoxyamine functional group which provides covalent labeling of carbonyl-containing compounds (aminoxyTMT).\n\nA key benefit of isobaric labeling over other quantification techniques (e.g. SILAC, ICAT, Label-free) is the increased multiplex capabilities and thus increased throughput potential. The ability to combine and analyze several samples simultaneously in one LC-MS run eliminates the need to analyze multiple data sets and eliminates run-to-run variation. Multiplexing reduces sample processing variability, improves specificity by quantifying the proteins from each condition simultaneously, and reduces turnaround time for multiple samples. The current available isobaric chemical tags facilitate the simultaneous analysis of up to 11 experimental samples.\n\n===Label-free quantification in mass spectrometry===\nOne approach for relative quantification is to separately analyze samples by MS and compare the spectra to determine peptide abundance in one sample relative to another, as in [[Label-free quantification|label-free]] strategies. It is generally accepted, that while label-free quantification is the least accurate of the quantification paradigms, it is also inexpensive and reliable when put under heavy statistical validation. There are two different methods of quantification in label-free quantitative proteomics: AUC (area under the curve) and spectral counting.\n\n====Methods of label-free quantification====\nAUC is a method by which for a given peptide spectrum in an LC-MS run, the area under the spectral peak is calculated. AUC peak measurements are linearly proportional to the concentration of protein in a given analyte mixture. Quantification is achieved with through ion counts, the measurement of the amount of an ion at a specific retention time.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Neilson KA, Ali NA, Muralidharan S, Mirzaei M, Mariani M, Assadourian G, Lee A, van Sluyter SC, Haynes PA | title = Less label, more free: approaches in label-free quantitative mass spectrometry | journal = Proteomics | volume = 11 | issue = 4 | pages = 535\u201353 | date = February 2011 | pmid = 21243637 | doi = 10.1002/pmic.201000553 }}</ref> Discretion is required for the standardization of the raw data.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = America AH, Cordewener JH | title = Comparative LC-MS: a landscape of peaks and valleys | journal = Proteomics | volume = 8 | issue = 4 | pages = 731\u201349 | date = February 2008 | pmid = 18297651 | doi = 10.1002/pmic.200700694 }}</ref> High-resolution spectrometer can alleviated problems that arise when trying to make data reproducible, however  much of the work regarding normalizing data can be done through software such as [[OpenMS]], and MassView.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Weixun|last2=Zhou|first2=Haihong|last3=Lin|first3=Hua|last4=Roy|first4=Sushmita|last5=Shaler|first5=Thomas A.|last6=Hill|first6=Lander R.|last7=Norton|first7=Scott|last8=Kumar|first8=Praveen|last9=Anderle|first9=Markus|date=2003-09-01|title=Quantification of Proteins and Metabolites by Mass Spectrometry without Isotopic Labeling or Spiked Standards|journal=Analytical Chemistry|volume=75|issue=18|pages=4818\u20134826|doi=10.1021/ac026468x|pmid=14674459|issn=0003-2700}}</ref>\n\nSpectral counting involves counting the spectra of an identified protein and then standardizing using some form of normalization.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lundgren DH, Hwang SI, Wu L, Han DK | title = Role of spectral counting in quantitative proteomics | journal = Expert Review of Proteomics | volume = 7 | issue = 1 | pages = 39\u201353 | date = February 2010 | pmid = 20121475 | doi = 10.1586/epr.09.69 }}</ref> Typically this is done with an abundant peptide mass selection (MS)  that is then fragmented and then MS/MS spectra are counted.<ref name=\":0\" /> Multiple samplings of the protein peak is required for accurate estimation of the protein abundance because of the complex physiochemical nature of peptides. Thus, optimization for MS/MS experiments is a constant concern. One alternative to get around this problems is use a data independent technique that cycles between high and low collision energies. Thus a large survey of all possible precursor and product ions is collected. This is limited, however, by the mass spectrometry software's ability to recognize and match peptide patterns of associations between the precursor and product ions.\n\n== Applications ==\n[[File:Journal.pone.0095194.g001.TIF|thumb|374x374px|Work flow of the Quantification of the physiological differences in \u03b1 and \u03b2 cells in mice using computer prediction (A) and SILAC isotope-label quantification(B). (C) is the candidate list of kinases that indicate physiological differences in \u03b1 and \u03b2 cells.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Choudhary A, Hu He K, Mertins P, Udeshi ND, Dan\u010d\u00edk V, Fomina-Yadlin D, Kubicek S, Clemons PA, Schreiber SL, Carr SA, Wagner BK | title = Quantitative-proteomic comparison of alpha and Beta cells to uncover novel targets for lineage reprogramming | journal = PLOS ONE | volume = 9 | issue = 4 | pages = e95194 | date = 2014-04-23 | pmid = 24759943 | pmc = 3997365 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0095194 | bibcode = 2014PLoSO...995194C }}</ref>]]\n\n=== Biomedical applications ===\nQuantitative proteomics has distinct applications in the medical field. Especially in the fields of drug and biomarker discovery. \nLC-MS/MS techniques have started to over take more traditional methods like the western blot and ELISA due to the cumbersome nature of labeling different and separating proteins using these methods and the more global analysis of protein quantification. Mass spectrometry methods are more sensitive to difference in protein structure like post-translational modification and thus can quantify differing modifications to proteins. Quantitative proteomics can circumvent these issues, only needing sequence information to be performed. Disadvantages, however, in sensitivity and analysis time must be kept in consideration.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Bantscheff M, Lemeer S, Savitski MM, Kuster B | title = Quantitative mass spectrometry in proteomics: critical review update from 2007 to the present | journal = Analytical and Bioanalytical Chemistry | volume = 404 | issue = 4 | pages = 939\u201365 | date = September 2012 | pmid = 22772140 | doi = 10.1007/s00216-012-6203-4 }}</ref>\n\n==== Drug discovery ====\nQuantitative proteomics has the largest applications in the protein target identification, protein target validation, and toxicity profiling of [[drug discovery]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ohtsuki S, Uchida Y, Kubo Y, Terasaki T | title = Quantitative targeted absolute proteomics-based ADME research as a new path to drug discovery and development: methodology, advantages, strategy, and prospects | journal = Journal of Pharmaceutical Sciences | volume = 100 | issue = 9 | pages = 3547\u201359 | date = September 2011 | pmid = 21560129 | doi = 10.1002/jps.22612 }}</ref> Drug discovery has been used to investigate protein-protein interaction and, more recently, drug-small molecule interactions. Thus, it has shown great promise in monitoring side-effects of small drug-like molecules and understanding the efficacy and therapeutic effect of one drug target over another.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Rix U, Superti-Furga G | title = Target profiling of small molecules by chemical proteomics | journal = Nature Chemical Biology | volume = 5 | issue = 9 | pages = 616\u201324 | date = September 2009 | pmid = 19690537 | doi = 10.1038/nchembio.216 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Schenone M, Dan\u010d\u00edk V, Wagner BK, Clemons PA | title = Target identification and mechanism of action in chemical biology and drug discovery | journal = Nature Chemical Biology | volume = 9 | issue = 4 | pages = 232\u201340 | date = April 2013 | pmid = 23508189 | pmc = 5543995 | doi = 10.1038/nchembio.1199 }}</ref> One of the more typical methodologies for absolute protein quantification in drug discovery is the use of LC-MS/MS with [[Selected reaction monitoring|multiple reaction monitoring]] (MRM). The mass spectrometry is typically done by a [[Triple quadrupole mass spectrometer|triple quadrupole MS]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Pierce Protein Assay]]\n*[[Protein mass spectrometry]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Quantitative proteomics}}\n\n[[Category:Mass spectrometry]]\n[[Category:Proteomics]]\n", "name_user": "Nwokejiezi Chinweotito", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantitative_proteomics"}
{"title_page": "Laurice Milton \u201cRed\u201d Shea", "text_new": "{{short description|Folk guitarist (b. 1938, d. June 10, 2008)}}\n[[Laurice Milton \u201cRed\u201d Shea|Red Shea]] (formerly Laurice Milton Pouliot) was a renowned Canadian folk guitarist. Over his career, he helped define the sounds of artists such as [[Gordon Lightfoot]] and [[Ian Tyson|Ian]] and [[Sylvia Tyson]], and was a regular on the TV show of Canadian Country music singer [[Tommy Hunter]].\n\n== Career ==\nShea was a self-taught musician.<ref>Quill, Greg. \u201c'Red' Shea, 70: Influential Folk Guitarist.\u201d Thestar.com, Toronto Star, 12 June 2008, www.thestar.com/entertainment/2008/06/12/red_shea_70_influential_folk_guitarist.html.</ref> In Saskatchewan in the late 1950s, Shea formed the Red and Les Trio with his brother Les and bassist Bill Gibbs, making appearances on Country Hoedown, a CBC Musical variety show. Later, Shea played backup guitar with the Bluegrass band [[the Good Brothers]], who were from Richmond Hill, Ontario.<ref>\u201cCanadian Guitarist 'Red' Shea Dies | CBC News.\u201d CBCnews, CBC/Radio Canada, 12 June 2008, www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/canadian-guitarist-red-shea-dies-1.759795.</ref>\n\nOn the folk circuit, Shea befriended [[Gordon Lightfoot]], for whom he played lead guitar between 1965 and 1975. Shea was a \u201cpivotal figure\u201d in Lightfoot\u2019s early career, according to music journalist Jerry LeBlanc. His guitar solo in a live performance recording of Canadian Railroad Trilogy at [[Massey Hall]] in 1969 is particularly notable.<ref>Martin, Sandra. \u201cRed Shea, 70.\u201d The Globe and Mail, The Globe and Mail, 1 Dec. 2016, www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/red-shea-70/article25579859/.</ref>\n\nShea appears on several of Lightfoot\u2019s records, including The Way I Feel, Did She Mention My Name, Sit Down Young Stranger, Summer Side of Life, Sundown, Cold on the Shoulder and Gord\u2019s Gold.\n\nShea later joined the Ian and Sylvia Tyson\u2019s band [[Great Speckled Bird (band)|The Great Speckled Bird]], becoming musical director of the Ian Tyson Show in the 1970s. In the 1980s, Shea became band leader on [[the Tommy Hunter show]], which ran until 1992.\n\n== Influences ==\nFolk-rock artists such as [[Dan Fogelberg]] and [[Randy Bachman]] have cited Shea as a major influence, with Bachman remarking that \u201cRed Shea was the ultimate extra guitar on Gordon Lightfoot\u2019s records and stage performances. He augmented every song with some sparkle and magic and made Gordon sound and look good.\u201d<ref>Martin, Sandra. \u201cRed Shea, 70.\u201d The Globe and Mail, The Globe and Mail, 1 Dec. 2016, www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/red-shea-70/article25579859/.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shea, Laurice}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian folk guitarists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Folk guitarist (b. 1938, d. June 10, 2008)}}\nRed Shea (formerly Laurice Milton Pouliot) was a renowned Canadian folk guitarist. Over his career, he helped define the sounds of artists such as [[Gordon Lightfoot]] and [[Ian Tyson|Ian]] and [[Sylvia Tyson]], and was a regular on the TV show of Canadian Country music singer [[Tommy Hunter]].\n\n== Career ==\nShea was a self-taught musician.<ref>Quill, Greg. \u201c'Red' Shea, 70: Influential Folk Guitarist.\u201d Thestar.com, Toronto Star, 12 June 2008, www.thestar.com/entertainment/2008/06/12/red_shea_70_influential_folk_guitarist.html.</ref> In Saskatchewan in the late 1950s, Shea formed the Red and Les Trio with his brother Les and bassist Bill Gibbs, making appearances on Country Hoedown, a CBC Musical variety show. Later, Shea played backup guitar with the Bluegrass band [[the Good Brothers]], who were from Richmond Hill, Ontario.<ref>\u201cCanadian Guitarist 'Red' Shea Dies | CBC News.\u201d CBCnews, CBC/Radio Canada, 12 June 2008, www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/canadian-guitarist-red-shea-dies-1.759795.</ref>\n\nOn the folk circuit, Shea befriended [[Gordon Lightfoot]], for whom he played lead guitar between 1965 and 1975. Shea was a \u201cpivotal figure\u201d in Lightfoot\u2019s early career, according to music journalist Jerry LeBlanc. His guitar solo in a live performance recording of Canadian Railroad Trilogy at [[Massey Hall]] in 1969 is particularly notable.<ref>Martin, Sandra. \u201cRed Shea, 70.\u201d The Globe and Mail, The Globe and Mail, 1 Dec. 2016, www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/red-shea-70/article25579859/.</ref>\n\nShea appears on several of Lightfoot\u2019s records, including The Way I Feel, Did She Mention My Name, Sit Down Young Stranger, Summer Side of Life, Sundown, Cold on the Shoulder and Gord\u2019s Gold.\n\nShea later joined the Ian and Sylvia Tyson\u2019s band [[Great Speckled Bird (band)|The Great Speckled Bird]], becoming musical director of the Ian Tyson Show in the 1970s. In the 1980s, Shea became band leader on [[the Tommy Hunter show]], which ran until 1992.\n\n== Influences ==\nFolk-rock artists such as [[Dan Fogelberg]] and [[Randy Bachman]] have cited Shea as a major influence, with Bachman remarking that \u201cRed Shea was the ultimate extra guitar on Gordon Lightfoot\u2019s records and stage performances. He augmented every song with some sparkle and magic and made Gordon sound and look good.\u201d<ref>Martin, Sandra. \u201cRed Shea, 70.\u201d The Globe and Mail, The Globe and Mail, 1 Dec. 2016, www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/red-shea-70/article25579859/.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shea, Laurice}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian folk guitarists]]\n", "name_user": "Bgk135", "label": "safe", "comment": "Provided link to Red Shea direct page.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laurice_Milton_%E2%80%9CRed%E2%80%9D_Shea"}
{"title_page": "2020s in political history", "text_new": "{{see also|2010s in political history}}\n{{Decadebox|202}}\n{{Year nav topic5|2020|politics and government|science}}\n'''2020s political history''' refers to significant political and societal historical events of the 2020s, presented as a historical overview in narrative format.\n\n\n{{toc limit|3}}\n\n==World events==\n{{hatnote|Section for historical events of world significance. This section can be divided by time period; within each time period, there can be subsections for some topics. Even the most global issues involve events in various specific countries; therefore, for any lengthy world topics that encompass multiple countries and regions, a sub-section for that specific topic might be advisable; however, this is not required for every topic covered here.}}\n===General world events===\n{{empty section|date=March 2020}}\n\n\n===Coronavirus===\n{{main|Coronavirus disease 2019}}\n{{see also|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe}}\n\nIn early 2020, the spread of the [[coronavirus]] became an issue of global concern. The virus appeared to originate in [[Wuhan, China]]. \n\nIn Japan, all schools and colleges were closed in early March and were not to reopen again until April. New cases began to appear in Italy and elsewhere in Europe. In the United States, the first cases were reported in California and Oregon; some individuals in New York were isolated for evaluation.Several cruise ships were quarantined for weeks on end, due to concerns about the coronavirus spreading there.\n\nIn the last week of February 2020, the [[Dow Jones Index]]{{dn|date=April 2020}} experienced some of the biggest one-day drops in its history.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[Hand washing]], maintaining distance from people who are [[coughing]] and not touching one's face with unwashed hands are measures recommended to prevent the disease.<ref name=\"Advice for public\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public|title=Advice for public|website=www.who.int|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126025750/https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public|archive-date=26 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It is recommended to cover one's nose and mouth with a tissue or a bent elbow when coughing.<ref name=\"Advice for public\" /> The [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) and U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) recommend those who suspect that they are carrying the virus wear a [[Surgical mask|surgical face mask]] and seek medical advice by calling a doctor rather than directly visiting a clinic in person. Masks are also recommended for those who are taking care of someone with a suspected infection but not for the general public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/steps-when-sick.html|title=2019 Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV)|last=CDC|date=2020-02-11|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214153016/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/steps-when-sick.html|archive-date=14 February 2020|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public|title=Advice for public|website=www.who.int|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126025750/https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public|archive-date=26 January 2020|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> There is no [[vaccine]] or specific [[antiviral treatment]], with management involving treatment of symptoms, [[supportive care]], and experimental measures.<ref name=\"cdc21Jan20202\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/prevention-treatment.html|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)|date=15 February 2020|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC)|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226145347/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/prevention-treatment.html|archive-date=26 February 2020|access-date=20 February 2020}}</ref> The [[case fatality rate]] is estimated at between 1% and 3%.<ref name=\"worldometers.info\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/coronavirus-death-rate/#ref-6|title=Wuhan Coronavirus Death Rate - Worldometer|website=www.worldometers.info|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131223143/https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/coronavirus-death-rate/#ref-6|archive-date=31 January 2020|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-2019-nCoV-severity-10-02-2020.pdf|title=Report 4: Severity of 2019-novel coronavirus (nCoV)|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210105717/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-2019-nCoV-severity-10-02-2020.pdf|archive-date=10 February 2020|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Epidemiology and history -->\nThe WHO has declared the 2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak to be a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]] (PHEIC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|title=Statement on the second meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV)|website=www.who.int|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131005904/https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | vauthors = Mahtani S, Berger M, O'Grady S, Iati M | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/coronavirus-china-live-updates/2020/02/05/114ced8a-479c-11ea-bc78-8a18f7afcee7_story.html | title = Hundreds of evacuees to be held on bases in California; Hong Kong and Taiwan restrict travel from mainland China | work = The Washington Post | date = 6 February 2020 | access-date = 11 February 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200207134650/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/coronavirus-china-live-updates/2020/02/05/114ced8a-479c-11ea-bc78-8a18f7afcee7_story.html | archive-date = 7 February 2020 | url-status = live }}</ref> As of 29 February 2020, [[China]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Iran]], [[Italy]], [[Japan]], [[Singapore]], [[South Korea]] and the [[United States]] are areas having evidence of [[community transmission]] of the disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/areas-presumed-ongoing-community-transmission-2019-ncov|title=Areas with presumed ongoing community transmission of 2019-nCoV|website=European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control |access-date=2020-02-28|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200219092151/https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/areas-presumed-ongoing-community-transmission-2019-ncov |archive-date=28 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"cnn2-29\">{{cite news |author1=Christina Maxouris |author2=Dakin Andone |title=First death from coronavirus in the United States confirmed in Washington state, officials say |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/29/health/us-coronavirus-saturday/index.html |accessdate=29 February 2020 |work=CNN - Health |date=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Italy announced that is closing ''all'' schools and colleges due to coronavirus. <ref> [https://www.bbc.com/news/live/world-51734185 Italy confirms earlier reports it is closing schools and universities until mid-March], BBC, March 4,2020. </ref> The total cases worldwide were announced to have risen to 93,000. Saudi Arabia announced it would suspend the traditional umrah pilgrimage. <ref> [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-03/u-s-death-toll-rises-to-9-more-travel-curbs-seen-virus-update N.Y. Patient\u2019s Family, Driver Infected; U.K. Surge: Virus Update], Bloomberg News, March 3, 2020, Updated on March 4, 2020. </ref> France closed 120 schools due to the coronavirus. <ref>  [https://www.marketwatch.com/story/france-germany-close-schools-in-virus-cluster-zones-2020-03-03 France closes 120 schools because of the coronavirus, sending home tens of thousands of students] Mar 3, 2020, France\u2019s education minister closed schools mostly in Brittany and the Oise region north of Paris, which have been hit hard by COVID-19. marketwatch.com. </ref> France reported that it had 257 cases of the illness. <ref> [https://www.thelocal.fr/20200301/latest-number-of-coronavirus-cases-in-france-rises-to-130 LATEST: France confirms new total of 257 coronavirus cases and new cluster zones] The Local, 1 March 2020. </ref> Cases increased across Europe. <ref> [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/01/coronavirus-deaths-iran-rise-global-outbreak-worsens New coronavirus cases jump sharply in Europe, with Italy worst hit] Italian death toll now 34, German cases nearly double, and South Korea and Iran also struggle to contain outbreak. by Peter Beaumont in London, Lily Kuo in Beijing, Kim Willsher in Paris and Angela Giuffrida in Rome, March 1, 2020, The Guardian. </ref> Tourist attractions were closed throughout Asian countries. <ref> [https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/02/news/coronavirus-closures-tourist-attractions-and-events/index.html Attractions closed and events canceled amid coronavirus outbreak], by Stacey Lastoe, CNN Updated 9:20 AM ET, Wed March 4, 2020. </ref> Israel and some other countries canceled some foreign flights from some countries. <ref> [https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/03/04/coronavirus-live-updates/ Live updates: Four new coronavirus cases in New York as U.S. braces for more disruption], Washington Post. </ref> Iran reported a rise in cases. <ref> [https://www.france24.com/en/20200303-iran-to-mobilise-army-against-coronavirus-as-death-toll-reaches-77 Iran to mobilise army against coronavirus as death toll tops 75], March 3, 2020. </ref> \n\nIn the United States, the CDC announced that the outbreak had spread, and reported 129 cases. The CDC warned local communities to look at methods to halt the spread. <ref> [https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/04/health/us-coronavirus-update-wednesday/index.html The US coronavirus death toll is rising and the CDC says communities should start thinking about ways to stop its spread.] By Christina Maxouris, CNN Updated 11:04 AM ET, Wed March 4, 2020. </ref>An [https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/us/coronavirus-us-cases.html interactive online map at the New York Times website] showed the rising numbers state by state. <ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/us/coronavirus-us-cases.html Interactive map], NY Times website. </ref> Experts said the outbreak might be potentially as bad as the outbreak of flu in 1957. <ref> [https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/how-bad-will-the-coronavirus-outbreak-get-in-the-us/ar-BB10HcuL How bad will the coronavirus outbreak get in the U.S.?], Joel Achenbach, Lenny Bernstein, Neena Satija, William Wan Washington Post via msn.com, March 4,2020. </ref> <ref> [https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2020/03/02/how-is-coronavirus-outbreak-going-end-heres-how-similar-epidemics-played-out/ How is the coronavirus outbreak going to end? Here\u2019s how similar epidemics played out.], by William Wan, Washington post, March 2, 2020. </ref>New cases were reported in California and Washington State. <ref> [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/04/world/coronavirus-news.html Coronavirus Live Updates], NY Times website. </ref>\n\n===Financial market problems===\n[[Black Monday (2020)|Black Monday]] was a global [[stock market crash]] on 9 March 2020 that occurred during the [[2020 stock market crash]].<ref name=S>Prynn, Jonathan, English, Simon, and Murphy, Joe.[https://standard.co.uk/news/politics/stock-markets-ftse-100-oil-prices-coronavirus-black-monday-a4382156.html \"Black Monday: Fourth biggest City fall as coronavirus panic hits markets\"], ''[[Evening Standard]]'', 9 March 2020. Retrieved 9 March 2020.</ref> Markets opened several percent lower, having fallen greatly during the preceding two weeks. Global stock markets suffered from the greatest single-day fall since 2008, during the [[Great Recession]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/09/global-stock-markets-post-biggest-falls-since-2008-financial-crisis|title=\nGlobal stock markets post biggest falls since 2008 financial crisis|date=9 March 2020|accessdate=10 March 2020|website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> This record crash was soon surpassed three days later on [[Black Thursday (2020)|Black Thursday]]. Notable contributing factors included the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]] and the [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war|Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war]].<ref name=S/><ref name=bbc>{{cite news |title=Black Monday: Shares face biggest fall since financial crisis |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-51796806 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |agency=BBC News |date=9 March 2020 |quote=Analysts described the market reaction as \"utter carnage\". |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309055650/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-51796806 |archive-date=9 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=cnbc>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/08/dow-futures-drop-700-points-as-all-out-oil-price-war-adds-to-coronavirus-stress.html|title=Dow sinks 2,000 points in worst day since 2008, S&P 500 drops more than 7%|last=Li|first=Yun|date=8 March 2020|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=10 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309155615/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/08/dow-futures-drop-700-points-as-all-out-oil-price-war-adds-to-coronavirus-stress.html|archive-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn the United States, a [[Trading curb|circuit breaker]] was triggered after stocks dropped sharply, halting trade for fifteen minutes.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-51796806|title=Global shares plunge in worst day since financial crisis|date=9 March 2020|accessdate=10 March 2020|website=[[BBC]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309150404/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-51796806|archive-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[FTSE 100 Index]] opened 560 points (8.6%) lower to 5920.<ref name=S/> Indices in Asia, continental Europe, and the United States also fell by several percent on the same day, with the worst affected, Italy's FTSE MIB, opening 11% lower.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/ftse-100-monday-latest-coronavirus-oil-price-markets-open-081657287.html|title=Oil and coronavirus fears spark 'Black Monday' for stock markets|website=finance.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=10 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309094632/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/ftse-100-monday-latest-coronavirus-oil-price-markets-open-081657287.html|archive-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Other financial market effects included a rush to the safety of [[government bond]]s as 10-year American Treasury yields fell below 0.5% for the first time ever, appreciation of the [[Japanese yen]], and [[Gold as an investment|gold]] rising above $1,700/ounce for the first time in seven years.<ref name=TheEconomist1>{{cite news|author= |title= Saudi-Russian price war sends oil and stockmarkets crashing|url= https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2020/03/09/saudi-russian-price-war-sends-oil-and-stockmarkets-crashing|work= [[The Economist]]|date= 9 March 2020|access-date= 9 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200309155422/https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2020/03/09/saudi-russian-price-war-sends-oil-and-stockmarkets-crashing|archive-date= 9 March 2020|url-status= live}}</ref> \n\nBlack Thursday <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/black-thursday-dow-suffers-biggest-201047970.html|title=Black Thursday: Dow Suffers Biggest Point Drop Ever, as Disney and Apple Fall Hard|website=[[Yahoo]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://business.inquirer.net/292328/psei-sees-worst-freefall-in-12-years|title=Black Thursday: PSEi sees worst freefall in 12 years|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|website=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|author=Doris Dumlao-Abadilla}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/business/2020/mar/12/pandemic-pandemonium-world-markets-crash-into-bear-country-on-black-thursday-2115906.html|title=Pandemic pandemonium: World markets crash into bear country on Black Thursday|website=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|author=Jonathan Ananda}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icis.com/explore/resources/news/2020/03/12/10481846/europe-crude-petchems-prices-extend-losses-as-stocks-suffer-black-thursday|title=Europe crude, petchems prices extend losses as stocks suffer 'Black Thursday'|author=Jonathan Lopez|website=Independent Commodity Intelligence Services|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> was a global [[stock market crash]] on March 12, 2020 as part of the greater [[2020 stock market crash]]. Global stock markets suffered from the greatest single-day fall since the [[Black Monday (1987)|1987 stock market crash]].<ref name=\"CNBC\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/11/futures-are-steady-wednesday-night-after-dow-closes-in-bear-market-traders-await-trump.html|title=Dow drops more than 8%, heads for biggest one-day plunge since 1987 market crash|website=[[CNBC]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|author1=Fred Imbert|author2=Thomas Franck}}</ref> Following [[Black Monday (2020)|Black Monday]] three days earlier, Black Thursday was attributed to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]] and a lack of investor confidence in US president [[Donald Trump]] after he imposed a 30-day [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|travel ban]] against the [[Schengen Area]].<ref name=\"NYT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/12/business/stock-market-today.html|title=Stocks Plunge as Trump\u2019s Travel Ban Adds to Distress: Live Updates|website=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History by region==\n\n===Asia===\n====Afghanistan====\nThe [[Afghan peace process]] comprises the proposals and negotiations in a bid to end the ongoing [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|war in Afghanistan]]. Although sporadic efforts have taken place since the war began in 2001, negotiations and the peace movement intensified in 2018 amid talks between the [[Taliban]], which is the main [[insurgent]] group fighting against the [[Afghan government]] and [[American troops]]; and the [[United States]], of which 20,000 soldiers maintain a presence within the country to support the Afghan government. Most of the talks have taken place in [[Doha]], the capital of [[Qatar]]. It is expected that a mutual agreement between the Taliban and the United States would be followed by a phased American withdrawal and the start of intra-Afghan peace talks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pajhwok.com/en/2019/01/24/hpc-welcomes-khalilzad%E2%80%99s-efforts-intra-afghan-talks|title=HPC welcomes Khalilzad's efforts for intra-Afghan talks|website=pajhwok.com}}</ref> Besides the United States, regional powers such as [[Pakistan]], [[China]] and [[Russia]], as well as [[NATO]] play a part in facilitating the peace process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/world/us-russia-china-pakistan-urge-taliban-to-agree-for-ceasefire-begin-talks-with-afghan-govt/article28423292.ece|title=US, Russia, China, Pakistan urge Taliban to agree for ceasefire, begin talks with Afghan govt|website=@businessline}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/india-not-excluded-from-peace-process-in-afghanistan-china-1569594-2019-07-15|title= not excluded from peace process in Afghanistan: China|website=India Today}}</ref>\n\nOn February 29, 2020, the U.S. signed a conditional peace agreement with the Taliban, which calls for the withdrawal of foreign troops in 14 months if the Taliban uphold the terms of the agreement.<ref name=proposedwithdrawal>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/afghanistan-us-taliban-peace-deal-signing/2020/02/29/b952fb04-5a67-11ea-8efd-0f904bdd8057_story.html |title=U.S. signs peace deal with Taliban agreeing to full withdrawal of American troops from Afghanistan |last=George |first=Susannah |date=February 29, 2020 |website=WashingtonPost.com}}</ref><ref name=stillproposedwithdrawal>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/us-strikes-deal-with-taliban-to-withdraw-troops-from-afghanistan/ar-BB10ym7c |title=U.S. Strikes Deal With Taliban to Withdraw Troops From Afghanistan |website=MSN.com |publisher=The New York Times |date=February 29, 2020 |last=Mashal |first=Mujib}}</ref> On March 1, 2020, however, the Afghan government, which was not a party to the deal, rejected the U.S. and Taliban's call for a prisoner swap by March 10, 2020, with President Ghani stating that such an agreement will require further negotiation and will also not be implemented as a precondition for future peace negotiations.<ref name=nprreject>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/01/810949474/afghan-president-rejects-timeline-for-prisoner-swap-proposed-in-us-taliban-peace|title=Afghan President Rejects Timeline For Prisoner Swap Proposed In US-Taliban Peace Deal|first=Cat|last=Schuknecht|publisher=NPR|date=March 1, 2020|accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=apreject>https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/01/afghan-peace-deal-prisoner-release-118473|title=Afghan peace deal hits first snag over prisoner releases|author=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=Politico|accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> <ref> [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51695370 Afghan conflict: President Ashraf Ghani rejects Taliban prisoner release], 1 March 2020, BBC. </ref><ref> [https://apnews.com/8cfce4344ad386697c78b033a3cb3dc6 Afghan peace deal hits first snag over prisoner releases], By KATHY GANNON, March 1, 2020, Associated Press. </ref> In March 2020, the Taliban announced they would resume hostilities with the Afghan Government if the prisoners were not released. <ref> [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51706126 Afghan conflict: Taliban to resume attacking local forces after deal with US], 2 March 2020, BBC. </ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51728326 Afghan conflict: Clashes shatter partial truce after US deal], 3 March 2020, BBC. </ref>\n\n====China====\nIn January 2020, China faced a major public health issue due to the effects of the [[2019\u201320 Coronavirus pandemic]], prompting worldwide health concerns about the potential impact of this disease. A drop in tourism<ref>{{cite web|website=Al Jazeera|title=Holiday cancelled? How the coronavirus is hurting tourism|author=Samantha Ho|date=Feb 6, 2020|accessdate=Feb 8, 2020 |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/ajimpact/holiday-cancelled-coronavirus-hurting-tourism-200205093345935.html}}</ref> and even an economic recession may result.<ref>{{cite web|website=CNBC |title=Coronavirus could easily tip China into a technical recession, economist warns|author=Chloe Taylor|date=Feb 4, 2020|accessdate=Feb 8, 2020 |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/04/coronavirus-could-tip-china-into-technical-recession-economist-warns.html}}</ref>\n\n====India====\n{{see also|Premiership of Narendra Modi|Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019#Protests|Citizenship Amendment Act protests}}\n\nThe Citizenship Amendment Act (Bill) protests occurred after the enactment of the [[Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019|Citizenship (Amendment) Act]] (CAA) by the Indian government on 12 December 2019, which triggered widespread ongoing protests across India and abroad against the act and the associated proposals to enact a [[National Register of Citizens]] (NRC).<ref name=\"hansindia\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehansindia.com/news/cities/hyderabad/student-unions-back-anti-citizenship-amendment-act-protests-590361|title=Student unions back anti Citizenship Amendment Act protests|last=India|first=The Hans|date=16 December 2019 |website=thehansindia.com |access-date=17 December 2019}}</ref> The protests began in [[Assam]],<ref name=\"India Today 12 Dec\">{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/mail-today/story/citizenship-bill-protests-here-why-assam-is-burning-1627538-2019-12-12|title=Citizenship Amendment Bill protests: Here's why Assam is burning|last1=Deka|first1=Kaushik|date=12 December 2019|work=India Today|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> [[Delhi]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/anti-citizenship-law-protests-latest-developments/articleshow/72683696.cms|title=Citizenship Amendment Bill 2019: Anti-citizenship law protests: Latest developments and reactions|date=16 December 2019|website=The Times of India|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref> [[Meghalaya]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/citizenship-bill-protests-violence-grips-assam-meghalaya-bengal-oppns-plans-mega-rally-2422713.html|title=Violence Grips Assam, Meghalaya, Bengal & Delhi as Protests Escalate Across India; Oppn Plans Mega Rally|website=News18|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref> [[Arunachal Pradesh]], and [[Tripura]] on 4 December 2019,<ref name=\"mamata rally\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/protests-and-strikes-hit-assam-manipur-tripura-against-cab/story-dPRUypEh1zaUzVOY86O7oK.html|title=Protests and strikes hit Assam, Manipur, Tripura against CAB|date=9 December 2019|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> and quickly spread across the country, although the concerns of the protesters vary.<ref name=\"AtlanticLate\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2019/12/india-citizenship-law-protest/603793/|title=When Is a Protest Too Late?|last=Serhan|first=Yasmeen|date=18 December 2019|website=The Atlantic|access-date=21 December 2019}}, Quote: \"Though the protesters in India share a common opposition to the new citizenship law, their reasons for rejecting the legislation vary.\"</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, a total of 46 people in New Delhi alone had been fatally injured due to the riots and disorder. <ref>[https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/death-toll-in-delhi-riots-rises-to-46-as-indias-capital-remains-on-edge/ Death Toll in Delhi Riots Rises to 46 as India\u2019s Capital Remains on Edge]. The Indian prime minister remains publicly silent on the violence. By Sheikh Saaliq. March 02, 2020. </ref> The riots in New Delhi were largely due to anti-Muslim sentiment. There were widespread reports of violence directed against Muslims. <ref> [https://time.com/5794354/delhi-riots-muslims-india/ Hate Is Being Preached Openly Against Us.' After Delhi Riots, Muslims in India Fear What's Next], BY SAMEER YASIR/DELHI AND BILLY PERRIGO, MARCH 3, 2020, time.com. </ref> <ref> [https://moderndiplomacy.eu/2020/03/02/trump-visits-modi-and-delhi-erupts-in-anti-muslim-riots/ Trump Visits Modi and Delhi Erupts in Anti-Muslim Riots], March 2, 2020 By Dr. Arshad M. Khan, moderndiplomacy.eu website. </ref> <ref> [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51719204 Delhi riots: How Muslims' homes were targeted and burnt], by Soutik Biswas, March 3, 2020. </ref> An Indian police officer was widely commended for risking his life to protect Muslims who were in danger. There were also various reports on individual Hindus who intervened to protect Muslims from mob violence. <ref> [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51670093 Delhi riots: 'Hero cop' who braved a mob to save lives], BBC, 28 February 2020. </ref> <ref> [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/01/india-delhi-after-hindu-mob-riot-religious-hatred-nationalists Inside Delhi: beaten, lynched and burnt alive], by Hannah Ellis-Petersen, Sun 1 Mar 2020, The Guardian. </ref> <ref> [https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2020/03/india-modi-hindu-muslim-delhi-riots/607315/ India Failed Delhi.] In failing to curb violence in its capital city, the country\u2019s government bears responsibility for it. by YASMEEN SERHAN, MARCH 2, 2020, theatlantic.com. </ref>\n\nVarious Muslim countries formally expressed concern. <ref> [https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/indonesia-condemns-anti-muslim-violence-in-india/1748804 Indonesia condemns anti-Muslim violence in India]. Indonesian Minister Razi urges New Delhi to protect Muslims and not harm them over differences in faith. Nicky Aulia Widadio, February 28, 2020. </ref>\n\nThe Amendment created a pathway to Indian citizenship for illegal migrants belonging to [[Hindus|Hindu]], [[Sikhs|Sikh]], [[Buddhist]], [[Jain]], [[Parsis|Parsi]], and [[Christians|Christian]] communities from [[Pakistan]], [[Bangladesh]] and [[Afghanistan]], who had entered India before 2014 fleeing religious persecution.<ref name=\"BBC explained\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-50670393 Citizenship Amendment Bill: India's new 'anti-Muslim' law explained], BBC News, 11 December 2019.</ref> The Amendment does not provide the same pathway to Muslims and others from these countries, nor to refugee [[Sri Lankan Tamils in India]], [[Rohingya]]s from [[Myanmar]], or [[Tibetan refugees in India|Buddhists from Tibet]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/a-dark-day-for-the-country-says-jamaat-chief/article30313127.ece|title=A dark day for the country, says Jamaat-e-Islami chief|last=Reporter|first=Staff|date=15 December 2019|work=The Hindu|access-date=17 January 2020|issn=0971-751X|quote=He said Tamil Hindus from Sri Lanka had been persecuted and questioned why they had not been brought under the ambit of the CAA}}{{subscription required}}</ref> The proposed [[National Register of Citizens]] (NRC) will be an official record of all legal citizens of India; individuals would need to provide a prescribed set of documents issued before a specified cutoff date to be included in it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/et-explains/is-a-pan-india-nrc-possible-the-lesson-from-assam/articleshow/72454225.cms?from=mdr|title=Understanding NRC: What it is and if it can be implemented across the country|date=23 December 2019|work=The Economic Times|access-date=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe amendment has been widely criticised as [[Religious discrimination|discriminating on the basis of religion]], in particular for excluding Muslims.<ref name=\"NPRExcludes\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/12/11/787220640/india-passes-controversial-citizenship-bill-that-would-exclude-muslims |title=India Passes Controversial Citizenship Bill That Would Exclude Muslims |newspaper=NPR.org |first=Sam |last=Gringlas}}</ref> Protestors against the amendment demand that it be scrapped and that the nationwide NRC not be implemented.<ref name=\"wsjdelhi\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/india-protests-against-new-law-spread-to-muslim-area-of-capital-11576596978|title=India Citizenship Protests Spread to Muslim Area of Capital|last=Pokharel|first=Krishna|website=WSJ|date=17 December 2019|access-date=17 January 2020|quote=Protests against a new citizenship law favoring non-Muslim immigrants erupted in violence in a Muslim-dominated part of the Indian capital [...] \"People are opposing this law because it discriminates against Muslims [...]}}</ref><ref name=\"Sigal Samuel\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2019/12/12/21010975/india-muslim-citizenship-bill-national-register|title=India just redefined its citizenship criteria to exclude Muslims|last=Samuel|first=Sigal|date=12 December 2019|website=Vox|access-date=17 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalheraldindia.com/politics/will-revoke-anti-poor-caa-nrc-if-voted-to-power-says-priyanka-gandhi-in-varanasi|title=Will revoke anti-poor CAA-NRC if voted to power, says Priyanka Gandhi in Varanasi|website=National Herald|language=en|access-date=26 January 2020}}</ref> They are concerned that Muslim citizens of India, as well as poor Indians, will be rendered [[Statelessness|stateless]] and put into [[detention camp]]s by the proposed nationwide NRC in combination with the CAA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india-today-insight/story/everything-you-wanted-to-know-about-the-caa-and-nrc-1630771-2019-12-23|title=Everything you wanted to know about the CAA and NRC|date=23 December 2019|first=Kaushik |last=Deka|website=India Today|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/all-you-need-to-know-about-proposed-pan-india-nrc/articleshow/72671119.cms|title=Know the difference between NRC and CAA Bill 2019|date=23 December 2019|work=The Economic Times|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5752186/india-protests-citizenship-act/|title=How a New Law in India Sparked Mass Protests and a Brutal Police Clampdown|website=Time|access-date=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/chandigarh/chandigarh-caa-is-essentially-anti-poor-says-former-ias-officer-kannan-gopinathan-6202416/|title=Chandigarh: CAA is essentially anti-poor, says former IAS officer Kannan Gopinathan|date=6 January 2020|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=26 January 2020}}</ref> They are also concerned that all citizens will be affected by the bureaucratic exercise of the NRC where they will have to prove their citizenship for inclusion in the registry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/its-not-just-about-muslims-all-indians-will-have-to-queue-up-to-prove-they-are-indians-owaisi-2432283.html|title=It's Not Just About Muslims, All Indians Will Have to Queue Up to Prove They are Indians: Owaisi|website=News18|access-date=17 January 2020|quote=\"Why are we protesting? We are protesting because, in the country, in the name of religion, preparation is being made to make us not just second-class citizens but stateless,\" [Owaisi] claimed, adding it is a loss for everyone.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/948969/the-nrc-is-a-bureaucratic-paper-monster-that-will-devour-and-divide-india|title=The NRC is a bureaucratic paper-monster that will devour and divide India|last=Mathur|first=Nayanika|website=Scroll.in|access-date=14 January 2020}}</ref> The protesters have raised voices against [[authoritarianism]], the police crackdown in other universities, and suppression of protests.\n\nProtesters in [[Assam]] and other [[Northeast India|northeastern states]] do not want [[Indian citizenship]] to be granted to any refugee or immigrant, regardless of their religion, as they fear it would alter the region's demographic balance, resulting in a loss of their political rights, culture, and land. They are also concerned that it will motivate further [[Human migration|migration]] from [[Bangladesh]] as well as violate the [[Assam Accord]], which was a prior agreement reached with the central government on migrants and refugees.<ref name=\"iexpressassam\">{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/assam-protests-citizenship-amendment-bill-nrc-northeast-bandh-5543785/|title=Explained: Why Assam, Northeast are angry|last1=Saha|first1=Abhishek|date=20 January 2019|work=The Indian Express|access-date=|quote=Protesters have expressed fears that the prospect of citizenship will encourage migration from Bangladesh. They have cited several grounds for opposing this. Demography: This will change across Northeastern states, protesters say, as has already been happening in Assam and Tripura over decades of migration (see graphs). \"Assamese could become the second language. Then there is also the question of loss of political rights and culture of the indigenous people,\u201d said former Chief Minister Prafulla Mahanta, who was the face of the Assam Movement (1979-85) against illegal immigration, and one of the signatories to the Assam Accord at the culmination of the movement. (...) Protesters say the Bill goes against the Assam Accord and negates the ongoing update of the National Register of Citizens (NRC).}}</ref><ref name=\"reuters1211\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-india-citizenship-idUSKBN1YF0QI|title=India's parliament passes citizenship law, protests flare|date=11 December 2019|work=Reuters|access-date=17 January 2020|quote=The bill will take away our rights, language and culture with millions of Bangladeshis getting citizenship (...) people in Assam and surrounding states fear that arriving settlers could increase competition for land and upset the region\u2019s demographic balance}}</ref>\n\nThe protests started in Assam on 4 December 2019, after the bill was introduced in parliament. Later on, protests erupted in [[Northeast India]], and subsequently spread to the major cities of India. On 15 December, major protests took place near [[Jamia Millia Islamia]] in [[New Delhi]] and [[Aligarh Muslim University]]. As the protests spread, private and public property was burnt and destroyed by mobs, and some railway stations were vandalized.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/caa-violence-arson-in-south-delhi-as-protesters-torch-four-buses-two-injured-11576412295374.html|title=CAA: Violence, arson in south Delhi as protesters torch four buses; two injured|date=15 December 2019|website=Livemint|access-date=17 January 2020|quote=Four buses were set ablaze by a mob and two fire officials were injured in stone pelting as the protests against the newly enacted Citizenship Act\" (...) \"The situation turned critical when a bus was burned by the protestors and police got into action}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theweek.com/5things/884376/violent-protests-over-citizenship-law-continue-india|title=Violent protests over citizenship law continue in India|website=The Week|access-date=17 January 2020|quote=Protesters set fire to buses and vandalized railroad stations}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/no-bullet-fired-by-police-during-protests-at-jamia-mha-officials-119121700271_1.html|title=Delhi cops didn't fire during Citizenship Act protests at Jamia: Officials|date=17 December 2019|work=Business Standard India|access-date=17 January 2020|quote=Several vehicles, including buses, were burnt down and public properties destroyed during the protests against the Citizenship Amendment Act, which was passed by Parliament last week.}}</ref> Police [[2019 Jamia Milia Islamia attack|forcibly entered]] the campus of Jamia, used batons and [[tear gas]] on the students, and more than 200 students were injured while around 100 were detained overnight in the police station. The police action was widely criticized and resulted in students across the country protesting in solidarity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/supreme-court-declines-to-take-up-police-action-against-jamia-protesters-says-it-is-a-law-and-order-problem/story-WlBa5J75IkHiW3iMbLffnK.html|title=High courts can inquire, says Supreme Court on plea over police action against protesters|date=17 December 2019|website=Hindustan Times|access-date=17 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/17/india-protests-students-condemn-barbaric-police|title=India protests: students condemn 'barbaric' police|last=Ellis-Petersen|first=Hannah|date=17 December 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=17 December 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n====Russia====\n{{see also|2020 Russian constitutional referendum}}\n\nA constitutional referendum will be held in [[Russia]] on 22 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vedomosti.ru/politics/articles/2020/02/26/823899-den-obscherossiiskogo-golosovaniya?utm_referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fzen.yandex.com&utm_campaign=dbr|title=\u0413\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u043e \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430\u043c \u0432 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u044e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0439\u0434\u0435\u0442 22 \u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u043b\u044f|website=\u0412\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> The draft [[2020 amendments to the Constitution of Russia|amendments to the Constitution]] were submitted to a referendum in accordance with article 2 of the Law on Amendments to the Constitution.<ref name=Law>[https://sozd.duma.gov.ru/bill/885214-7 \u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043e \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0435 \u043a \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438]</ref>\n\nThe referendum is referred to as an All-Russian vote, as it is not held in accordance with the Federal Constitutional Law on the Referendum. Unlike a referendum carried out in accordance with the referendum law, voters will be asked whether they approve the entire revised constitution as a whole, rather than approving each amendment separately.<ref>[https://tass.com/politics/1111023 Public vote on constitutional amendments will be held on the law as a whole \u2014 official]</ref> At the same time, there are no differences from the referendum, just as in 1993, when the [[1993 Russian constitutional referendum|All-Russian vote]] on the adoption of the Constitution was held, which was also not officially referred to as a referendum.\n\nThe referendum was proposed by President [[Vladimir Putin]] during his [[2020 Presidential Address to the Federal Assembly]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.interfax.ru/russia/691265|title=\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u043b \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438 \"\u0432\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435\" \u043f\u043e \u043f\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u043a \u0432 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u044e|website=\u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0444\u0430\u043a\u0441|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\n==== Turkey ====\n{{see also|2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria|Northwestern Syria offensive (December 2019\u2013present)|2019 Turkish offensive into north-western Syria}}\nIn March 2020, [[Turkey]] started a military offensive against the [[Syrian Armed Forces]] as part of its [[Turkish involvement in the Syrian Civil War|intervention in the Syrian Civil War]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gall|first=Carlotta|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/01/world/middleeast/turkey-syria-assault.html|title=Turkey Declares Major Offensive Against Syrian Government|date=2020-03-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> That same month Turkey also declared that it would no longer stop migrants from entering the [[European Union]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51678462|title=Turkey lets refugees exit towards Europe|date=2020-02-28|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Middle East and Northern Africa===\n==== Iran ====\n{{See also|2019\u201320 Persian Gulf crisis|2020 Iran protests|2020 Iranian legislative election}}\n\nIn January [[2020]], the [[United States]] [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|assassinated]] the commander of the [[Quds Force]] of the [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]], general [[Qasem Soleimani]]. This led to an [[2020 Iranian attack on U.S. forces in Iraq|Iranian missile strike]] against bases housing US troops in Iraq five days later. As a result of expectations of a US retribution, the [[Islamic Republic of Iran Air Defense Force|Iranian air defence system]] accidentally shot down [[Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752]], killing all 176 people on board.<ref>[https://www.vox.com/world/2020/1/13/21051794/us-iran-soleimani-ukraine-airline-questions 9 questions about the US-Iran crisis you were too embarrassed to ask] By Alex Ward and Zack Beauchamp, Vox, 13 Jan 2020</ref>\n====Iraq====\n{{see also|2019\u201320 Iraqi protests}} \nIn 2020, demonstrations took place in Baghdad and other parts of Iraq, over popular discontent with government corruption, unemployment, poor government services, and foreign interference within Iraq.  Reports said that 450 protesters had been fatally shot by security forces. <ref name=\"bbc iraq\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51712107 |date=March 2, 2020|title= Iraq power vacuum as political crisis hits PM post. |website=bbc.com |publisher=[[BBC]] |access-date=March 3, 2020}} </ref> Major protests were based in [[Nasiriyah]] in [[Dhi Qar]] province, with hundreds of protesters arriving there from other cities.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2020/02/nasiriyah-dhi-qar-iraq-protests.html |title= Nasiriyah becomes the Iraqi protest capital. }}</ref> New clashes erupted in Baghdad between protesters and security forces, with security forces using gunfire against protesters.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.timesofisrael.com/protester-shot-dead-in-fresh-iraq-violence/ |title= Protester shot dead in fresh Iraq violence. }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.660citynews.com/2020/02/23/iraqi-officials-1-protester-shot-dead-in-fresh-violence/ |title=Iraqi officials: 1 protester shot dead in fresh violence. }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/2147131/iraqi-nurse-spends-her-weekends-stitching-wounds-protest-site |title= Iraqi Nurse Spends Her Weekends Stitching Wounds at Protest Site. }}</ref> One march included more than 1,000 students.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.660citynews.com/2020/02/23/iraqi-officials-1-protester-shot-dead-in-fresh-violence/ |title= Iraqi students hold anti-government protests. }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, [[Mohammed Allawi]] sent a letter to the [[President of Iraq]], stating that he had to decline to take office as Prime Minister since the Iraqi Parliament had declined to approve his cabinet. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/uncertainty-looms-iraqi-pm-designate-allawi-steps-200302063000903.html |title= Uncertainty looms as Iraqi PM-designate Allawi steps down. |}} Iraq's crisis deepens as Mohammed Tawfiq Allawi halts efforts to form new government amid political infighting. Mar 2, 2020, Al Jazeera. </ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/02/iraqs-allawi-bows-out-as-pm-designate-rockets-hit-green-zone.html |title= Iraq's Allawi bows out as PM-designate, rockets hit Green Zone. |}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20200302-iraqs-pm-designate-allawi-steps-down/ |title= Iraq\u2019s PM-designate Allawi steps down. |}}</ref> Reports indicated that the crowds of protesters in Baghdad had expressed widespread opposition to Allawi. <ref name=\"bbc iraq\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51712107 |date=March 2, 2020|title= Iraq power vacuum as political crisis hits PM post. |website=bbc.com |publisher=[[BBC]] |access-date=March 3, 2020}} </ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.dw.com/en/iraqs-prime-minister-designate-mohammed-allawi-withdraws-from-race/a-52601139 |title= Iraq's Prime Minister-designate Mohammed Allawi withdraws from race. |}}</ref>\n\n====Libya====\n{{main|Libyan peace process#Political track}}\nIn February 2020, the political track of the Libyan peace process started in Geneva among 20 Libyans, from both the Tobruk-based and Tripoli-based parts of the [[House of Representatives (Libya)|Libyan House of Representatives]], and from the independent persons' group selected by [[United Nations Support Mission in Libya|UN Support Mission in Libya]] (UNSMIL), including [[Ministry of Interior (Libya)|Interior Minister]] [[Fathi Bashagha]], former Education Minister [[Othman Abdul Jalil]] and former head of the HCS [[Abdulrahman Sewehli]].<ref name=\"LibObs_pol_track_boycott\">{{cite news | last1= Assad | first1= Abdulkader | title=UNSMIL kicks off political talks in Geneva despite boycott of major Libyan lawmakers | date= 2020-02-26 |newspaper= [[The Libya Observer]] | url=https://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/unsmil-kicks-political-talks-geneva-despite-boycott-major-libyan-lawmakers |accessdate=2020-02-27 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227211142/https://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/unsmil-kicks-political-talks-geneva-despite-boycott-major-libyan-lawmakers |archivedate=2020-02-27 |url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped --> |url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref> The aimed composition was 13 HoR representatives from both the Tobruk and Tripoli branches, 13 HCS representatives and 14 UNSMIL-selected independent Libyans, for a total of 40.<ref name=\"LibHerald_Tobruk_wants_13\">{{cite news | title= UNSMIL political track talks to go ahead despite pullout by Tobruk HoR and Tripoli State Council | date= 2020-02-27 |newspaper= [[Libya Herald]] | url= https://www.libyaherald.com/2020/02/25/unsmil-political-track-talks-to-go-ahead-despite-pullout-by-tobruk-hor-and-tripoli-state-council/ |accessdate=2020-02-27 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200227220123/https://www.libyaherald.com/2020/02/25/unsmil-political-track-talks-to-go-ahead-despite-pullout-by-tobruk-hor-and-tripoli-state-council/ |archivedate= 2020-02-27 |url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped --> |url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref>\n\n====Syria====\n{{see also|Syrian civil war|Timeline of the Syrian Civil War|Timeline of the Syrian Civil War (January\u2013April 2020)|Northwestern Syria offensive (December 2019\u2013March 2020)}}\n\nIn early 2020, the Syrian Civil War flared up, with massive fighting between Syrian government forces and rebel groups in northwestern Syria. The conflict began to threaten to draw Turkey and Syria into armed conflict, as Turkey seemed to support some rebel groups. In the wake of the withdrawal by the United States of most of its troops from the war zone in Syria, Russia stepped in as a mediator between the factions, i.e., between the Syrian government, local Kurdish groups, Turkey, and some rebel groups. \n\nNew waves of migrants fled over the Turkish border and also attempted to enter Greece, but were barred by Greek forces. There were concerns about a new refugee crisis possibly overtaking the region.\n\nIn March 2020, Syria claimed that a number of its soldiers had been killed in Turkish attacks.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51701069 Syria war: Turkish drone strikes 'kill 19 Syrian soldiers'], bbc.com. </ref>  Turkey warned that millions of migrants might head for the EU. <ref> [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51707958 Turkey says millions of migrants may head to EU], MArch 2, 2020, bbc. </ref> Greece suspended all asylum applications.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51695468 Greece suspends asylum applications as migrants seek to leave Turkey], 1 March 2020, bbc. </ref>\n\n====Yemen====\n{{See also|Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)}}\n\nThe Yemeni Civil War is an ongoing conflict that began in 2015 between two factions: the [[Abdrabbuh Mansur Hadi]] led Yemeni government and the [[Houthi]] armed movement, along with their supporters and allies. Both claim to constitute the official government of [[Yemen]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/143295/asher-orkaby/houthi-who|agency=Foreign Affairs|title=Houthi Who?|first=Asher|last=Orkaby|date=25 March 2015|accessdate=25 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150327115828/http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/143295/asher-orkaby/houthi-who|archivedate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Houthis|Houthi]] forces currently control the capital [[Sana'a|Sana\u02bda]], allied with forces loyal to the former president [[Ali Abdullah Saleh]], have clashed with the forces loyal to Hadi who are based in [[Aden]]. [[Al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] (AQAP) and the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] have also carried out attacks, with AQAP controlling swathes of territory in the hinterlands, and along stretches of the coast.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yemen in Crisis|url=http://www.cfr.org/yemen/yemen-crisis/p36488|publisher=Council on Foreign Relations|date=8 July 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150509030311/http://www.cfr.org/yemen/yemen-crisis/p36488|archivedate=9 May 2015}}</ref> Concurrently, the Hadi government is in conflict with [[United Arab Emirates|UAE forces]] as a result of UAE military measures such as the [[United Arab Emirates takeover of Socotra]] and UAE-backed STC takeover of Aden.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/08/yemen-southern-separatists-regain-control-port-city-aden-190829073935248.html|title=Hadi urges Saudi intervention to stop UAE support for separatists|website=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref>\n\n===Sub-Saharan Africa===\n<!----\n{{collapse top|title=Sub-Saharan Africa|expand=yes}}\n---->\n\nAs the 2020s begin, there is the possibility of unprecedented economic growth throughout Africa, based on probable increases in trade when the [[African Continental Free Trade Area |African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCTA)]] goes fully into effect on July 1, 2020, abolishing 90% of tariffs between member states and bringing a 50% increase in trade in the next few years.<ref name=hammond>[https://www.africanliberty.org/2020/01/24/what-can-we-expect-from-africa-in-the-2020s/ What Can We Expect from Africa in the 2020s?] by Alexander Hammond, African Liberty.org, 24 Jan 2020</ref><ref name=odi>[https://www.odi.org/blogs/16535-will-2020-be-decade-Africa-economic-transformation Will the 2020s be the decade of Africa\u2019s economic transformation?] by Arkebe Okubay, ODI.org, 14 Jan 2020</ref> This economic growth could lead directly to increases in life expectancy, literacy, and per capita income.\n\n[[Nigeria]] and [[South Africa]] account for the largest shares of Africa's [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] at 29.3% and 19.1%, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|website=African Development Bank Group|year=2020|accessdate=Feb 3, 2020|title=West Africa Regional Overview |url=https://www.afdb.org/en/countries/west-africa/west-africa-overview}}</ref> Civil strife and terrorism continue to plague the continent, particularly in the [[Sahel]] and the [[Horn of Africa]].<ref name=relief>[https://reliefweb.int/report/world/conflict-still-africa-s-biggest-challenge-2020 Conflict is still Africa\u2019s biggest challenge in 2020] by Simon Allison, Relief Web, 6 Jan 2020</ref> Finally, Africa is more vulnerable than any other region to the world's changing weather patterns.<ref>{{cite web|website=BBC World News|title=How Africa will be affected by climate change|author=Richard Washington|date=Dec 15, 2019|accessdate=Feb 3, 2020|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-50726701}}</ref>\n\n====West Africa====\n{{See also|2020 in West Africa}}\n[[Burkina Faso]], [[Mali]], and [[Nigeria]] face serious challenges related to security and terrorism such as the January 2020 [[2020 Gamboru bombing]].<ref>[https://www.dw.com/en/nigeria-hit-by-deadly-bomb-attack-near-cameroon/a-51908242 Nigeria hit by deadly bomb attack near Cameroon] Deutsche Welle, 7 Jan 2020</ref><ref>[https://apnews.com/08eddc78099bbcda5caf8bee7de1fa2a French summit aims to boost counterterror fight in W. Africa]  [https://apnews.com/36e33f583ce814ea36bf46fc37ec369b Niger army chief fired after 89 killed in extremist attack]</ref> In January 2020 the United States called for a reduction of the [[United Nations Multidimensional Integrated Stabilization Mission in Mali|United Nations Multidimensional Integrated Stabilization Mission in Mali (MINUSMA)]] with a new focus on protecting civilians. France and Russia opposed reductions.<ref>[https://apnews.com/09672220276b5cdbce63f139566b58c4 US calls for smaller UN force in Mali, Russia says no change] By Edith M. Lederer, AP, 15 Jan 2020, retrieved 8 Feb 2020</ref>\n\n[[Female genital mutilation|Female genital mutilation (FGM)]] is a continuing issue in [[Guinea]], [[the Gambia]], Burkina Faso, Mali, and [[Sierra Leone]].<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/science-health/female-genital-mutilation-still-prevalent-west-africa Female Genital Mutilation Still Prevalent in West Africa] By Annika Hammerschlag, Voice of America, 6 February 2020</ref>\n\nSenegalese-born American rapper [[Akon|Akon's]] new \"Akon City\" located near [[Dakar]],<ref>{{cite web|website=CNN Travel|date=14 Jan 2020 |url=https://edition.cnn.com/travel/article/akon-city-senegal-trnd/index.html |title=Akon created his own city in Senegal called 'Akon City'|author=Amir Vera}}</ref> investment in solar energy,<ref>{{cite web|website=Archdye.com |title=Senegal completes largest wind farm in West Africa|date=Jan 8, 2020 |url=https://www.archyde.com/senegal-completes-largest-wind-farm-in-west-africa/?amp}}</ref> and a transition toward eco-farming on a national scale are [[Senegal|Senegal's]] responses to climate change.<ref>[https://allafrica.com/stories/202002050726.html Senegal Turns to Eco-Farming to Protect Food Supply As Climate Changes]</ref>\n\n====East Africa====\n{{See also|2020 in East Africa}}\nHuman rights concerns and freedom of the press are highlighted in [[South Sudan]],<ref>[https://apnews.com/f6da04d6674e981b525454d995b86f9b US sanctions South Sudan\u2019s vice president over abuses] by Cara Anna, AP, 8 Jan 2020, retrieved 15 Feb 2020</ref> [[Comoros]],<ref>[https://allafrica.com/stories/202001160648.html Comoros: Two Reporters Arrested in Comoros, Placed Under Judicial Control] allAfrica, 16 Jan 2020, retrieved 11 Feb 2020</ref> and [[Tanzania]] as 2020 begins.<ref>[https://allafrica.com/stories/202002030868.html Tanzania: Obstructions to LGBT Health, Rights]</ref>\n====Ethiopia====\nTensions began to rise again between Ethiopia and Eritrea, after several years of efforts to negotiate peace, due to possible border disputes. <ref> [https://www.trtworld.com/africa/why-are-ethiopian-leaders-calling-eritrea-s-president-hitler-34158 Why are Ethiopian leaders calling Eritrea's president \u2018Hitler\u2019?], An escalating war of words is taking place between Eritrea and Ethiopia, as the two countries face-off over a flaring border dispute that historically claimed the lives of over 100,000 people. February 27, 2020. trtworld.com. </ref><ref> [https://cruxnow.com/church-in-africa/2020/02/ethiopian-cardinal-other-church-leaders-barred-from-entering-eritrea/ Ethiopian cardinal, other church leaders barred from entering Eritrea], Fredrick Nzwili, CNSFeb 28, 2020, CATHOLIC NEWS SERVICE. </ref><ref> [https://www.voanews.com/africa/un-decries-lack-reforms-and-widespread-abuse-eritrea UN Decries Lack of Reforms and Widespread Abuse in Eritrea], By Lisa Schlein, March 01, 2020. </ref>\n\nAfter having won the Nobel Peace Prize in 2019, Prime Minister Abiy Ahmed's government adopted some policies which raised some concerns about political developments in Ethiopia. Abiy dissolved the governing coalition and formed a new party, the Prosperity Party; some said the imposition of a brand-new political party was detrimental to political stability. Also, the government enacted some restrictions on some forms of expression which raised concern about standards of free speech.<ref>[https://www.ezega.com/News/NewsDetails/7745/Ethiopia-Approves-Controversial-Law-on-Hate-Speech-and-Disinformation Ethiopia Approves Controversial Law on Hate Speech and Disinformation, By Staff Reporter, ezega.com. </ref><ref> [https://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/upfront/2020/02/ethiopia-sliding-abiy-ahmed-200214062515704.html Is Ethiopia sliding backwards under Abiy Ahmed?] We challenge an adviser to Ethiopia's prime minister on his record. 14 Feb 2020, al-jazeera. </ref>\nAbiy's response to rebel groups has raised some concerns about undue harshness, although some others allege that he was originally too lenient. <ref> [https://eastafricamonitor.com/how-popular-is-abiy-ahmed-in-ethiopia-as-election-looms/ How popular is Abiy Ahmed in Ethiopia as election looms?], February 27, 2020. </ref><ref>[https://www.france24.com/en/20200229-ethiopia-s-abiy-faces-outcry-over-crackdown-on-rebels [https://www.france24.com/en/20200229-ethiopia-s-abiy-faces-outcry-over-crackdown-on-rebels Ethiopia's Abiy faces outcry over crackdown on rebels],Issued on: 29/02/2020. france24.com </ref> Amnesty International raised concerns about the status of one opposition leader.<ref> [https://eastafricamonitor.com/amnesty-ethiopian-police-must-account-for-missing-opposition-leader/ Amnesty: Ethiopian police must account for missing opposition leader], March 3, 2020. </ref> <ref> [https://todaynewsafrica.com/breaking-amnesty-international-rages-as-nobel-peace-prize-winner-abiy-ahmed-unleashes-police-on-opposition-in-oromia-ethiopia-vender-killed-musician-injured/ Amnesty International Rages As Nobel Peace Prize Winner Abiy Ahmed Unleashes Police On Opposition In Oromia, Ethiopia. Vendor Killed, Musician Injured] By TODAY NEWS AFRICA </ref> Abiy encouraged Ethiopian refugees to return home, due to improving conditions. <ref> [https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/africa/Abiy-govt-more-refugees-going-home/4552902-5468496-mcpgxd/index.html Abiy\u2019s citizen-focused govt bringing more refugees home], TUESDAY FEBRUARY 25 2020, theeastafrican.co.ke. </ref>\n\n====Sudan====\n{{See also|Sudanese peace process}}\n\nIn January 2020, progress was made in peace negotiations, in the areas of land, transitional justice and system of government issues via the ''Darfur'' track of negotiations. SRF and Sovereignty Council representatives agreed on the creation of a [[Darfur war crimes court|Special Court for Darfur]] to conduct investigations and trials for [[war crime]]s and [[crimes against humanity]] carried out during the [[War in Darfur]] by the al-Bashir presidency and by warlords. ''Two Areas'' negotiations with SPLM-N (al-Hilu) had progressed on six framework agreement points, after a two-week pause, but disagreement remained on SPLM-N (al-Hilu)'s requirement of a secular state in South Kordofan and [[Nuba Mountains]] and [[Blue Nile (state)|Blue Nile]] self-determination. On 24 January on the ''Two Areas'' track, political and security agreements, constituting a ''framework'' agreement, were signed by Hemetti on behalf of the Sovereignty Council and Ahmed El Omda Badi on behalf of SPLM-N (Agar). The agreements give legislative autonomy to South Kordofan and Blue Nile; propose solutions for the sharing of land and other resources, and aim to unify all militias and government soldiers into a single unified Sudanese military body.\n\nOn 26 January, a \"final\" peace agreement for the northern track, including issues of studies for new dams, compensation for people displaced by existing dams, road construction and burial of electronic and nuclear waste, was signed by Shamseldin Kabashi of the Sovereignty Council and Dahab Ibrahim of the [[Kush Movement]]. <ref> [https://www.middleeasteye.net/big-story/can-south-sudans-men-war-lead-country-peace Can South Sudan's men of war lead the country to peace?], by Peter Oborne & Jan-Peter Westad, February 15, 2020. Middle East Eye website. </ref><ref> [https://www.dabangasudan.org/en/all-news/article/sudan-peace-talks-agreement-on-east-track-finalised  Sudan peace talks: Agreement on eastern track finalised], February 23 - 2020, dabangasudan website. </ref><ref>[https://thehill.com/opinion/international/484591-the-trouble-with-south-sudans-transitional-government The trouble with South Sudan's transitional government] BY AMIR IDRIS, oped, 02/28/20, thehill.com. </ref> \n\nIn February 2020, a new unity government was announced, to govern the entire country, with the support of all sides of the conflict.<ref> [https://www.npr.org/2020/02/22/808471587/south-sudan-forges-unity-government-renewing-fragile-hope-for-peace South Sudan Forges Unity Government, Renewing Fragile Hope For Peace] February 22, 2020, by Colin Dwyer, NPR. </ref><ref> [https://apnews.com/d3b929b5a687b69068e4f3ca24cccd7f South Sudan\u2019s rivals form unity government meant to end war] By MAURA AJAK, February 22, 2020, Associated Press. </ref> As one part of the agreement, the current cabinet was disbanded, in order to enable more opposition members to be appointed to cabinet roles. <ref> [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51562367 South Sudan rivals Salva Kiir and Riek Machar strike unity deal], 22 February 2020, BBC. </ref> <ref> [https://carnegieendowment.org/2020/02/27/unity-government-rekindles-hopes-for-peace-in-south-sudan-pub-81173 Unity Government Rekindles Hopes for Peace in South Sudan] by ASHLEY QUARCOO, FEBRUARY 27, 2020, Carnegie Endowment website. </ref> <ref> [https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/south-sudan-rival-leaders-form-coalition-government-200222121043672.html South Sudan's rival leaders form coalition government]. Opposition leader Riek Machar was sworn in on Saturday as the deputy of President Salva Kiir. 22 Feb 2020. Al Jazeera. </ref><ref>[https://reliefweb.int/report/south-sudan/senior-state-department-official-developments-south-sudan-s-peace-process Senior State Department Official On Developments in South Sudan\u2019s Peace Process], Source US State Dept. Published 26 Feb 2020. </ref> In March 2020, negotiators and officials on both sides of the conflict attempted to work out arrangements to facilitate the appointment of civilian governors for various regions, in concert with ongoing peace efforts. <ref> [https://www.dabangasudan.org/en/all-news/article/appointing-of-civilian-governors-mps-remain-obstacles-for-sudan-s-peace Appointing of civilian governors, MPs remains obstacles for Sudan\u2019s peace], March 1 - 2020 dabangasudan website. </ref> The EU announced its support for the peace efforts and pledged to provide financial support of 100 million Euros. <ref> [https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/IP_20_352 European Union announces \u20ac100 million to support the democratic transition process in Sudan], February 29, 2020, EU official website. </ref>\n\n====Central Africa====\n{{See also|2020 in Middle Africa}}\n\n====Southern Africa====\n\n<!----\n{{collapse bottom}}\n--->\n\n===Europe===\n<!----\n{{collapse top|title=Europe|expand=yes}}\n---->\n\n====European Union====\nThe [[European Union]] reduced in member states from 28 to 27 with the exit of the [[United Kingdom]] on January 31, 2020.\n\n==== Greece ====\nFollowing a surge of migrant arrivals from Turkey, [[Greece]] suspended all asylum applications in March 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stevis-Gridneff|first=Matina|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/01/world/europe/greece-migrants-border-turkey.html|title=Greece Suspends Asylum as Turkey Opens Gates for Migrants|date=2020-03-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== Ireland ====\nThe [[2020 Irish general election]] resulted in a historic win for the [[Sinn F\u00e9in]], making it the second largest party of the [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=correspondent|first=Rory Carroll Ireland|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/10/sinn-fein-declares-victory-irish-general-election|title=Sinn F\u00e9in declares victory in Irish general election|date=2020-02-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The result was seen as a historic shift in [[Ireland|Ireland's]] political landscape, effectively ending the [[two-party system]] of [[Fine Gael]] and [[Fianna F\u00e1il]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sinn-fein-shatters-irelands-political-landscape-to-become-second-largest-party/|title=Sinn Fein shatters Ireland\u2019s political landscape to become second largest party|last=Agencies|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> The reason for the electoral upset for these parties was believed to be  in voter dissatisfaction on issues of [[Health in Ireland|health]], housing and [[Homelessness in Ireland|homelessness]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/6449024a-4c19-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5|title=Subscribe to read {{!}} Financial Times|website=www.ft.com|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\n====United Kingdom====\n{{See also|Premiership of Boris Johnson|Brexit|Brexit negotiations in 2019}}\n\n[[Brexit]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hall|first1=Damien|title='Breksit' or 'bregzit'? The question that divides a nation|url=https://theconversation.com/breksit-or-bregzit-the-question-that-divides-a-nation-82278|date=11 August 2017|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=22 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704035541/http://theconversation.com/breksit-or-bregzit-the-question-that-divides-a-nation-82278|archive-date=4 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> (a [[portmanteau]] of \"British\" and \"exit\") is the [[Withdrawal from the European Union|withdrawal]] of the [[United Kingdom]] (UK) from the [[European Union]] (EU). Following a UK-wide [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|referendum in June 2016]], in which 52% voted to leave and 48% voted to remain in the EU, the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] formally announced the country's withdrawal in March 2017, beginning the [[Brexit negotiations|Brexit process]]. The withdrawal was delayed by deadlock in the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|British parliament]]. Following a general election, Parliament [[European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Act 2020|ratified]] the [[Brexit withdrawal agreement|withdrawal agreement]], and the UK left the EU at 11&nbsp;p.m. [[Greenwich Mean Time|GMT]] on 31 January 2020. This began a transition period that is set to end on 31 December 2020, during which the UK and EU will negotiate their future relationship.<ref name=Bennett>{{Cite news|title=How will the Brexit transition period work?|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/0/brexit-2020-transition-period/|newspaper=Telegraph|date=27 January 2020|author=Asa Bennett|access-date=28 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128044559/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/0/brexit-2020-transition-period/|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The UK remains subject to [[European Union law|EU law]] and remains part of the EU [[European Union Customs Union|customs union]] and [[European Single Market|single market]] during the transition, but is no longer part of the EU's political bodies or institutions.<ref name=Edgington>{{cite news|author=Tom Edgington|title=Brexit: What is the transition period?|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50838994|date=31 January 2020|access-date=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131215049/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50838994|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=QAEC>{{cite news|publisher=European Commission|date=24 January 2020|title=Questions and Answers on the United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union on 31 January 2020|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/qanda_20_104|access-date=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201003034/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/qanda_20_104|archive-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\n<!----\n{{collapse top|title=North America|expand=yes}}\n---->\n\n====Caribbean====\n{{See also|2020 in the Caribbean}}\nIn '''[[Haiti]]''', there is pressure on President [[Jovenel Mo\u00efse]] due to charges of corruption, poor living conditions, a high crime rate, and rising inflation.<ref name=al_stories /> '''[[Puerto Rico]]''' continues to struggle with the devastation from [[Hurricane Maria]] in 2017 and a [[2020 Puerto Rico earthquakes|series of earthquakes in 2019-20]] and a subsequent political shakeup.<ref>[https://www.cbsnews.com/news/puerto-rican-governor-fires-emergency-director-after-aid-is-found-sitting-in-warehouse-2020-01-18/ ''Puerto Rico governor fires emergency director after aid is found sitting in warehouse.''] Audrey McNamara. CBS News. 19 January 2020. Accessed 25 January 2020.  [https://www.cbsnews.com/news/puerto-rico-supplies-warehouse-governor-wanda-vazquez-fires-2-more-officials-over-viral-video-showing-aid-2020-01-19/ ''Puerto Rico governor fires 2 more officials after emergency supplies found sitting in warehouse.''] Peter Martinez and Audrey McNamara. CBS News. 19 January 2020. Accessed 25 January 2020.</ref>\n\n====Central America regional items====\n{{See also|2020 in Central America}}\nInternal and external migratiion are major concerns throughout the region.<ref name=al_stories />\n\nHuman rights and oppression are a major concern in '''[[Nicaragua]]''', which saw 70,000 emigrants in 2019. '''[[Costa Rica]]''' is struggling to care for 55,000 of those migrants. President [[Nayib Bukele]] of '''[[El Salvador]]''' is popular, but the country's economy is stagnant and crime continues to grow. '''[[Guatemala]]''' and '''[[Honduras]]''' are also facing corruption and high crime rates, as well as suffering from the effects of climate change.<ref name=al_stories />\n\n====Dominican Republic====\n{{see also|2020 Dominican Republic general election}} \n\nIn March 2020, massive protests occurred in the Dominican Republic, due to announced postponement of national elections.<ref> [https://www.latinousa.org/2020/03/02/trabucazo2020photos/ PHOTOS: Dominicans Hold Massive #Trabucazo2020 Demonstration For Democracy] By TATIANA FERNANDEZ GEARA, MAR 2, 2020, latinousa.org. </ref>\n\n====Mexico====\n{{see also|Presidency of Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador|LXIV Legislature of the Mexican Congress|Fourth Transformation}}\nAs the [[Fourth Transformation]] enters its second year, President [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador|Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador (AMLO)]] faces challenges involving social violence (particularly drug-related and other [[List of countries by intentional homicide rate|killings]]),<ref>[https://aristeguinoticias.com/0201/mexico/senala-amlo-que-su-reto-para-2020-es-serenar-a-mexico/ Se\u00f1ala AMLO que su reto para 2020 es serenar a M\u00e9xico] Aristegui Noticias, 2 Jan 2020  [https://www.univision.com/noticias/america-latina/una-reaparicion-fortalecida-del-narco-y-la-presion-de-trump-la-seguridad-sera-el-mayor-reto-de-amlo-en-2020 Una \"reaparici\u00f3n fortalecida\" del narco y la presi\u00f3n de Trump: la seguridad ser\u00e1 el mayor reto de AMLO en 2020] by Patricia Velez Santiago, Univision Noticias, 2 Jan 2020</ref> corruption, major infrastructure development, universal health care,<ref>[https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/mexico/sociedad/sector-salud-el-principal-reto-para-el-gobierno-de-amlo-en-2020-4638480.html Sector salud, el principal reto para el gobierno de AMLO en 2020] El Sol de Mexico, 29 December 2019</ref>  and decentralization of the government.<ref>{{cite web|website=Diario Contrapeso Ciudadano|title=TOP 5: RETOS DE AMLO EN 2020|language=es|trans-title=Top 5: Challenges for AMLO in 2020|date=Jan 8, 2020|url=https://www.contrapesociudadano.com/top-5-retos-de-amlo-en-2020/}}</ref><ref>[https://billieparkernoticias.com/define-amlo-los-dos-retos-por-resolver-este-2020-seguridad-publica-y-seguridad-social/ Define AMLO los dos retos por resolver este 2020: Seguridad P\u00fablica y Seguridad Social.] Billie Parker Noticias, 14 Jan 2020</ref> At a news conference on January 15, 2020, journalist [[Jorge Ramos (news anchor)|Jorge Ramos]] pointed that during AMLO's first year as president, there were more homicides than under his predecessors; Ramos asked if a change in strategy and/or personal were required. The president assured him that we would see results by December.<ref>[https://www.proceso.com.mx/614236/amlo-jorge-ramos-seguridad AMLO responde a Jorge Ramos: en diciembre, resultados sobre seguridad] by Sara Pantoja, Proceso, 15 Jan 2020</ref> \n\nFollowing several notorious cases of [[femicide]], [[violence against women in Mexico|violence against women]] emerges as a priority concern. Hundreds of thousands march on March 8<ref>[https://www.msn.com/es-mx/noticias/mujeres/marchan-m%C3%A1s-de-15-mil-en-monterrey/ar-BB10Wwwk More than 15,000 march in Monterrey] {{in lang|es}} by Caroline Leon, Milenio, 9 Mar 2020  [https://politica.expansion.mx/mexico/2020/03/08/miles-mujeres-marchan-cdmx-consignas-pintas-reclamos-justicia Thousands of women march on CDMX between slogans, graffiti, and claims for justice] {{in lang|es}} Expansion Politica, 8 Mar 2020</ref> and millions of women strike on March 9, [[2020 in Mexico|2020]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-51736957 Fury fuels historic women's strike in Mexico] By Will Grant\nBBC News, 9 Mar 2020  [https://www.msn.com/es-mx/noticias/mexico/hoy-ellas-no-llegaron-as%C3%AD-luce-m%C3%A9xico-por-el-el9nadiesemueve/ar-BB10WyzH \"Today, they did not arrive\": This is how Mexico looks for # El9NadieSeMueve] {{in lang|es}} by Gustavo \u00c1lvarez, 24 Horas, 9 Mar 2020  [https://www.msn.com/es-mx/noticias/mexico/paro-de-mujeres-paraliza-la-c%c3%a1mara-de-diputados/ar-BB10XzHs Women's strike paralyzes the Chamber of Deputies] by Fernando Dami\u00e1n, Milenio, 9 Mar 2020  [https://www.msn.com/es-mx/video/noticias/cierran-sucursales-bancarias-ante-paro-de-mujeres/vi-BB10X1gh Bank branches closed in response to women's strike] {{in lang|es}} La Jornada, 9 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n====United States====\n{{see also|Presidency of Donald Trump|Timeline of the Donald Trump presidency (2020 Q1)|116th United States Congress|2020 United States presidential election|2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|2020 United States federal budget}}\n\nThe [[Impeachment of Donald Trump]] and the [[2020 United States presidential election]] dominate the first year of the decade. Foreign policy concerns are primarily related to trade and tariffs, disengagement from the Middle East, and [[Iran\u2013United States relations]]. Domestic issues include gun control and gun rights, immigrations, student loan debt, health care, climate change, and abortion rights.<ref>{{cite web|website=U.S. News|title=America 2020|accessdate=25 Jan 2020 |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/elections}}</ref> [[Baby boomers|As the nation ages]], funding of [[Social programs in the United States|social programs]] and the national debt ($23 trillion in January 2020) will be major concerns in the decade to come.<ref>{{cite web|website=Reason|title=The 2020s Will Be the Decade of Deficit Doomsday|author=Eric Boehm|date=Jan 10, 2020 |url=https://reason.com/2020/01/10/in-the-2020s-dealing-with-the-national-debt-will-no-longer-be-optional/}}</ref>\n\n===South America===\n<!----\n{{collapse top|title=South America|expand=yes}}\n---->\n\nWomen's rights, including [[Abortion-rights movements|the right to abortion]] and concerns about [[femicide]] and [[rape]] are major concerns throughout the region. Improvements on environmental issues have been tied to international trade agreements.<ref name=al_stories />\n\n====Argentina====\n[[Argentina|Argentina's]] economy faces major problems of debt, inflation, and growing poverty. Vice President [[Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez de Kirchner]] is on trial for corruption.<ref name=al_stories />\n\n====Bolivia====\nAfter the contested [[2019 Bolivian general election]] and the subsequent [[2019 Bolivian political crisis|political crisis]], Bolivia struggles to restore democracy.<ref name=al_stories />\n\nBolivians are now protesting against the opposition movement, as they feel that the movement's leaders have failed to unify in support of one credible candidate who could replace the current leaders.<ref>[https://www.france24.com/en/20200212-anger-in-bolivia-as-anti-morales-bloc-splinters-before-may-polls Anger in Bolivia as anti-Morales bloc splinters before May polls] Feb. 12, 2020, France 24 website. </ref>\n\nIn early 2020, [[MIT]] released a study which cast major doubts on the claims in 2019 by the [[Organization of American States|OAS]] which asserted that massive election fraud had occurred, and which were responsible for compelling President [[Evo Morales]] to step down from office. <ref> [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/28/world/americas/bolivia-election-fraud.html .I.T. Researchers Cast Doubt on Bolivian Election Fraud]. An international audit said officials had engaged in lies and manipulation to assure victory for Evo Morales. Academics at M.I.T.\u2019s Election Data and Science Lab questioned that finding. By Julie Turkewitz, Feb. 28, 2020. NY Times </ref><ref> [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/02/26/bolivia-dismissed-its-october-elections-fraudulent-our-research-found-no-reason-suspect-fraud/ Bolivia dismissed its October elections as fraudulent. Our research found no reason to suspect fraud.] Bolivians will hold a new election in May \u2014 without ousted president Evo Morales. By John Curiel and Jack R. Williams, Feb. 27, 2020. Washington Post. </ref><ref> [https://theglobepost.com/2020/02/27/mit-no-evidence-of-fraud-bolivia-election/ MIT Researchers Find No Evidence of Fraud in Bolivia\u2019s October Election] by Bryan Bowman  February 27, 2020. The Globe Post, Canada.</ref><ref>[https://www.salon.com/2020/02/28/mit-study-right-wing-coup-in-bolivia-was-based-on-false-claims-of-election-fraud_partner/ MIT study: Right-wing coup in Bolivia was based on false claims of election fraud U.S. media and politicians largely backed the overthrow of leftist president Evo Morales \u2014 but the excuse was BS], by EOIN HIGGINS, FEBRUARY 28, 2020, salon.com </ref><ref>[https://cepr.net/press-release/new-study-finds-no-evidence-of-oas-fraud-claims-very-likely-evo-morales-won-bolivias-october-elections-in-the-first-round/ MIT statisticians confirm findings of CEPR Study [on Bolivian election], CEPR article. </ref>\n\n====Brazil====\nEntering its second year in power, the [[Presidency of Jair Bolsonaro]] struggles with its fight against corruption and crime while being under fire for its anti-environmentalist policies and its handling of the [[2019 Amazon rainforest wildfires]].<ref name=al_stories />\n\n====Chile====\n{{see also|2019\u201320 Chilean protests}}\nAfter turbulence in [[2019\u201320 Chilean protests|2019]] in which 25 people died and 2,300 were injured by security forces, as well as arbitrary arrests of children and torture, Chile struggles to regain popular trust in the military, police, and the media.<ref name=al_stories>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/latin-america-2020-stories-watch-191202204939337.html Latin America in 2020: Stories to watch] by Charlotte Mitchell, Al Jazeera, 2 Jan 2020, Retrieved 24 Jan 2020</ref>\n\n====Colombia====\n{{see also|2019\u201320 Colombian protests}}\nThe 2019\u201320 Colombian protests are a collection of ongoing protests that began on 21 November 2019. Hundreds of thousands of [[Colombians]] demonstrated for various reasons. Some protested against various proposed economic and political reforms proposed by the [[Government of Colombia|government]] of [[Iv\u00e1n Duque M\u00e1rquez]], others against the few violent protestors and in favor of the [[Colombian peace process]], etc. <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/21/americas/colombia-national-strike-intl/index.html|title=Colombia protests prompt teargas, curfew and border closures|last=|first=|date=22 November 2019|website=[[CNN]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n\nWhile mostly peaceful in nature, a few violent incidents took place throughout the protests, leading to overnight [[curfew]]s in [[Cali]] and [[Bogot\u00e1]]. It is \"one of the largest mass demonstrations Colombia has witnessed in recent years\".<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5737190/colombia-protests/|title=Hundreds of Thousands Protested Colombia's Conservative Government. Here's What to Know|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref>\n\n====Peru====\n{{see also|2017\u201320 Peruvian political crisis|2020 Peruvian parliamentary election}} \n\nThe fallout from the [[Operation Car Wash|Odebrecht scandal]] and corruption investigations into opposition leader [[Keiko Fujimori]] and past presidents [[Pedro Pablo Kuczynski]] (2016\u201318), [[Ollanta Humala]] (2011\u201316), [[Alejandro Toledo]] (2001\u201306), and the late [[Alan Garcia]] (1985\u201390 and 2006\u201311) continue.<ref name=al_stories />\n\nEarly parliamentary elections were held in [[Peru]] on 26 January 2020.<ref name=LAT>[https://latinamericareports.com/perus-political-storm-a-timeline-of-events/3375/ Peru\u2019s political storm: a timeline of events] Los Angeles Times, 4 October 2019</ref> The elections were called after President [[Mart\u00edn Vizcarra]] dissolved the [[Congress of the Republic of Peru|Congress of the Republic]] on 30 September 2019.<ref name=LAT/>\n\nAll 130 congressmen corresponding to the 26 electoral districts will be elected to office for the remainder of the 2016\u20132021 congressional period. It was the seventh parliamentary election under the 1993 Constitution, which created the current Congress of the Republic of Peru.\n\n====Venezuela====\n{{see also|2020 Venezuelan presidential crisis}}\n\n[[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] or [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]]? Two leaders struggle for the leadership of beleaguered Venezuela. No matter the political solution, the winner will have to deal with a devastated economy.<ref name=al_stories />\n<!----\n{{collapse bottom}}\n--->\n\n===Oceania and Australia===\n====Australia====\nThe [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season]] was particularly destructive, killing at least 28 and destroying no fewer than 3,000 homes. The fires were widespread, but [[New South Wales|New South Wales (NSW)]] was the hardest hit. In December 2019 the smoke around [[Sydney]] was so bad that air quality was 11 times the \"hazardous\" level and temperatures were over 40&nbsp;\u00b0C (113\u00b0-120&nbsp;\u00b0F). Natural causes such as [[lightning strike]]s started most of the fires, which were exasperated by dry conditions and [[Drought in Australia|drought]], although police in NSW arrested at least 24 people for deliberately starting fires. In total, 7.3 million hectares (17.9 million acres) have burned across Australia's six states\u2014an area larger than [[Belgium]] and [[Denmark]] combined. Experts estimate 500 million animals died, not including bats, frogs, or insects; one-third of Australia's [[koala]]s were killed, according to [[Minister for the Environment (Australia)|Minister for the Environment]] [[Sussan Ley]].<ref>{{cite web|website=CNN World|title=Australia's deadly wildfires are showing no signs of stopping. Here's what you need to know |date=Jan 14, 2020|accessdate=Feb 8, 2020|author=Jessie Yeung|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/01/australia/australia-fires-explainer-intl-hnk-scli/index.html}}</ref>\n\n==History by issues and global trends ==\n\n===Climate change===\n{{See also|2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season}}\nThe [[United Nations]] calls climate change \"the defining issue of our time\",<ref>[https://www.un.org/en/sections/issues-depth/climate-change/ Climate Change] United Nations, retrieved 14 Jan 2020</ref> and the [[World Health Organization]] says it \"threatens the essential ingredients of good health - clean air, safe drinking water, nutritious food supply, and safe shelter - and has the potential to undermine decades of progress in global health\".<ref>[https://www.who.int/health-topics/climate-change#tab=tab_1 Climate change] World Health Organization, 14 Jan 2020</ref> 55% of American adult voters consider climate change an important issue in the [[2020 United States presidential election]].<ref>[https://news.gallup.com/poll/276932/several-issues-tie-important-2020-election.aspx Several Issues Tie as Most Important in 2020 Election] [[Gallup (company)|Gallup]], 13 January 2020</ref>\n\nThe environmental website ''Business Green'' predicts that the [[2020 United States presidential election]] will be crucial to action on climate change. Incumbent Republican President [[Donald Trump]] has already pulled out of the [[Paris Agreement]] and he continues to deny climate change,<ref>[https://insideclimatenews.org/news/19122019/trump-climate-policy-record-rollback-fossil-energy-history-candidate-profile Donald Trump's Record on Climate Change] by Stacey Feldman & Marianne Lavelle, Inside Climate News, 19 Dec 2019</ref> but his [[2020 Democratic Party presidential candidates|various Democratic opponents]] all support some kind of action on the issue.<ref>[https://www.vox.com/2019/9/10/20851109/2020-democrats-climate-change-plan-president A guide to how 2020 Democrats plan to fight climate change] By Umair Irfan, [[Vox (website)|Vox]], 19 Dec 2019</ref> The [[2019 United Nations Climate Change Conference|2019 United Nations Climate Change Conference (COP25)]] was not seen as successful, and COP26 may be just as fruitless. Electric vehicles are likely to offer the cheapest option in a few years, and many energy-inefficient businesses will probably go bankrupt. \"Peak meat\" may come about in the middle of the decade as consumers look for vegetarian alternatives. As renewable energy becomes less expensive, the demand for new technologies, such as long-lasting batteries and carbon storage will soar. Solid, particularly plastic, waste disposal will become a greater problem as many countries ban plastic waste imports and the petroleum industry changes from energy production to [https://webstore.iea.org/download/summary/190?fileName=English-WEO-2018-ES.pdf other uses of petrochemicals.pdf].<ref>{{cite web|website=GreenBiz|title=10 key trends to watch for the 2020s|author=Madeline Cuff|date=Jan 6, 2020|accessdate=Feb 1, 2020 |url=https://www.greenbiz.com/article/10-key-trends-watch-2020s}}</ref>\n\nA February 2020 study at the [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]] predicts that 70% to 90% of [[coral]] habitats will be destroyed by 2100.<ref>[https://www.theinertia.com/environment/scientists-predict-90-of-coral-reefs-will-disappear-by-2100/ Scientists Predict 90% of Coral Reefs Will Disappear By 2100] by Juan Hernandez, The Inertia, 18 Feb 2020</ref> The United Nations issued a statement in March 2020 stating that climate change is more mortal than [[COVID-19]], pointing out the loss of farmland, the effect of hurricanes and heatwaves, and the increase in diseases such as dengue. 100 people died and 18,000 were hospitalized in Japan while France reported 1,462 heat-related deaths in 2019. 2,800,000 people came down with dengue, leading to 1,250 deaths.<ref>[https://news.un.org/es/story/2020/03/1470901?fbclid=IwAR21rjJt1o_f8bsadkE61qoCzaqnkp3CRqBNIygsgBRHf0OCLbgXffn7Ins Climate change is more deadly than coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} United Nations News, 10 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n===Human rights===\n[[Heidi Hautala]], a [[member of the European Parliament]], writes that [[Slavery in the 21st century|40 million slaves]] in the world generate an estimated US$150 billion in profits a year and that purchasing products made with slave labor is legal in most European markets. She called upon the EU to lead in ending child labor and slave labor.<ref>[https://www.business-humanrights.org/en/responsible-business-conduct-the-european-business-model-of-the-2020s Responsible Business Conduct - the European Business model of the 2020s] Business & Human Rights Resource Centre, retrieved 1 Feb 2020</ref> [[Craig Kielburger]], founder of [[WE (organization)|WE]], sees mental health, data and privacy issues, and corporate social responsibility as human rights issues of the 2020s.<ref>[https://www.we.org/en-CA/we-stories/opinion/craig-kielburger-issues-that-will-define-the-next-decade-2020s What will define the next decade?] by Craig Kielburger, WE.org, retrieved 1 Feb 2020</ref> [[Alex Neve]] of [[Amnesty International|Amnesty International Canada]] and [[June Oscar]], a [[Bunuba|Bunuba aboriginal woman from Australia]] make the case for increased attention to indigenous rights in the 2020s.<ref>[https://www.thestar.com/opinion/contributors/2020/01/07/canada-human-rights-and-a-new-decade-time-to-dig-deeper-than-ever.html Canada, human rights and a new decade: time to dig deeper than ever] By Alex Neve, The Star (Toronto, Canada), 7 Jan 2020  [https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/31/june-oscars-2020s-vision-reaching-our-potential-as-a-nation-begins-with-truth-telling June Oscar's 2020s vision: Reaching our potential as a nation begins with truth-telling] by June Oscar, The Guardian (Australia), 30 Jan 2020</ref>\n\nThe [[Human Rights Watch]] [https://www.hrw.org/sites/default/files/supporting_resources/hrw_world_report_2019_etr_0.pdf World Report 2019.pdf] addresses human rights issues in [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemen]], Hungary, Syria, Venezuela, Philippines, Democratic Republic of Congo, China, United States, Myanmar, Turkey, Egypt, and Russia. They highlight immigration (including [[Trump administration family separation policy|family separation]]), religious oppression, food and medicine shortages, war and [[Chemical weapon proliferation|chemical weapons]], and a lack of democracy.<ref>[https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2019# WORLD REPORT 2019] by Kenneth Roth, Executive Director, Human Rights Watch, retrieved 1 Feb 2020</ref> [[Amnesty International|Amnesty International's]] top goals are to make [[same-sex relationship]]s legal, [[Abortion-rights movements|legalize abortion]], and [[Capital punishment by country|abolish the death penalty]] in all countries.'''\n\n====Women's rights====\nThe [[World Economic Forum]] published a report on the global gender gap in January 2020 that concludes gender parity will not be reached for 99.5 years. The report benchmarks 153 countries in four dimensions: Economic Participation and Opportunity, Educational Attainment, Health and Survival, and Political Empowerment. The top-ranking country for parity is [[Iceland]], and [[Albania]], [[Ethiopia]], [[Mali]], [[Mexico]], and [[Spain]] are the most improved. At least 35 countries have achieved gender parity in education, and 71 have closed at least 97% of the gap in health. Political empowerment remains poor\u201485 countries have never had a female head of state and women hold only 25% of all available positions, while eight countries have no women in government at all. Globally, only 55% of women (ages 15\u201364) are economically active, compared to 78% of men. 72 countries do not allow women to open bank accounts or obtain credit.<ref>{{cite web|website=World Economic Forum|title=Report: Mind the 100 Year Gap|accessdate=25 Jan 2020|language=en|url=https://www.weforum.org/reports/gender-gap-2020-report-100-years-pay-equality}}</ref>\n\nWriting on ''The European Sting,'' [[Saadia Zahidi]] writes there are three areas where the most can be done to close the gender gap. She says that businesses must take the lead, claiming that the most diverse companies are ones that have the best long-term performance. Second, she calls for both policy incentives and political role-models. \"As more women reach visible positions of power, it creates a virtuous cycle, normalizing the association of women and leadership for future generations. The role-model effect is already visible: countries with higher levels of women in political power also tend to have higher levels of women in business leadership,\" she writes. Third, she says we have a unique window to use education to train [[women in STEM fields]].<ref>{{cite web|website=European Sting|title=3 ways to make the 2020s the decade we close the gender gap|date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://europeansting.com/2019/12/18/3-ways-to-make-the-2020s-the-decade-we-close-the-gender-gap/}}</ref>\n\n===Technology===\nTrends in technology include greater use of [[Artificial intelligence|artificial intelligence (AI)]], [[Self-driving car|autonomous vehicles (AV)]], [[virtual reality]], a ten-year human [[Life expectancy|lifespan]] increase (due to better drugs, stem cell manipulation, and gene therapy), renewable and [[sustainable energy]], and space (commercialization, weaponization, and exploration).<ref>[http://connectedfuture.economist.com/connecting-capabilities/article/five-technologies-youll-use-2020s/ Five technologies you\u2019ll use in the 2020s] The Economist, Retrieved 16 Jan 2020  [https://singularityhub.com/2020/01/10/20-tech-metatrends-to-look-out-for-in-the-2020s/ 20 Technology Metatrends That Will Define the Next Decade] By Peter H. Diamandis, MD, Singularity Hub, 16 Jan 2020  [https://www.prweek.com/article/1670682/20-trends-2020s 20 trends for the 2020s] by Robert Moran, Brunswick Group, PR Week, 14 January 2020</ref>\n\nIn a January 2020 interview with ''[[Financial Times|the Financial Times]]'', German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] urged Europe to develop its own technology, such as [[List of battery types|manufacturing of batteries]], electric cars, and [[cloud computing]]. Europe depends mostly on Asia for electric car batteries, and it has no [[hyperscale computing]] companies to support companies like [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] and [[Facebook Platform|Facebook]].<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/16/tech/angela-merkel-tech-europe/index.html Angela Merkel: Europe should make its own chips and electric car batteries] By Charles Riley, CNN Business, 16 Jan 2020</ref>\n\n[[Switzerland|Switzerland's]] neutrality was called into question when it was in revealed in February 2020 that German and U.S. intelligence services had been using coding devices manufactured by [[Crypto AG]] to spy on other countries.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51487856 Swiss Crypto AG spying scandal shakes reputation for neutrality] BBC World, 16 Feb 2020</ref>\n\n===World banking and finance===\n====trends====\n[[BofA Securities]] analysts say a range of economic and social challenges are \"all heading to a boiling point\" in the 2020s. They predict peak [[globalization]] (including the trade wars between China and the U.S. and between [[2019 Japan\u2013South Korea trade dispute|South Korea and Japan]]), disruptive [[Demography|demographics]] (as people over-65 outnumber children under-5 for the first time), rising interest rates, and [[global warming]]. They predict that automation will return manufacturing away from low-income countries to countries of consumption. They predict higher inflation and outperformance by global equities and commodities versus bonds. They note that during the 2010s the \"economic spoils went to holders of capital, not workers,\" which is why interest rates will increase. The investment bank says that climate action could be transformative in energy, farming, transportation, and even globalization, adding \"Bold climate action could yield a direct economic gain of $US26 trillion through to 2030 compared with business as usual.\" Retailers may be hit hard as [[conspicuous consumption]] ends and sharing and [[Circular economy|circular economies]] become more popular.<ref>[https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-13/the-2020s-set-to-be-an-economic-turning-point/11699386 The 2020s are set to be an economic turning point, says global banking giant] By business reporter Michael Janda, ABC.net.au, 13 Nov 2019</ref>\n====history====\nIn 2020, concerns about corona virus caused major downturns in economic stock indexes.\n\n===World trade===\n[[Trump tariffs|Trump's trade wars]] appear to be drawing to a close as an agreement with [[China\u2013United States trade war|China]] and the ratification of the [[United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement]] approach.  Tomasz Brodzicki of [[IHS Markit]] predicts that world merchandise trade volume will increase by 2.7% to 14.175 billion tons (US$18.870 trillion) in 2020 and by 5% to 14.881 billion tons (US$19.795 trillion) in 2021. He forecasts the highest growth rates in 2020 for South and North America and the lowest for Africa. He predicts low trade growth for the U.S. and Canada and continuing conflicts with China, which should benefit [[Taiwan]], [[Vietnam]], and other parts of the [[ASEAN Free Trade Area]]. He also says the paralysis of the multilateral dispute settlement system in the [[World Trade Organization|World Trade Organization (WTO)]] will probably last.<ref name=tomasz>[https://ihsmarkit.com/research-analysis/outlook-for-global-trade-in-2020.html Outlook for Global Trade in 2020] Author: Tomasz Brodzicki, Ph.D., Senior Economist II, IHS Markit Maritime & Trade, 2 Jan 2020</ref>\n\nThe [[African Continental Free Trade Area |African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCTA)]] will go fully into effect on July 1, 2020, abolishing 90% of tariffs between member states and bringing a 50% increase in trade in the next few years.<ref name=hammond /> In June 2019 the [[Mercosur]] (Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay, and Uruguay) reached a [https://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2019/640138/EPRS_BRI(2019)640138_EN.pdf tentative agreement.pdf] with the [[European Union]]. They are also looking forward to similar agreements with the United States, Canada, and the EFTA bloc\u2014made up of [[Iceland]], [[Norway]], [[Liechtenstein]], and [[Switzerland]].<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mercosur-summit-argentina/south-american-bloc-eyes-fast-track-for-eu-trade-deal-idUSKCN1UC1PL South American bloc eyes fast-track for EU trade deal] by Maximilian Heath, Reuters Business News, 17 July 2019</ref>\n\nVarious analysts focused on the preservation and expansion of free trade; e.g., [[Michael Hirsh (journalist)|Michael Hirsh]] at ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' asserted that globalism and free trade would expand, despite the efforts of [[Donald Trump]] and other opponents of free trade.<ref>[https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/12/27/why-liberal-international-order-will-endure-next-decade-2020-democracy/ Why the Liberal International Order Will Endure Into the Next Decade] By Michael Hirsh, Foreign Policy, 27 Dec 2019, retrieved 2 March 2020</ref> Hirsh notes that despite Brexit, UK Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] remains committed to [[free trade]]. He also notes that other countries are expanding their efforts to increase trade.<ref>{{cite web|website=Foreign Policy|title=Why the Liberal International Order Will Endure Into the Next Decade|date=Dec 27, 2019|author=Michael Hirsh|accessdate=Feb 1, 2020|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/12/27/why-liberal-international-order-will-endure-next-decade-2020-democracy/}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{collapse top|See also}}\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n\n;General overviews\n* [[2020s]]\n* [[21st century]]\n* [[List of protests in the 21st century]]\n\n;Timeline articles for current year\n* [[2020]]\n* [[2020 in politics and government]]\n* [[2020 in science]]\n;Specific issues and topics\n* [[Brexit negotiations]]\n* [[Coronavirus disease 2019]]\n\n;Overviews and historical topics for this period\n* [[Premiership of Boris Johnson]]\n* [[Presidency of Donald Trump]]\n{{Col-break}}\n;Country and regional entries and timelines\n* [[2020 in the United States]]\n* [[2020 in United States politics and government]]\n* [[2020 in the Caribbean]]\n* [[2020 in Central America]]\n* [[2020 in East Africa]]\n* [[2020 in West Africa]]\n{{cat see also|2020 by country}}\n\n;Related decade overviews\n* 2020s decade overviews:\n**[[2020s in United Kingdom political history]]\n**[[Draft:2020s in United States political history]]\n* Related decade overviews: \n**[[2010s political history]]\n**[[2010s in United Kingdom political history]]\n**[[Draft:2010s in United States political history]]\n;Categories\n{{cat see also|21st-century social movements|Category:21st-century conflicts}}\n{{cat see also|2020s|2020s in politics|2020s economic history}}\n{{cat see also|2020|2020 in politics|2020 by country|2020 in law}}\n\n\n{{Col-break}}\n{{portal|Current events|Countries|Modern history|Africa|Asia|Europe|North America|South America|Oceania}}\n{{col end}}\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Collapse top|News outlets and informational sites}}\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n;World news sites\n*[https://www.realclearworld.com/ Real Clear World], news and commentary items from publications around the world\n*[https://twitter.com/ Twitter]\n\n;Europe\nChris Edwards of ''Global Horizons'' recommends eight international news sources:<ref>[http://natoassociation.ca/8-useful-world-news-sources/ 8 Useful World News Sources] Chris Edwards of global Horizons, NATO Association, 29 Aug 2013</ref>\n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/world BBC World News page], world news with a British/Western perspective\n*[https://www.economist.com/ The Economist], London-based economics news\nIn addition to the [[BBC World Service]], ''[[Esquire (magazine)]]'' recommends:<ref>[https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a5800/world-news-032509/ The Foreign Media: Four Sites That Do It Better Than We Do] BY TIM HEFFERNAN, Esquire, 25 Mar 2009</ref>\n*[https://www.spiegel.de/international/ Der Spiegel International (in English)], a European perspective\n*[https://iwpr.net/ The Institute for War and Peace Reporting]\n*[https://www.crisisgroup.org/ International Crisis Group]\n*[https://www.france24.com/en/ France 24 (TV network)], owned by the government of [[France 24|France]]\n\n;North America\n;;Wire services and capsulized news sites\n*[https://www.reuters.com/ Reuters wire service], New York City-based with mostly international and financial news\n*[https://www.ap.org/en-us/ The Associated Press wire service], New York-based wire service\n*[https://www.bloomberg.com/ Bloomberg News], financial and general news (paywall)\n*[https://edition.cnn.com/world CNN world news (TV network)], Atlanta-based with wide coverage, [[CNN International]]\n;Conventional newspaper and magazine websites\n*[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/ The Globe and Mail], Canadian and international news\n*[https://www.wsj.com/ The Wall Street Journal], business and general news (paywall)\n*[https://www.washingtonpost.com/ The Washington Post], U.S. political and general news (paywall)\n*[https://www.newyorker.com/ The New Yorker], in-depth reporting on news; also includes fiction (paywall)\n*[https://www.foreignaffairs.com/ Foreign Affairs magazine], premier U.S. magazine for foreign affairs (paywall)\n*[https://www.theatlantic.com/world/ The Atlantic magazine], Washington-based with long feature articles and analysis\n*[https://www.politico.com/ Politico], politics\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/ New York Times] U.S. and world news (paywall)\n*[https://mexiconewsdaily.com/about/ Mexico News Daily], world news from Mexico\n{{Col-break}}\n;Africa\n*[https://allafrica.com/ allAfrica]\n\n;Asia/Mideast\n*[https://www.aljazeera.com/ Al Jazeera], the Middle East and world news\n* [https://www.arabnews.com/world Arab News world news page]\n*[https://www.scmp.com/news/china South China Morning Post]\n*[https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia Channel News Asia (CNA)], world news from [[CNA (news channel)|Singapore]]\n*[https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/index.html China Daily], owned by the government of [[China Daily|China]]\n*[https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-international/ The Hindu], world news from [[The Hindu|India]]\n*[https://www.rt.com/news/ RT (TV network)], owned by the government of [[RT (TV network)|Russia]]\n\n;South America\n* [https://brazilian.report/ The Brazilian Report].\n*[https://latinamericanpost.com/ Latin American Post], world news from Colombia\n\n;General recommendations\n''[[Forbes]]'' recommends:<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/berlinschoolofcreativeleadership/2017/02/01/10-journalism-brands-where-you-will-find-real-facts-rather-than-alternative-facts/#406355f9e9b5 10 Journalism Brands Where You Find Real Facts Rather Than Alternative Facts] By Paul Glader of The Berlin School of Creative Leadership, Forbes, retrieved 1 Feb 2020</ref>\n*''[[The New York Times]]'', the BBC, and [[Reuters]]\n\n;UN informational websites\n* [https://unstats.un.org/unsd/dnss/cp/searchcp.aspx United Nations Country Profiles website]\n* [https://data.un.org/en/index.html UN Data website, index by individual countries]\n* [http://hdr.undp.org/en/content/country-profiles Country Profiles] at website for [[UN Development Program (UNDP)]], Human Development Reports\n* [http://countrystudies.us/ Country Studies website]. on-line versions of US government books published between 1986 and 1998. \n* [https://www.unfpa.org/publications/country-profiles Country Profiles] at website of [[United Nations Population Fund]]. \n* [https://country-profiles.unstatshub.org/ Country index] at website of [[United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs]] (UN DESA)\n* [https://www.un.org/development/desa/en/about/desa-divisions.html Divisions of UN Department of Economic and Social Affairs]\n{{Col end}}\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n==References==\n{{collapse top|References}}\n<small>\n{{Reflist}}\n </small>\n{{collapse bottom}}\n{{2020s in political history}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Financial crises}}\n\n[[Category:2020s in politics| ]]\n[[Category:2020s|politics]]\n[[Category:2020s in international relations]]\n[[Category:Politics overviews by decade]]\n[[Category:2020 in politics]]\n[[Category:21st century in politics]]\n", "text_old": "{{see also|2010s in political history}}\n{{Decadebox|202}}\n{{Year nav topic5|2020|politics and government|science}}\n'''2020s political history''' refers to significant political and societal historical events of the 2020s, presented as a historical overview in narrative format.\n\n\n{{toc limit|3}}\n\n==World events==\n{{hatnote|Section for historical events of world significance. This section can be divided by time period; within each time period, there can be subsections for some topics. Even the most global issues involve events in various specific countries; therefore, for any lengthy world topics that encompass multiple countries and regions, a sub-section for that specific topic might be advisable; however, this is not required for every topic covered here.}}\n===General world events===\n{{empty section|date=March 2020}}\n\n\n===Coronavirus===\n{{main|Coronavirus disease 2019}}\n{{see also|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe}}\n\nIn early 2020, the spread of the [[coronavirus]] became an issue of global concern. The virus appeared to originate in [[Wuhan, China]]. \n\nIn Japan, all schools and colleges were closed in early March and were not to reopen again until April. New cases began to appear in Italy and elsewhere in Europe. In the United States, the first cases were reported in California and Oregon; some individuals in New York were isolated for evaluation.Several cruise ships were quarantined for weeks on end, due to concerns about the coronavirus spreading there.\n\nIn the last week of February 2020, the [[Dow Jones Index]]{{dn|date=April 2020}} experienced some of the biggest one-day drops in its history.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[Hand washing]], maintaining distance from people who are [[coughing]] and not touching one's face with unwashed hands are measures recommended to prevent the disease.<ref name=\"Advice for public\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public|title=Advice for public|website=www.who.int|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126025750/https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public|archive-date=26 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It is recommended to cover one's nose and mouth with a tissue or a bent elbow when coughing.<ref name=\"Advice for public\" /> The [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) and U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) recommend those who suspect that they are carrying the virus wear a [[Surgical mask|surgical face mask]] and seek medical advice by calling a doctor rather than directly visiting a clinic in person. Masks are also recommended for those who are taking care of someone with a suspected infection but not for the general public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/steps-when-sick.html|title=2019 Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV)|last=CDC|date=2020-02-11|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214153016/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/steps-when-sick.html|archive-date=14 February 2020|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public|title=Advice for public|website=www.who.int|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126025750/https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public|archive-date=26 January 2020|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> There is no [[vaccine]] or specific [[antiviral treatment]], with management involving treatment of symptoms, [[supportive care]], and experimental measures.<ref name=\"cdc21Jan20202\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/prevention-treatment.html|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)|date=15 February 2020|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC)|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226145347/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/prevention-treatment.html|archive-date=26 February 2020|access-date=20 February 2020}}</ref> The [[case fatality rate]] is estimated at between 1% and 3%.<ref name=\"worldometers.info\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/coronavirus-death-rate/#ref-6|title=Wuhan Coronavirus Death Rate - Worldometer|website=www.worldometers.info|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131223143/https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/coronavirus-death-rate/#ref-6|archive-date=31 January 2020|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-2019-nCoV-severity-10-02-2020.pdf|title=Report 4: Severity of 2019-novel coronavirus (nCoV)|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210105717/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-2019-nCoV-severity-10-02-2020.pdf|archive-date=10 February 2020|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Epidemiology and history -->\nThe WHO has declared the 2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak to be a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]] (PHEIC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|title=Statement on the second meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV)|website=www.who.int|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131005904/https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | vauthors = Mahtani S, Berger M, O'Grady S, Iati M | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/coronavirus-china-live-updates/2020/02/05/114ced8a-479c-11ea-bc78-8a18f7afcee7_story.html | title = Hundreds of evacuees to be held on bases in California; Hong Kong and Taiwan restrict travel from mainland China | work = The Washington Post | date = 6 February 2020 | access-date = 11 February 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200207134650/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/coronavirus-china-live-updates/2020/02/05/114ced8a-479c-11ea-bc78-8a18f7afcee7_story.html | archive-date = 7 February 2020 | url-status = live }}</ref> As of 29 February 2020, [[China]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Iran]], [[Italy]], [[Japan]], [[Singapore]], [[South Korea]] and the [[United States]] are areas having evidence of [[community transmission]] of the disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/areas-presumed-ongoing-community-transmission-2019-ncov|title=Areas with presumed ongoing community transmission of 2019-nCoV|website=European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control |access-date=2020-02-28|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200219092151/https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/areas-presumed-ongoing-community-transmission-2019-ncov |archive-date=28 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"cnn2-29\">{{cite news |author1=Christina Maxouris |author2=Dakin Andone |title=First death from coronavirus in the United States confirmed in Washington state, officials say |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/29/health/us-coronavirus-saturday/index.html |accessdate=29 February 2020 |work=CNN - Health |date=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Italy announced that is closing ''all'' schools and colleges due to coronavirus. <ref> [https://www.bbc.com/news/live/world-51734185 Italy confirms earlier reports it is closing schools and universities until mid-March], BBC, March 4,2020. </ref> The total cases worldwide were announced to have risen to 93,000. Saudi Arabia announced it would suspend the traditional umrah pilgrimage. <ref> [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-03/u-s-death-toll-rises-to-9-more-travel-curbs-seen-virus-update N.Y. Patient\u2019s Family, Driver Infected; U.K. Surge: Virus Update], Bloomberg News, March 3, 2020, Updated on March 4, 2020. </ref> France closed 120 schools due to the coronavirus. <ref>  [https://www.marketwatch.com/story/france-germany-close-schools-in-virus-cluster-zones-2020-03-03 France closes 120 schools because of the coronavirus, sending home tens of thousands of students] Mar 3, 2020, France\u2019s education minister closed schools mostly in Brittany and the Oise region north of Paris, which have been hit hard by COVID-19. marketwatch.com. </ref> France reported that it had 257 cases of the illness. <ref> [https://www.thelocal.fr/20200301/latest-number-of-coronavirus-cases-in-france-rises-to-130 LATEST: France confirms new total of 257 coronavirus cases and new cluster zones] The Local, 1 March 2020. </ref> Cases increased across Europe. <ref> [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/01/coronavirus-deaths-iran-rise-global-outbreak-worsens New coronavirus cases jump sharply in Europe, with Italy worst hit] Italian death toll now 34, German cases nearly double, and South Korea and Iran also struggle to contain outbreak. by Peter Beaumont in London, Lily Kuo in Beijing, Kim Willsher in Paris and Angela Giuffrida in Rome, March 1, 2020, The Guardian. </ref> Tourist attractions were closed throughout Asian countries. <ref> [https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/02/news/coronavirus-closures-tourist-attractions-and-events/index.html Attractions closed and events canceled amid coronavirus outbreak], by Stacey Lastoe, CNN Updated 9:20 AM ET, Wed March 4, 2020. </ref> Israel and some other countries canceled some foreign flights from some countries. <ref> [https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/03/04/coronavirus-live-updates/ Live updates: Four new coronavirus cases in New York as U.S. braces for more disruption], Washington Post. </ref> Iran reported a rise in cases. <ref> [https://www.france24.com/en/20200303-iran-to-mobilise-army-against-coronavirus-as-death-toll-reaches-77 Iran to mobilise army against coronavirus as death toll tops 75], March 3, 2020. </ref> \n\nIn the United States, the CDC announced that the outbreak had spread, and reported 129 cases. The CDC warned local communities to look at methods to halt the spread. <ref> [https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/04/health/us-coronavirus-update-wednesday/index.html The US coronavirus death toll is rising and the CDC says communities should start thinking about ways to stop its spread.] By Christina Maxouris, CNN Updated 11:04 AM ET, Wed March 4, 2020. </ref>An [https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/us/coronavirus-us-cases.html interactive online map at the New York Times website] showed the rising numbers state by state. <ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/us/coronavirus-us-cases.html Interactive map], NY Times website. </ref> Experts said the outbreak might be potentially as bad as the outbreak of flu in 1957. <ref> [https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/how-bad-will-the-coronavirus-outbreak-get-in-the-us/ar-BB10HcuL How bad will the coronavirus outbreak get in the U.S.?], Joel Achenbach, Lenny Bernstein, Neena Satija, William Wan Washington Post via msn.com, March 4,2020. </ref> <ref> [https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2020/03/02/how-is-coronavirus-outbreak-going-end-heres-how-similar-epidemics-played-out/ How is the coronavirus outbreak going to end? Here\u2019s how similar epidemics played out.], by William Wan, Washington post, March 2, 2020. </ref>New cases were reported in California and Washington State. <ref> [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/04/world/coronavirus-news.html Coronavirus Live Updates], NY Times website. </ref>\n\n===Financial market problems===\n[[Black Monday (2020)|Black Monday]] was a global [[stock market crash]] on 9 March 2020 that occurred during the [[2020 stock market crash]].<ref name=S>Prynn, Jonathan, English, Simon, and Murphy, Joe.[https://standard.co.uk/news/politics/stock-markets-ftse-100-oil-prices-coronavirus-black-monday-a4382156.html \"Black Monday: Fourth biggest City fall as coronavirus panic hits markets\"], ''[[Evening Standard]]'', 9 March 2020. Retrieved 9 March 2020.</ref> Markets opened several percent lower, having fallen greatly during the preceding two weeks. Global stock markets suffered from the greatest single-day fall since 2008, during the [[Great Recession]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/09/global-stock-markets-post-biggest-falls-since-2008-financial-crisis|title=\nGlobal stock markets post biggest falls since 2008 financial crisis|date=9 March 2020|accessdate=10 March 2020|website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> This record crash was soon surpassed three days later on [[Black Thursday (2020)|Black Thursday]]. Notable contributing factors included the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]] and the [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war|Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war]].<ref name=S/><ref name=bbc>{{cite news |title=Black Monday: Shares face biggest fall since financial crisis |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-51796806 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |agency=BBC News |date=9 March 2020 |quote=Analysts described the market reaction as \"utter carnage\". |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309055650/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-51796806 |archive-date=9 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=cnbc>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/08/dow-futures-drop-700-points-as-all-out-oil-price-war-adds-to-coronavirus-stress.html|title=Dow sinks 2,000 points in worst day since 2008, S&P 500 drops more than 7%|last=Li|first=Yun|date=8 March 2020|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=10 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309155615/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/08/dow-futures-drop-700-points-as-all-out-oil-price-war-adds-to-coronavirus-stress.html|archive-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn the United States, a [[Trading curb|circuit breaker]] was triggered after stocks dropped sharply, halting trade for fifteen minutes.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-51796806|title=Global shares plunge in worst day since financial crisis|date=9 March 2020|accessdate=10 March 2020|website=[[BBC]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309150404/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-51796806|archive-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[FTSE 100 Index]] opened 560 points (8.6%) lower to 5920.<ref name=S/> Indices in Asia, continental Europe, and the United States also fell by several percent on the same day, with the worst affected, Italy's FTSE MIB, opening 11% lower.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/ftse-100-monday-latest-coronavirus-oil-price-markets-open-081657287.html|title=Oil and coronavirus fears spark 'Black Monday' for stock markets|website=finance.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=10 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309094632/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/ftse-100-monday-latest-coronavirus-oil-price-markets-open-081657287.html|archive-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Other financial market effects included a rush to the safety of [[government bond]]s as 10-year American Treasury yields fell below 0.5% for the first time ever, appreciation of the [[Japanese yen]], and [[Gold as an investment|gold]] rising above $1,700/ounce for the first time in seven years.<ref name=TheEconomist1>{{cite news|author= |title= Saudi-Russian price war sends oil and stockmarkets crashing|url= https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2020/03/09/saudi-russian-price-war-sends-oil-and-stockmarkets-crashing|work= [[The Economist]]|date= 9 March 2020|access-date= 9 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200309155422/https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2020/03/09/saudi-russian-price-war-sends-oil-and-stockmarkets-crashing|archive-date= 9 March 2020|url-status= live}}</ref> \n\nBlack Thursday <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/black-thursday-dow-suffers-biggest-201047970.html|title=Black Thursday: Dow Suffers Biggest Point Drop Ever, as Disney and Apple Fall Hard|website=[[Yahoo]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://business.inquirer.net/292328/psei-sees-worst-freefall-in-12-years|title=Black Thursday: PSEi sees worst freefall in 12 years|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|website=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|author=Doris Dumlao-Abadilla}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/business/2020/mar/12/pandemic-pandemonium-world-markets-crash-into-bear-country-on-black-thursday-2115906.html|title=Pandemic pandemonium: World markets crash into bear country on Black Thursday|website=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|author=Jonathan Ananda}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icis.com/explore/resources/news/2020/03/12/10481846/europe-crude-petchems-prices-extend-losses-as-stocks-suffer-black-thursday|title=Europe crude, petchems prices extend losses as stocks suffer 'Black Thursday'|author=Jonathan Lopez|website=Independent Commodity Intelligence Services|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> was a global [[stock market crash]] on March 12, 2020 as part of the greater [[2020 stock market crash]]. Global stock markets suffered from the greatest single-day fall since the [[Black Monday (1987)|1987 stock market crash]].<ref name=\"CNBC\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/11/futures-are-steady-wednesday-night-after-dow-closes-in-bear-market-traders-await-trump.html|title=Dow drops more than 8%, heads for biggest one-day plunge since 1987 market crash|website=[[CNBC]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|author1=Fred Imbert|author2=Thomas Franck}}</ref> Following [[Black Monday (2020)|Black Monday]] three days earlier, Black Thursday was attributed to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]] and a lack of investor confidence in US president [[Donald Trump]] after he imposed a 30-day [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|travel ban]] against the [[Schengen Area]].<ref name=\"NYT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/12/business/stock-market-today.html|title=Stocks Plunge as Trump\u2019s Travel Ban Adds to Distress: Live Updates|website=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History by region==\n\n===Asia===\n====Afghanistan====\nThe [[Afghan peace process]] comprises the proposals and negotiations in a bid to end the ongoing [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|war in Afghanistan]]. Although sporadic efforts have taken place since the war began in 2001, negotiations and the peace movement intensified in 2018 amid talks between the [[Taliban]], which is the main [[insurgent]] group fighting against the [[Afghan government]] and [[American troops]]; and the [[United States]], of which 20,000 soldiers maintain a presence within the country to support the Afghan government. Most of the talks have taken place in [[Doha]], the capital of [[Qatar]]. It is expected that a mutual agreement between the Taliban and the United States would be followed by a phased American withdrawal and the start of intra-Afghan peace talks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pajhwok.com/en/2019/01/24/hpc-welcomes-khalilzad%E2%80%99s-efforts-intra-afghan-talks|title=HPC welcomes Khalilzad's efforts for intra-Afghan talks|website=pajhwok.com}}</ref> Besides the United States, regional powers such as [[Pakistan]], [[China]] and [[Russia]], as well as [[NATO]] play a part in facilitating the peace process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/world/us-russia-china-pakistan-urge-taliban-to-agree-for-ceasefire-begin-talks-with-afghan-govt/article28423292.ece|title=US, Russia, China, Pakistan urge Taliban to agree for ceasefire, begin talks with Afghan govt|website=@businessline}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/india-not-excluded-from-peace-process-in-afghanistan-china-1569594-2019-07-15|title= not excluded from peace process in Afghanistan: China|website=India Today}}</ref>\n\nOn February 29, 2020, the U.S. signed a conditional peace agreement with the Taliban, which calls for the withdrawal of foreign troops in 14 months if the Taliban uphold the terms of the agreement.<ref name=proposedwithdrawal>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/afghanistan-us-taliban-peace-deal-signing/2020/02/29/b952fb04-5a67-11ea-8efd-0f904bdd8057_story.html |title=U.S. signs peace deal with Taliban agreeing to full withdrawal of American troops from Afghanistan |last=George |first=Susannah |date=February 29, 2020 |website=WashingtonPost.com}}</ref><ref name=stillproposedwithdrawal>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/us-strikes-deal-with-taliban-to-withdraw-troops-from-afghanistan/ar-BB10ym7c |title=U.S. Strikes Deal With Taliban to Withdraw Troops From Afghanistan |website=MSN.com |publisher=The New York Times |date=February 29, 2020 |last=Mashal |first=Mujib}}</ref> On March 1, 2020, however, the Afghan government, which was not a party to the deal, rejected the U.S. and Taliban's call for a prisoner swap by March 10, 2020, with President Ghani stating that such an agreement will require further negotiation and will also not be implemented as a precondition for future peace negotiations.<ref name=nprreject>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/01/810949474/afghan-president-rejects-timeline-for-prisoner-swap-proposed-in-us-taliban-peace|title=Afghan President Rejects Timeline For Prisoner Swap Proposed In US-Taliban Peace Deal|first=Cat|last=Schuknecht|publisher=NPR|date=March 1, 2020|accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=apreject>https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/01/afghan-peace-deal-prisoner-release-118473|title=Afghan peace deal hits first snag over prisoner releases|author=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=Politico|accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> <ref> [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51695370 Afghan conflict: President Ashraf Ghani rejects Taliban prisoner release], 1 March 2020, BBC. </ref><ref> [https://apnews.com/8cfce4344ad386697c78b033a3cb3dc6 Afghan peace deal hits first snag over prisoner releases], By KATHY GANNON, March 1, 2020, Associated Press. </ref> In March 2020, the Taliban announced they would resume hostilities with the Afghan Government if the prisoners were not released. <ref> [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51706126 Afghan conflict: Taliban to resume attacking local forces after deal with US], 2 March 2020, BBC. </ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51728326 Afghan conflict: Clashes shatter partial truce after US deal], 3 March 2020, BBC. </ref>\n\n====China====\nIn January 2020, China faced a major public health issue due to the effects of the [[2019\u201320 Coronavirus pandemic]], prompting worldwide health concerns about the potential impact of this disease. A drop in tourism<ref>{{cite web|website=Al Jazeera|title=Holiday cancelled? How the coronavirus is hurting tourism|author=Samantha Ho|date=Feb 6, 2020|accessdate=Feb 8, 2020 |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/ajimpact/holiday-cancelled-coronavirus-hurting-tourism-200205093345935.html}}</ref> and even an economic recession may result.<ref>{{cite web|website=CNBC |title=Coronavirus could easily tip China into a technical recession, economist warns|author=Chloe Taylor|date=Feb 4, 2020|accessdate=Feb 8, 2020 |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/04/coronavirus-could-tip-china-into-technical-recession-economist-warns.html}}</ref>\n\n====India====\n{{see also|Premiership of Narendra Modi|Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019#Protests|Citizenship Amendment Act protests}}\n\nThe Citizenship Amendment Act (Bill) protests occurred after the enactment of the [[Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019|Citizenship (Amendment) Act]] (CAA) by the Indian government on 12 December 2019, which triggered widespread ongoing protests across India and abroad against the act and the associated proposals to enact a [[National Register of Citizens]] (NRC).<ref name=\"hansindia\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehansindia.com/news/cities/hyderabad/student-unions-back-anti-citizenship-amendment-act-protests-590361|title=Student unions back anti Citizenship Amendment Act protests|last=India|first=The Hans|date=16 December 2019 |website=thehansindia.com |access-date=17 December 2019}}</ref> The protests began in [[Assam]],<ref name=\"India Today 12 Dec\">{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/mail-today/story/citizenship-bill-protests-here-why-assam-is-burning-1627538-2019-12-12|title=Citizenship Amendment Bill protests: Here's why Assam is burning|last1=Deka|first1=Kaushik|date=12 December 2019|work=India Today|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> [[Delhi]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/anti-citizenship-law-protests-latest-developments/articleshow/72683696.cms|title=Citizenship Amendment Bill 2019: Anti-citizenship law protests: Latest developments and reactions|date=16 December 2019|website=The Times of India|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref> [[Meghalaya]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/citizenship-bill-protests-violence-grips-assam-meghalaya-bengal-oppns-plans-mega-rally-2422713.html|title=Violence Grips Assam, Meghalaya, Bengal & Delhi as Protests Escalate Across India; Oppn Plans Mega Rally|website=News18|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref> [[Arunachal Pradesh]], and [[Tripura]] on 4 December 2019,<ref name=\"mamata rally\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/protests-and-strikes-hit-assam-manipur-tripura-against-cab/story-dPRUypEh1zaUzVOY86O7oK.html|title=Protests and strikes hit Assam, Manipur, Tripura against CAB|date=9 December 2019|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> and quickly spread across the country, although the concerns of the protesters vary.<ref name=\"AtlanticLate\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2019/12/india-citizenship-law-protest/603793/|title=When Is a Protest Too Late?|last=Serhan|first=Yasmeen|date=18 December 2019|website=The Atlantic|access-date=21 December 2019}}, Quote: \"Though the protesters in India share a common opposition to the new citizenship law, their reasons for rejecting the legislation vary.\"</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, a total of 46 people in New Delhi alone had been fatally injured due to the riots and disorder. <ref>[https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/death-toll-in-delhi-riots-rises-to-46-as-indias-capital-remains-on-edge/ Death Toll in Delhi Riots Rises to 46 as India\u2019s Capital Remains on Edge]. The Indian prime minister remains publicly silent on the violence. By Sheikh Saaliq. March 02, 2020. </ref> The riots in New Delhi were largely due to anti-Muslim sentiment. There were widespread reports of violence directed against Muslims. <ref> [https://time.com/5794354/delhi-riots-muslims-india/ Hate Is Being Preached Openly Against Us.' After Delhi Riots, Muslims in India Fear What's Next], BY SAMEER YASIR/DELHI AND BILLY PERRIGO, MARCH 3, 2020, time.com. </ref> <ref> [https://moderndiplomacy.eu/2020/03/02/trump-visits-modi-and-delhi-erupts-in-anti-muslim-riots/ Trump Visits Modi and Delhi Erupts in Anti-Muslim Riots], March 2, 2020 By Dr. Arshad M. Khan, moderndiplomacy.eu website. </ref> <ref> [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51719204 Delhi riots: How Muslims' homes were targeted and burnt], by Soutik Biswas, March 3, 2020. </ref> An Indian police officer was widely commended for risking his life to protect Muslims who were in danger. There were also various reports on individual Hindus who intervened to protect Muslims from mob violence. <ref> [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51670093 Delhi riots: 'Hero cop' who braved a mob to save lives], BBC, 28 February 2020. </ref> <ref> [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/01/india-delhi-after-hindu-mob-riot-religious-hatred-nationalists Inside Delhi: beaten, lynched and burnt alive], by Hannah Ellis-Petersen, Sun 1 Mar 2020, The Guardian. </ref> <ref> [https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2020/03/india-modi-hindu-muslim-delhi-riots/607315/ India Failed Delhi.] In failing to curb violence in its capital city, the country\u2019s government bears responsibility for it. by YASMEEN SERHAN, MARCH 2, 2020, theatlantic.com. </ref>\n\nVarious Muslim countries formally expressed concern. <ref> [https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/indonesia-condemns-anti-muslim-violence-in-india/1748804 Indonesia condemns anti-Muslim violence in India]. Indonesian Minister Razi urges New Delhi to protect Muslims and not harm them over differences in faith. Nicky Aulia Widadio, February 28, 2020. </ref>\n\nThe Amendment created a pathway to Indian citizenship for illegal migrants belonging to [[Hindus|Hindu]], [[Sikhs|Sikh]], [[Buddhist]], [[Jain]], [[Parsis|Parsi]], and [[Christians|Christian]] communities from [[Pakistan]], [[Bangladesh]] and [[Afghanistan]], who had entered India before 2014 fleeing religious persecution.<ref name=\"BBC explained\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-50670393 Citizenship Amendment Bill: India's new 'anti-Muslim' law explained], BBC News, 11 December 2019.</ref> The Amendment does not provide the same pathway to Muslims and others from these countries, nor to refugee [[Sri Lankan Tamils in India]], [[Rohingya]]s from [[Myanmar]], or [[Tibetan refugees in India|Buddhists from Tibet]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/a-dark-day-for-the-country-says-jamaat-chief/article30313127.ece|title=A dark day for the country, says Jamaat-e-Islami chief|last=Reporter|first=Staff|date=15 December 2019|work=The Hindu|access-date=17 January 2020|issn=0971-751X|quote=He said Tamil Hindus from Sri Lanka had been persecuted and questioned why they had not been brought under the ambit of the CAA}}{{subscription required}}</ref> The proposed [[National Register of Citizens]] (NRC) will be an official record of all legal citizens of India; individuals would need to provide a prescribed set of documents issued before a specified cutoff date to be included in it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/et-explains/is-a-pan-india-nrc-possible-the-lesson-from-assam/articleshow/72454225.cms?from=mdr|title=Understanding NRC: What it is and if it can be implemented across the country|date=23 December 2019|work=The Economic Times|access-date=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe amendment has been widely criticised as [[Religious discrimination|discriminating on the basis of religion]], in particular for excluding Muslims.<ref name=\"NPRExcludes\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/12/11/787220640/india-passes-controversial-citizenship-bill-that-would-exclude-muslims |title=India Passes Controversial Citizenship Bill That Would Exclude Muslims |newspaper=NPR.org |first=Sam |last=Gringlas}}</ref> Protestors against the amendment demand that it be scrapped and that the nationwide NRC not be implemented.<ref name=\"wsjdelhi\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/india-protests-against-new-law-spread-to-muslim-area-of-capital-11576596978|title=India Citizenship Protests Spread to Muslim Area of Capital|last=Pokharel|first=Krishna|website=WSJ|date=17 December 2019|access-date=17 January 2020|quote=Protests against a new citizenship law favoring non-Muslim immigrants erupted in violence in a Muslim-dominated part of the Indian capital [...] \"People are opposing this law because it discriminates against Muslims [...]}}</ref><ref name=\"Sigal Samuel\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2019/12/12/21010975/india-muslim-citizenship-bill-national-register|title=India just redefined its citizenship criteria to exclude Muslims|last=Samuel|first=Sigal|date=12 December 2019|website=Vox|access-date=17 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalheraldindia.com/politics/will-revoke-anti-poor-caa-nrc-if-voted-to-power-says-priyanka-gandhi-in-varanasi|title=Will revoke anti-poor CAA-NRC if voted to power, says Priyanka Gandhi in Varanasi|website=National Herald|language=en|access-date=26 January 2020}}</ref> They are concerned that Muslim citizens of India, as well as poor Indians, will be rendered [[Statelessness|stateless]] and put into [[detention camp]]s by the proposed nationwide NRC in combination with the CAA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india-today-insight/story/everything-you-wanted-to-know-about-the-caa-and-nrc-1630771-2019-12-23|title=Everything you wanted to know about the CAA and NRC|date=23 December 2019|first=Kaushik |last=Deka|website=India Today|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/all-you-need-to-know-about-proposed-pan-india-nrc/articleshow/72671119.cms|title=Know the difference between NRC and CAA Bill 2019|date=23 December 2019|work=The Economic Times|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5752186/india-protests-citizenship-act/|title=How a New Law in India Sparked Mass Protests and a Brutal Police Clampdown|website=Time|access-date=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/chandigarh/chandigarh-caa-is-essentially-anti-poor-says-former-ias-officer-kannan-gopinathan-6202416/|title=Chandigarh: CAA is essentially anti-poor, says former IAS officer Kannan Gopinathan|date=6 January 2020|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=26 January 2020}}</ref> They are also concerned that all citizens will be affected by the bureaucratic exercise of the NRC where they will have to prove their citizenship for inclusion in the registry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/its-not-just-about-muslims-all-indians-will-have-to-queue-up-to-prove-they-are-indians-owaisi-2432283.html|title=It's Not Just About Muslims, All Indians Will Have to Queue Up to Prove They are Indians: Owaisi|website=News18|access-date=17 January 2020|quote=\"Why are we protesting? We are protesting because, in the country, in the name of religion, preparation is being made to make us not just second-class citizens but stateless,\" [Owaisi] claimed, adding it is a loss for everyone.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/948969/the-nrc-is-a-bureaucratic-paper-monster-that-will-devour-and-divide-india|title=The NRC is a bureaucratic paper-monster that will devour and divide India|last=Mathur|first=Nayanika|website=Scroll.in|access-date=14 January 2020}}</ref> The protesters have raised voices against [[authoritarianism]], the police crackdown in other universities, and suppression of protests.\n\nProtesters in [[Assam]] and other [[Northeast India|northeastern states]] do not want [[Indian citizenship]] to be granted to any refugee or immigrant, regardless of their religion, as they fear it would alter the region's demographic balance, resulting in a loss of their political rights, culture, and land. They are also concerned that it will motivate further [[Human migration|migration]] from [[Bangladesh]] as well as violate the [[Assam Accord]], which was a prior agreement reached with the central government on migrants and refugees.<ref name=\"iexpressassam\">{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/assam-protests-citizenship-amendment-bill-nrc-northeast-bandh-5543785/|title=Explained: Why Assam, Northeast are angry|last1=Saha|first1=Abhishek|date=20 January 2019|work=The Indian Express|access-date=|quote=Protesters have expressed fears that the prospect of citizenship will encourage migration from Bangladesh. They have cited several grounds for opposing this. Demography: This will change across Northeastern states, protesters say, as has already been happening in Assam and Tripura over decades of migration (see graphs). \"Assamese could become the second language. Then there is also the question of loss of political rights and culture of the indigenous people,\u201d said former Chief Minister Prafulla Mahanta, who was the face of the Assam Movement (1979-85) against illegal immigration, and one of the signatories to the Assam Accord at the culmination of the movement. (...) Protesters say the Bill goes against the Assam Accord and negates the ongoing update of the National Register of Citizens (NRC).}}</ref><ref name=\"reuters1211\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-india-citizenship-idUSKBN1YF0QI|title=India's parliament passes citizenship law, protests flare|date=11 December 2019|work=Reuters|access-date=17 January 2020|quote=The bill will take away our rights, language and culture with millions of Bangladeshis getting citizenship (...) people in Assam and surrounding states fear that arriving settlers could increase competition for land and upset the region\u2019s demographic balance}}</ref>\n\nThe protests started in Assam on 4 December 2019, after the bill was introduced in parliament. Later on, protests erupted in [[Northeast India]], and subsequently spread to the major cities of India. On 15 December, major protests took place near [[Jamia Millia Islamia]] in [[New Delhi]] and [[Aligarh Muslim University]]. As the protests spread, private and public property was burnt and destroyed by mobs, and some railway stations were vandalized.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/caa-violence-arson-in-south-delhi-as-protesters-torch-four-buses-two-injured-11576412295374.html|title=CAA: Violence, arson in south Delhi as protesters torch four buses; two injured|date=15 December 2019|website=Livemint|access-date=17 January 2020|quote=Four buses were set ablaze by a mob and two fire officials were injured in stone pelting as the protests against the newly enacted Citizenship Act\" (...) \"The situation turned critical when a bus was burned by the protestors and police got into action}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theweek.com/5things/884376/violent-protests-over-citizenship-law-continue-india|title=Violent protests over citizenship law continue in India|website=The Week|access-date=17 January 2020|quote=Protesters set fire to buses and vandalized railroad stations}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/no-bullet-fired-by-police-during-protests-at-jamia-mha-officials-119121700271_1.html|title=Delhi cops didn't fire during Citizenship Act protests at Jamia: Officials|date=17 December 2019|work=Business Standard India|access-date=17 January 2020|quote=Several vehicles, including buses, were burnt down and public properties destroyed during the protests against the Citizenship Amendment Act, which was passed by Parliament last week.}}</ref> Police [[2019 Jamia Milia Islamia attack|forcibly entered]] the campus of Jamia, used batons and [[tear gas]] on the students, and more than 200 students were injured while around 100 were detained overnight in the police station. The police action was widely criticized and resulted in students across the country protesting in solidarity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/supreme-court-declines-to-take-up-police-action-against-jamia-protesters-says-it-is-a-law-and-order-problem/story-WlBa5J75IkHiW3iMbLffnK.html|title=High courts can inquire, says Supreme Court on plea over police action against protesters|date=17 December 2019|website=Hindustan Times|access-date=17 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/17/india-protests-students-condemn-barbaric-police|title=India protests: students condemn 'barbaric' police|last=Ellis-Petersen|first=Hannah|date=17 December 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=17 December 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n====Russia====\n{{see also|2020 Russian constitutional referendum}}\n\nA constitutional referendum will be held in [[Russia]] on 22 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vedomosti.ru/politics/articles/2020/02/26/823899-den-obscherossiiskogo-golosovaniya?utm_referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fzen.yandex.com&utm_campaign=dbr|title=\u0413\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u043e \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430\u043c \u0432 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u044e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0439\u0434\u0435\u0442 22 \u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u043b\u044f|website=\u0412\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> The draft [[2020 amendments to the Constitution of Russia|amendments to the Constitution]] were submitted to a referendum in accordance with article 2 of the Law on Amendments to the Constitution.<ref name=Law>[https://sozd.duma.gov.ru/bill/885214-7 \u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043e \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0435 \u043a \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438]</ref>\n\nThe referendum is referred to as an All-Russian vote, as it is not held in accordance with the Federal Constitutional Law on the Referendum. Unlike a referendum carried out in accordance with the referendum law, voters will be asked whether they approve the entire revised constitution as a whole, rather than approving each amendment separately.<ref>[https://tass.com/politics/1111023 Public vote on constitutional amendments will be held on the law as a whole \u2014 official]</ref> At the same time, there are no differences from the referendum, just as in 1993, when the [[1993 Russian constitutional referendum|All-Russian vote]] on the adoption of the Constitution was held, which was also not officially referred to as a referendum.\n\nThe referendum was proposed by President [[Vladimir Putin]] during his [[2020 Presidential Address to the Federal Assembly]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.interfax.ru/russia/691265|title=\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u043b \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438 \"\u0432\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435\" \u043f\u043e \u043f\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u043a \u0432 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u044e|website=\u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0444\u0430\u043a\u0441|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\n==== Turkey ====\n{{see also|2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria|Northwestern Syria offensive (December 2019\u2013present)|2019 Turkish offensive into north-western Syria}}\nIn March 2020, [[Turkey]] started a military offensive against the [[Syrian Armed Forces]] as part of its [[Turkish involvement in the Syrian Civil War|intervention in the Syrian Civil War]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gall|first=Carlotta|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/01/world/middleeast/turkey-syria-assault.html|title=Turkey Declares Major Offensive Against Syrian Government|date=2020-03-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> That same month Turkey also declared that it would no longer stop migrants from entering the [[European Union]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51678462|title=Turkey lets refugees exit towards Europe|date=2020-02-28|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Middle East and Northern Africa===\n==== Iran ====\n{{See also|2019\u201320 Persian Gulf crisis|2020 Iran protests|2020 Iranian legislative election}}\n\nIn January [[2020]], the [[United States]] [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|assassinated]] the commander of the [[Quds Force]] of the [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]], general [[Qasem Soleimani]]. This led to an [[2020 Iranian attack on U.S. forces in Iraq|Iranian missile strike]] against bases housing US troops in Iraq five days later. As a result of expectations of a US retribution, the [[Islamic Republic of Iran Air Defense Force|Iranian air defence system]] accidentally shot down [[Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752]], killing all 176 people on board.<ref>[https://www.vox.com/world/2020/1/13/21051794/us-iran-soleimani-ukraine-airline-questions 9 questions about the US-Iran crisis you were too embarrassed to ask] By Alex Ward and Zack Beauchamp, Vox, 13 Jan 2020</ref>\n====Iraq====\n{{see also|2019\u201320 Iraqi protests}} \nIn 2020, demonstrations took place in Baghdad and other parts of Iraq, over popular discontent with government corruption, unemployment, poor government services, and foreign interference within Iraq.  Reports said that 450 protesters had been fatally shot by security forces. <ref name=\"bbc iraq\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51712107 |date=March 2, 2020|title= Iraq power vacuum as political crisis hits PM post. |website=bbc.com |publisher=[[BBC]] |access-date=March 3, 2020}} </ref> Major protests were based in [[Nasiriyah]] in [[Dhi Qar]] province, with hundreds of protesters arriving there from other cities.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2020/02/nasiriyah-dhi-qar-iraq-protests.html |title= Nasiriyah becomes the Iraqi protest capital. }}</ref> New clashes erupted in Baghdad between protesters and security forces, with security forces using gunfire against protesters.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.timesofisrael.com/protester-shot-dead-in-fresh-iraq-violence/ |title= Protester shot dead in fresh Iraq violence. }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.660citynews.com/2020/02/23/iraqi-officials-1-protester-shot-dead-in-fresh-violence/ |title=Iraqi officials: 1 protester shot dead in fresh violence. }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/2147131/iraqi-nurse-spends-her-weekends-stitching-wounds-protest-site |title= Iraqi Nurse Spends Her Weekends Stitching Wounds at Protest Site. }}</ref> One march included more than 1,000 students.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.660citynews.com/2020/02/23/iraqi-officials-1-protester-shot-dead-in-fresh-violence/ |title= Iraqi students hold anti-government protests. }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, [[Mohammed Allawi]] sent a letter to the [[President of Iraq]], stating that he had to decline to take office as Prime Minister since the Iraqi Parliament had declined to approve his cabinet. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/uncertainty-looms-iraqi-pm-designate-allawi-steps-200302063000903.html |title= Uncertainty looms as Iraqi PM-designate Allawi steps down. |}} Iraq's crisis deepens as Mohammed Tawfiq Allawi halts efforts to form new government amid political infighting. Mar 2, 2020, Al Jazeera. </ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/02/iraqs-allawi-bows-out-as-pm-designate-rockets-hit-green-zone.html |title= Iraq's Allawi bows out as PM-designate, rockets hit Green Zone. |}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20200302-iraqs-pm-designate-allawi-steps-down/ |title= Iraq\u2019s PM-designate Allawi steps down. |}}</ref> Reports indicated that the crowds of protesters in Baghdad had expressed widespread opposition to Allawi. <ref name=\"bbc iraq\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51712107 |date=March 2, 2020|title= Iraq power vacuum as political crisis hits PM post. |website=bbc.com |publisher=[[BBC]] |access-date=March 3, 2020}} </ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.dw.com/en/iraqs-prime-minister-designate-mohammed-allawi-withdraws-from-race/a-52601139 |title= Iraq's Prime Minister-designate Mohammed Allawi withdraws from race. |}}</ref>\n\n====Libya====\n{{main|Libyan peace process#Political track}}\nIn February 2020, the political track of the Libyan peace process started in Geneva among 20 Libyans, from both the Tobruk-based and Tripoli-based parts of the [[House of Representatives (Libya)|Libyan House of Representatives]], and from the independent persons' group selected by [[United Nations Support Mission in Libya|UN Support Mission in Libya]] (UNSMIL), including [[Ministry of Interior (Libya)|Interior Minister]] [[Fathi Bashagha]], former Education Minister [[Othman Abdul Jalil]] and former head of the HCS [[Abdulrahman Sewehli]].<ref name=\"LibObs_pol_track_boycott\">{{cite news | last1= Assad | first1= Abdulkader | title=UNSMIL kicks off political talks in Geneva despite boycott of major Libyan lawmakers | date= 2020-02-26 |newspaper= [[The Libya Observer]] | url=https://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/unsmil-kicks-political-talks-geneva-despite-boycott-major-libyan-lawmakers |accessdate=2020-02-27 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227211142/https://www.libyaobserver.ly/news/unsmil-kicks-political-talks-geneva-despite-boycott-major-libyan-lawmakers |archivedate=2020-02-27 |url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped --> |url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref> The aimed composition was 13 HoR representatives from both the Tobruk and Tripoli branches, 13 HCS representatives and 14 UNSMIL-selected independent Libyans, for a total of 40.<ref name=\"LibHerald_Tobruk_wants_13\">{{cite news | title= UNSMIL political track talks to go ahead despite pullout by Tobruk HoR and Tripoli State Council | date= 2020-02-27 |newspaper= [[Libya Herald]] | url= https://www.libyaherald.com/2020/02/25/unsmil-political-track-talks-to-go-ahead-despite-pullout-by-tobruk-hor-and-tripoli-state-council/ |accessdate=2020-02-27 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200227220123/https://www.libyaherald.com/2020/02/25/unsmil-political-track-talks-to-go-ahead-despite-pullout-by-tobruk-hor-and-tripoli-state-council/ |archivedate= 2020-02-27 |url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped --> |url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref>\n\n====Syria====\n{{see also|Syrian civil war|Timeline of the Syrian Civil War|Timeline of the Syrian Civil War (January\u2013April 2020)|Northwestern Syria offensive (December 2019\u2013March 2020)}}\n\nIn early 2020, the Syrian Civil War flared up, with massive fighting between Syrian government forces and rebel groups in northwestern Syria. The conflict began to threaten to draw Turkey and Syria into armed conflict, as Turkey seemed to support some rebel groups. In the wake of the withdrawal by the United States of most of its troops from the war zone in Syria, Russia stepped in as a mediator between the factions, i.e., between the Syrian government, local Kurdish groups, Turkey, and some rebel groups. \n\nNew waves of migrants fled over the Turkish border and also attempted to enter Greece, but were barred by Greek forces. There were concerns about a new refugee crisis possibly overtaking the region.\n\nIn March 2020, Syria claimed that a number of its soldiers had been killed in Turkish attacks.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51701069 Syria war: Turkish drone strikes 'kill 19 Syrian soldiers'], bbc.com. </ref>  Turkey warned that millions of migrants might head for the EU. <ref> [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51707958 Turkey says millions of migrants may head to EU], MArch 2, 2020, bbc. </ref> Greece suspended all asylum applications.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51695468 Greece suspends asylum applications as migrants seek to leave Turkey], 1 March 2020, bbc. </ref>\n\n====Yemen====\n{{See also|Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)}}\n\nThe Yemeni Civil War is an ongoing conflict that began in 2015 between two factions: the [[Abdrabbuh Mansur Hadi]] led Yemeni government and the [[Houthi]] armed movement, along with their supporters and allies. Both claim to constitute the official government of [[Yemen]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/143295/asher-orkaby/houthi-who|agency=Foreign Affairs|title=Houthi Who?|first=Asher|last=Orkaby|date=25 March 2015|accessdate=25 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150327115828/http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/143295/asher-orkaby/houthi-who|archivedate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Houthis|Houthi]] forces currently control the capital [[Sana'a|Sana\u02bda]], allied with forces loyal to the former president [[Ali Abdullah Saleh]], have clashed with the forces loyal to Hadi who are based in [[Aden]]. [[Al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] (AQAP) and the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] have also carried out attacks, with AQAP controlling swathes of territory in the hinterlands, and along stretches of the coast.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yemen in Crisis|url=http://www.cfr.org/yemen/yemen-crisis/p36488|publisher=Council on Foreign Relations|date=8 July 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150509030311/http://www.cfr.org/yemen/yemen-crisis/p36488|archivedate=9 May 2015}}</ref> Concurrently, the Hadi government is in conflict with [[United Arab Emirates|UAE forces]] as a result of UAE military measures such as the [[United Arab Emirates takeover of Socotra]] and UAE-backed STC takeover of Aden.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/08/yemen-southern-separatists-regain-control-port-city-aden-190829073935248.html|title=Hadi urges Saudi intervention to stop UAE support for separatists|website=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref>\n\n===Sub-Saharan Africa===\n<!----\n{{collapse top|title=Sub-Saharan Africa|expand=yes}}\n---->\n\nAs the 2020s begin, there is the possibility of unprecedented economic growth throughout Africa, based on probable increases in trade when the [[African Continental Free Trade Area |African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCTA)]] goes fully into effect on July 1, 2020, abolishing 90% of tariffs between member states and bringing a 50% increase in trade in the next few years.<ref name=hammond>[https://www.africanliberty.org/2020/01/24/what-can-we-expect-from-africa-in-the-2020s/ What Can We Expect from Africa in the 2020s?] by Alexander Hammond, African Liberty.org, 24 Jan 2020</ref><ref name=odi>[https://www.odi.org/blogs/16535-will-2020-be-decade-Africa-economic-transformation Will the 2020s be the decade of Africa\u2019s economic transformation?] by Arkebe Okubay, ODI.org, 14 Jan 2020</ref> This economic growth could lead directly to increases in life expectancy, literacy, and per capita income.\n\n[[Nigeria]] and [[South Africa]] account for the largest shares of Africa's [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] at 29.3% and 19.1%, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|website=African Development Bank Group|year=2020|accessdate=Feb 3, 2020|title=West Africa Regional Overview |url=https://www.afdb.org/en/countries/west-africa/west-africa-overview}}</ref> Civil strife and terrorism continue to plague the continent, particularly in the [[Sahel]] and the [[Horn of Africa]].<ref name=relief>[https://reliefweb.int/report/world/conflict-still-africa-s-biggest-challenge-2020 Conflict is still Africa\u2019s biggest challenge in 2020] by Simon Allison, Relief Web, 6 Jan 2020</ref> Finally, Africa is more vulnerable than any other region to the world's changing weather patterns.<ref>{{cite web|website=BBC World News|title=How Africa will be affected by climate change|author=Richard Washington|date=Dec 15, 2019|accessdate=Feb 3, 2020|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-50726701}}</ref>\n\n====West Africa====\n{{See also|2020 in West Africa}}\n[[Burkina Faso]], [[Mali]], and [[Nigeria]] face serious challenges related to security and terrorism such as the January 2020 [[2020 Gamboru bombing]].<ref>[https://www.dw.com/en/nigeria-hit-by-deadly-bomb-attack-near-cameroon/a-51908242 Nigeria hit by deadly bomb attack near Cameroon] Deutsche Welle, 7 Jan 2020</ref><ref>[https://apnews.com/08eddc78099bbcda5caf8bee7de1fa2a French summit aims to boost counterterror fight in W. Africa]  [https://apnews.com/36e33f583ce814ea36bf46fc37ec369b Niger army chief fired after 89 killed in extremist attack]</ref> In January 2020 the United States called for a reduction of the [[United Nations Multidimensional Integrated Stabilization Mission in Mali|United Nations Multidimensional Integrated Stabilization Mission in Mali (MINUSMA)]] with a new focus on protecting civilians. France and Russia opposed reductions.<ref>[https://apnews.com/09672220276b5cdbce63f139566b58c4 US calls for smaller UN force in Mali, Russia says no change] By Edith M. Lederer, AP, 15 Jan 2020, retrieved 8 Feb 2020</ref>\n\n[[Female genital mutilation|Female genital mutilation (FGM)]] is a continuing issue in [[Guinea]], [[the Gambia]], Burkina Faso, Mali, and [[Sierra Leone]].<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/science-health/female-genital-mutilation-still-prevalent-west-africa Female Genital Mutilation Still Prevalent in West Africa] By Annika Hammerschlag, Voice of America, 6 February 2020</ref>\n\nSenegalese-born American rapper [[Akon|Akon's]] new \"Akon City\" located near [[Dakar]],<ref>{{cite web|website=CNN Travel|date=14 Jan 2020 |url=https://edition.cnn.com/travel/article/akon-city-senegal-trnd/index.html |title=Akon created his own city in Senegal called 'Akon City'|author=Amir Vera}}</ref> investment in solar energy,<ref>{{cite web|website=Archdye.com |title=Senegal completes largest wind farm in West Africa|date=Jan 8, 2020 |url=https://www.archyde.com/senegal-completes-largest-wind-farm-in-west-africa/?amp}}</ref> and a transition toward eco-farming on a national scale are [[Senegal|Senegal's]] responses to climate change.<ref>[https://allafrica.com/stories/202002050726.html Senegal Turns to Eco-Farming to Protect Food Supply As Climate Changes]</ref>\n\n====East Africa====\n{{See also|2020 in East Africa}}\nHuman rights concerns and freedom of the press are highlighted in [[South Sudan]],<ref>[https://apnews.com/f6da04d6674e981b525454d995b86f9b US sanctions South Sudan\u2019s vice president over abuses] by Cara Anna, AP, 8 Jan 2020, retrieved 15 Feb 2020</ref> [[Comoros]],<ref>[https://allafrica.com/stories/202001160648.html Comoros: Two Reporters Arrested in Comoros, Placed Under Judicial Control] allAfrica, 16 Jan 2020, retrieved 11 Feb 2020</ref> and [[Tanzania]] as 2020 begins.<ref>[https://allafrica.com/stories/202002030868.html Tanzania: Obstructions to LGBT Health, Rights]</ref>\n====Ethiopia====\nTensions began to rise again between Ethiopia and Eritrea, after several years of efforts to negotiate peace, due to possible border disputes. <ref> [https://www.trtworld.com/africa/why-are-ethiopian-leaders-calling-eritrea-s-president-hitler-34158 Why are Ethiopian leaders calling Eritrea's president \u2018Hitler\u2019?], An escalating war of words is taking place between Eritrea and Ethiopia, as the two countries face-off over a flaring border dispute that historically claimed the lives of over 100,000 people. February 27, 2020. trtworld.com. </ref><ref> [https://cruxnow.com/church-in-africa/2020/02/ethiopian-cardinal-other-church-leaders-barred-from-entering-eritrea/ Ethiopian cardinal, other church leaders barred from entering Eritrea], Fredrick Nzwili, CNSFeb 28, 2020, CATHOLIC NEWS SERVICE. </ref><ref> [https://www.voanews.com/africa/un-decries-lack-reforms-and-widespread-abuse-eritrea UN Decries Lack of Reforms and Widespread Abuse in Eritrea], By Lisa Schlein, March 01, 2020. </ref>\n\nAfter having won the Nobel Peace Prize in 2019, Prime Minister Abiy Ahmed's government adopted some policies which raised some concerns about political developments in Ethiopia. Abiy dissolved the governing coalition and formed a new party, the Prosperity Party; some said the imposition of a brand-new political party was detrimental to political stability. Also, the government enacted some restrictions on some forms of expression which raised concern about standards of free speech.<ref>[https://www.ezega.com/News/NewsDetails/7745/Ethiopia-Approves-Controversial-Law-on-Hate-Speech-and-Disinformation Ethiopia Approves Controversial Law on Hate Speech and Disinformation, By Staff Reporter, ezega.com. </ref><ref> [https://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/upfront/2020/02/ethiopia-sliding-abiy-ahmed-200214062515704.html Is Ethiopia sliding backwards under Abiy Ahmed?] We challenge an adviser to Ethiopia's prime minister on his record. 14 Feb 2020, al-jazeera. </ref>\nAbiy's response to rebel groups has raised some concerns about undue harshness, although some others allege that he was originally too lenient. <ref> [https://eastafricamonitor.com/how-popular-is-abiy-ahmed-in-ethiopia-as-election-looms/ How popular is Abiy Ahmed in Ethiopia as election looms?], February 27, 2020. </ref><ref>[https://www.france24.com/en/20200229-ethiopia-s-abiy-faces-outcry-over-crackdown-on-rebels [https://www.france24.com/en/20200229-ethiopia-s-abiy-faces-outcry-over-crackdown-on-rebels Ethiopia's Abiy faces outcry over crackdown on rebels],Issued on: 29/02/2020. france24.com </ref> Amnesty International raised concerns about the status of one opposition leader.<ref> [https://eastafricamonitor.com/amnesty-ethiopian-police-must-account-for-missing-opposition-leader/ Amnesty: Ethiopian police must account for missing opposition leader], March 3, 2020. </ref> <ref> [https://todaynewsafrica.com/breaking-amnesty-international-rages-as-nobel-peace-prize-winner-abiy-ahmed-unleashes-police-on-opposition-in-oromia-ethiopia-vender-killed-musician-injured/ Amnesty International Rages As Nobel Peace Prize Winner Abiy Ahmed Unleashes Police On Opposition In Oromia, Ethiopia. Vendor Killed, Musician Injured] By TODAY NEWS AFRICA </ref> Abiy encouraged Ethiopian refugees to return home, due to improving conditions. <ref> [https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/africa/Abiy-govt-more-refugees-going-home/4552902-5468496-mcpgxd/index.html Abiy\u2019s citizen-focused govt bringing more refugees home], TUESDAY FEBRUARY 25 2020, theeastafrican.co.ke. </ref>\n\n====Sudan====\n{{See also|Sudanese peace process}}\n\nIn January 2020, progress was made in peace negotiations, in the areas of land, transitional justice and system of government issues via the ''Darfur'' track of negotiations. SRF and Sovereignty Council representatives agreed on the creation of a [[Darfur war crimes court|Special Court for Darfur]] to conduct investigations and trials for [[war crime]]s and [[crimes against humanity]] carried out during the [[War in Darfur]] by the al-Bashir presidency and by warlords. ''Two Areas'' negotiations with SPLM-N (al-Hilu) had progressed on six framework agreement points, after a two-week pause, but disagreement remained on SPLM-N (al-Hilu)'s requirement of a secular state in South Kordofan and [[Nuba Mountains]] and [[Blue Nile (state)|Blue Nile]] self-determination. On 24 January on the ''Two Areas'' track, political and security agreements, constituting a ''framework'' agreement, were signed by Hemetti on behalf of the Sovereignty Council and Ahmed El Omda Badi on behalf of SPLM-N (Agar). The agreements give legislative autonomy to South Kordofan and Blue Nile; propose solutions for the sharing of land and other resources, and aim to unify all militias and government soldiers into a single unified Sudanese military body.\n\nOn 26 January, a \"final\" peace agreement for the northern track, including issues of studies for new dams, compensation for people displaced by existing dams, road construction and burial of electronic and nuclear waste, was signed by Shamseldin Kabashi of the Sovereignty Council and Dahab Ibrahim of the [[Kush Movement]]. <ref> [https://www.middleeasteye.net/big-story/can-south-sudans-men-war-lead-country-peace Can South Sudan's men of war lead the country to peace?], by Peter Oborne & Jan-Peter Westad, February 15, 2020. Middle East Eye website. </ref><ref> [https://www.dabangasudan.org/en/all-news/article/sudan-peace-talks-agreement-on-east-track-finalised  Sudan peace talks: Agreement on eastern track finalised], February 23 - 2020, dabangasudan website. </ref><ref>[https://thehill.com/opinion/international/484591-the-trouble-with-south-sudans-transitional-government The trouble with South Sudan's transitional government] BY AMIR IDRIS, oped, 02/28/20, thehill.com. </ref> \n\nIn February 2020, a new unity government was announced, to govern the entire country, with the support of all sides of the conflict.<ref> [https://www.npr.org/2020/02/22/808471587/south-sudan-forges-unity-government-renewing-fragile-hope-for-peace South Sudan Forges Unity Government, Renewing Fragile Hope For Peace] February 22, 2020, by Colin Dwyer, NPR. </ref><ref> [https://apnews.com/d3b929b5a687b69068e4f3ca24cccd7f South Sudan\u2019s rivals form unity government meant to end war] By MAURA AJAK, February 22, 2020, Associated Press. </ref> As one part of the agreement, the current cabinet was disbanded, in order to enable more opposition members to be appointed to cabinet roles. <ref> [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51562367 South Sudan rivals Salva Kiir and Riek Machar strike unity deal], 22 February 2020, BBC. </ref> <ref> [https://carnegieendowment.org/2020/02/27/unity-government-rekindles-hopes-for-peace-in-south-sudan-pub-81173 Unity Government Rekindles Hopes for Peace in South Sudan] by ASHLEY QUARCOO, FEBRUARY 27, 2020, Carnegie Endowment website. </ref> <ref> [https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/south-sudan-rival-leaders-form-coalition-government-200222121043672.html South Sudan's rival leaders form coalition government]. Opposition leader Riek Machar was sworn in on Saturday as the deputy of President Salva Kiir. 22 Feb 2020. Al Jazeera. </ref><ref>[https://reliefweb.int/report/south-sudan/senior-state-department-official-developments-south-sudan-s-peace-process Senior State Department Official On Developments in South Sudan\u2019s Peace Process], Source US State Dept. Published 26 Feb 2020. </ref> In March 2020, negotiators and officials on both sides of the conflict attempted to work out arrangements to facilitate the appointment of civilian governors for various regions, in concert with ongoing peace efforts. <ref> [https://www.dabangasudan.org/en/all-news/article/appointing-of-civilian-governors-mps-remain-obstacles-for-sudan-s-peace Appointing of civilian governors, MPs remains obstacles for Sudan\u2019s peace], March 1 - 2020 dabangasudan website. </ref> The EU announced its support for the peace efforts and pledged to provide financial support of 100 million Euros. <ref> [https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/IP_20_352 European Union announces \u20ac100 million to support the democratic transition process in Sudan], February 29, 2020, EU official website. </ref>\n\n====Central Africa====\n{{See also|2020 in Middle Africa}}\n\n====Southern Africa====\n\n<!----\n{{collapse bottom}}\n--->\n\n===Europe===\n<!----\n{{collapse top|title=Europe|expand=yes}}\n---->\n\n====European Union====\nThe [[European Union]] reduced in member states from 28 to 27 with the exit of the [[United Kingdom]] on January 31, 2020.\n\n==== Greece ====\nFollowing a surge of migrant arrivals from Turkey, [[Greece]] suspended all asylum applications in March 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stevis-Gridneff|first=Matina|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/01/world/europe/greece-migrants-border-turkey.html|title=Greece Suspends Asylum as Turkey Opens Gates for Migrants|date=2020-03-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== Ireland ====\nThe [[2020 Irish general election]] resulted in a historic win for the [[Sinn F\u00e9in]], making it the second largest party of the [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=correspondent|first=Rory Carroll Ireland|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/10/sinn-fein-declares-victory-irish-general-election|title=Sinn F\u00e9in declares victory in Irish general election|date=2020-02-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The result was seen as a historic shift in [[Ireland|Ireland's]] political landscape, effectively ending the [[two-party system]] of [[Fine Gael]] and [[Fianna F\u00e1il]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sinn-fein-shatters-irelands-political-landscape-to-become-second-largest-party/|title=Sinn Fein shatters Ireland\u2019s political landscape to become second largest party|last=Agencies|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> The reason for the electoral upset for these parties was believed to be  in voter dissatisfaction on issues of [[Health in Ireland|health]], housing and [[Homelessness in Ireland|homelessness]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/6449024a-4c19-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5|title=Subscribe to read {{!}} Financial Times|website=www.ft.com|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\n====United Kingdom====\n{{See also|Premiership of Boris Johnson|Brexit|Brexit negotiations in 2019}}\n\n[[Brexit]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hall|first1=Damien|title='Breksit' or 'bregzit'? The question that divides a nation|url=https://theconversation.com/breksit-or-bregzit-the-question-that-divides-a-nation-82278|date=11 August 2017|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=22 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704035541/http://theconversation.com/breksit-or-bregzit-the-question-that-divides-a-nation-82278|archive-date=4 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> (a [[portmanteau]] of \"British\" and \"exit\") is the [[Withdrawal from the European Union|withdrawal]] of the [[United Kingdom]] (UK) from the [[European Union]] (EU). Following a UK-wide [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|referendum in June 2016]], in which 52% voted to leave and 48% voted to remain in the EU, the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] formally announced the country's withdrawal in March 2017, beginning the [[Brexit negotiations|Brexit process]]. The withdrawal was delayed by deadlock in the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|British parliament]]. Following a general election, Parliament [[European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Act 2020|ratified]] the [[Brexit withdrawal agreement|withdrawal agreement]], and the UK left the EU at 11&nbsp;p.m. [[Greenwich Mean Time|GMT]] on 31 January 2020. This began a transition period that is set to end on 31 December 2020, during which the UK and EU will negotiate their future relationship.<ref name=Bennett>{{Cite news|title=How will the Brexit transition period work?|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/0/brexit-2020-transition-period/|newspaper=Telegraph|date=27 January 2020|author=Asa Bennett|access-date=28 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128044559/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/0/brexit-2020-transition-period/|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The UK remains subject to [[European Union law|EU law]] and remains part of the EU [[European Union Customs Union|customs union]] and [[European Single Market|single market]] during the transition, but is no longer part of the EU's political bodies or institutions.<ref name=Edgington>{{cite news|author=Tom Edgington|title=Brexit: What is the transition period?|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50838994|date=31 January 2020|access-date=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131215049/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50838994|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=QAEC>{{cite news|publisher=European Commission|date=24 January 2020|title=Questions and Answers on the United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union on 31 January 2020|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/qanda_20_104|access-date=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201003034/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/qanda_20_104|archive-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\n<!----\n{{collapse top|title=North America|expand=yes}}\n---->\n\n====Caribbean====\n{{See also|2020 in the Caribbean}}\nIn '''[[Haiti]]''', there is pressure on President [[Jovenel Mo\u00efse]] due to charges of corruption, poor living conditions, a high crime rate, and rising inflation.<ref name=al_stories /> '''[[Puerto Rico]]''' continues to struggle with the devastation from [[Hurricane Maria]] in 2017 and a [[2020 Puerto Rico earthquakes|series of earthquakes in 2019-20]] and a subsequent political shakeup.<ref>[https://www.cbsnews.com/news/puerto-rican-governor-fires-emergency-director-after-aid-is-found-sitting-in-warehouse-2020-01-18/ ''Puerto Rico governor fires emergency director after aid is found sitting in warehouse.''] Audrey McNamara. CBS News. 19 January 2020. Accessed 25 January 2020.  [https://www.cbsnews.com/news/puerto-rico-supplies-warehouse-governor-wanda-vazquez-fires-2-more-officials-over-viral-video-showing-aid-2020-01-19/ ''Puerto Rico governor fires 2 more officials after emergency supplies found sitting in warehouse.''] Peter Martinez and Audrey McNamara. CBS News. 19 January 2020. Accessed 25 January 2020.</ref>\n\n====Central America regional items====\n{{See also|2020 in Central America}}\nInternal and external migratiion are major concerns throughout the region.<ref name=al_stories />\n\nHuman rights and oppression are a major concern in '''[[Nicaragua]]''', which saw 70,000 emigrants in 2019. '''[[Costa Rica]]''' is struggling to care for 55,000 of those migrants. President [[Nayib Bukele]] of '''[[El Salvador]]''' is popular, but the country's economy is stagnant and crime continues to grow. '''[[Guatemala]]''' and '''[[Honduras]]''' are also facing corruption and high crime rates, as well as suffering from the effects of climate change.<ref name=al_stories />\n\n====Dominican Republic====\n{{see also|2020 Dominican Republic general election}} \n\nIn March 2020, massive protests occurred in the Dominican Republic, due to announced postponement of national elections.<ref> [https://www.latinousa.org/2020/03/02/trabucazo2020photos/ PHOTOS: Dominicans Hold Massive #Trabucazo2020 Demonstration For Democracy] By TATIANA FERNANDEZ GEARA, MAR 2, 2020, latinousa.org. </ref>\n\n====Mexico====\n{{see also|Presidency of Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador|LXIV Legislature of the Mexican Congress|Fourth Transformation}}\nAs the [[Fourth Transformation]] enters its second year, President [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador|Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador (AMLO)]] faces challenges involving social violence (particularly drug-related and other [[List of countries by intentional homicide rate|killings]]),<ref>[https://aristeguinoticias.com/0201/mexico/senala-amlo-que-su-reto-para-2020-es-serenar-a-mexico/ Se\u00f1ala AMLO que su reto para 2020 es serenar a M\u00e9xico] Aristegui Noticias, 2 Jan 2020  [https://www.univision.com/noticias/america-latina/una-reaparicion-fortalecida-del-narco-y-la-presion-de-trump-la-seguridad-sera-el-mayor-reto-de-amlo-en-2020 Una \"reaparici\u00f3n fortalecida\" del narco y la presi\u00f3n de Trump: la seguridad ser\u00e1 el mayor reto de AMLO en 2020] by Patricia Velez Santiago, Univision Noticias, 2 Jan 2020</ref> corruption, major infrastructure development, universal health care,<ref>[https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/mexico/sociedad/sector-salud-el-principal-reto-para-el-gobierno-de-amlo-en-2020-4638480.html Sector salud, el principal reto para el gobierno de AMLO en 2020] El Sol de Mexico, 29 December 2019</ref>  and decentralization of the government.<ref>{{cite web|website=Diario Contrapeso Ciudadano|title=TOP 5: RETOS DE AMLO EN 2020|language=es|trans-title=Top 5: Challenges for AMLO in 2020|date=Jan 8, 2020|url=https://www.contrapesociudadano.com/top-5-retos-de-amlo-en-2020/}}</ref><ref>[https://billieparkernoticias.com/define-amlo-los-dos-retos-por-resolver-este-2020-seguridad-publica-y-seguridad-social/ Define AMLO los dos retos por resolver este 2020: Seguridad P\u00fablica y Seguridad Social.] Billie Parker Noticias, 14 Jan 2020</ref> At a news conference on January 15, 2020, journalist [[Jorge Ramos (news anchor)|Jorge Ramos]] pointed that during AMLO's first year as president, there were more homicides than under his predecessors; Ramos asked if a change in strategy and/or personal were required. The president assured him that we would see results by December.<ref>[https://www.proceso.com.mx/614236/amlo-jorge-ramos-seguridad AMLO responde a Jorge Ramos: en diciembre, resultados sobre seguridad] by Sara Pantoja, Proceso, 15 Jan 2020</ref> \n\nFollowing several notorious cases of [[femicide]], [[violence against women in Mexico|violence against women]] emerges as a priority concern. Hundreds of thousands march on March 8<ref>[https://www.msn.com/es-mx/noticias/mujeres/marchan-m%C3%A1s-de-15-mil-en-monterrey/ar-BB10Wwwk More than 15,000 march in Monterrey] {{in lang|es}} by Caroline Leon, Milenio, 9 Mar 2020  [https://politica.expansion.mx/mexico/2020/03/08/miles-mujeres-marchan-cdmx-consignas-pintas-reclamos-justicia Thousands of women march on CDMX between slogans, graffiti, and claims for justice] {{in lang|es}} Expansion Politica, 8 Mar 2020</ref> and millions of women strike on March 9, [[2020 in Mexico|2020]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-51736957 Fury fuels historic women's strike in Mexico] By Will Grant\nBBC News, 9 Mar 2020  [https://www.msn.com/es-mx/noticias/mexico/hoy-ellas-no-llegaron-as%C3%AD-luce-m%C3%A9xico-por-el-el9nadiesemueve/ar-BB10WyzH \"Today, they did not arrive\": This is how Mexico looks for # El9NadieSeMueve] {{in lang|es}} by Gustavo \u00c1lvarez, 24 Horas, 9 Mar 2020  [https://www.msn.com/es-mx/noticias/mexico/paro-de-mujeres-paraliza-la-c%c3%a1mara-de-diputados/ar-BB10XzHs Women's strike paralyzes the Chamber of Deputies] by Fernando Dami\u00e1n, Milenio, 9 Mar 2020  [https://www.msn.com/es-mx/video/noticias/cierran-sucursales-bancarias-ante-paro-de-mujeres/vi-BB10X1gh Bank branches closed in response to women's strike] {{in lang|es}} La Jornada, 9 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n====United States====\n{{see also|Presidency of Donald Trump|Timeline of the Donald Trump presidency (2020 Q1)|116th United States Congress|2020 United States presidential election|2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|2020 United States federal budget}}\n\nThe [[Impeachment of Donald Trump]] and the [[2020 United States presidential election]] dominate the first year of the decade. Foreign policy concerns are primarily related to trade and tariffs, disengagement from the Middle East, and [[Iran\u2013United States relations]]. Domestic issues include gun control and gun rights, immigrations, student loan debt, health care, climate change, and abortion rights.<ref>{{cite web|website=U.S. News|title=America 2020|accessdate=25 Jan 2020 |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/elections}}</ref> [[Baby boomers|As the nation ages]], funding of [[Social programs in the United States|social programs]] and the national debt ($23 trillion in January 2020) will be major concerns in the decade to come.<ref>{{cite web|website=Reason|title=The 2020s Will Be the Decade of Deficit Doomsday|author=Eric Boehm|date=Jan 10, 2020 |url=https://reason.com/2020/01/10/in-the-2020s-dealing-with-the-national-debt-will-no-longer-be-optional/}}</ref>\n\n===South America===\n<!----\n{{collapse top|title=South America|expand=yes}}\n---->\n\nWomen's rights, including [[Abortion-rights movements|the right to abortion]] and concerns about [[femicide]] and [[rape]] are major concerns throughout the region. Improvements on environmental issues have been tied to international trade agreements.<ref name=al_stories />\n\n====Argentina====\n[[Argentina|Argentina's]] economy faces major problems of debt, inflation, and growing poverty. Vice President [[Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez de Kirchner]] is on trial for corruption.<ref name=al_stories />\n\n====Bolivia====\nAfter the contested [[2019 Bolivian general election]] and the subsequent [[2019 Bolivian political crisis|political crisis]], Bolivia struggles to restore democracy.<ref name=al_stories />\n\nBolivians are now protesting against the opposition movement, as they feel that the movement's leaders have failed to unify in support of one credible candidate who could replace the current leaders.<ref>[https://www.france24.com/en/20200212-anger-in-bolivia-as-anti-morales-bloc-splinters-before-may-polls Anger in Bolivia as anti-Morales bloc splinters before May polls] Feb. 12, 2020, France 24 website. </ref>\n\nIn early 2020, [[MIT]] released a study which cast major doubts on the claims in 2019 by the [[Organization of American States|OAS]] which asserted that massive election fraud had occurred, and which were responsible for compelling President [[Evo Morales]] to step down from office. <ref> [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/28/world/americas/bolivia-election-fraud.html .I.T. Researchers Cast Doubt on Bolivian Election Fraud]. An international audit said officials had engaged in lies and manipulation to assure victory for Evo Morales. Academics at M.I.T.\u2019s Election Data and Science Lab questioned that finding. By Julie Turkewitz, Feb. 28, 2020. NY Times </ref><ref> [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/02/26/bolivia-dismissed-its-october-elections-fraudulent-our-research-found-no-reason-suspect-fraud/ Bolivia dismissed its October elections as fraudulent. Our research found no reason to suspect fraud.] Bolivians will hold a new election in May \u2014 without ousted president Evo Morales. By John Curiel and Jack R. Williams, Feb. 27, 2020. Washington Post. </ref><ref> [https://theglobepost.com/2020/02/27/mit-no-evidence-of-fraud-bolivia-election/ MIT Researchers Find No Evidence of Fraud in Bolivia\u2019s October Election] by Bryan Bowman  February 27, 2020. The Globe Post, Canada.</ref><ref>[https://www.salon.com/2020/02/28/mit-study-right-wing-coup-in-bolivia-was-based-on-false-claims-of-election-fraud_partner/ MIT study: Right-wing coup in Bolivia was based on false claims of election fraud U.S. media and politicians largely backed the overthrow of leftist president Evo Morales \u2014 but the excuse was BS], by EOIN HIGGINS, FEBRUARY 28, 2020, salon.com </ref><ref>[https://cepr.net/press-release/new-study-finds-no-evidence-of-oas-fraud-claims-very-likely-evo-morales-won-bolivias-october-elections-in-the-first-round/ MIT statisticians confirm findings of CEPR Study [on Bolivian election], CEPR article. </ref>\n\n====Brazil====\nEntering its second year in power, the [[Presidency of Jair Bolsonaro]] struggles with its fight against corruption and crime while being under fire for its anti-environmentalist policies and its handling of the [[2019 Amazon rainforest wildfires]].<ref name=al_stories />\n\n====Chile====\n{{see also|2019\u201320 Chilean protests}}\nAfter turbulence in [[2019\u201320 Chilean protests|2019]] in which 25 people died and 2,300 were injured by security forces, as well as arbitrary arrests of children and torture, Chile struggles to regain popular trust in the military, police, and the media.<ref name=al_stories>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/latin-america-2020-stories-watch-191202204939337.html Latin America in 2020: Stories to watch] by Charlotte Mitchell, Al Jazeera, 2 Jan 2020, Retrieved 24 Jan 2020</ref>\n\n====Colombia====\n{{see also|2019\u201320 Colombian protests}}\nThe 2019\u201320 Colombian protests are a collection of ongoing protests that began on 21 November 2019. Hundreds of thousands of [[Colombians]] demonstrated for various reasons. Some protested against various proposed economic and political reforms proposed by the [[Government of Colombia|government]] of [[Iv\u00e1n Duque M\u00e1rquez]], others against the few violent protestors and in favor of the [[Colombian peace process]], etc. <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/21/americas/colombia-national-strike-intl/index.html|title=Colombia protests prompt teargas, curfew and border closures|last=|first=|date=22 November 2019|website=[[CNN]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n\nWhile mostly peaceful in nature, a few violent incidents took place throughout the protests, leading to overnight [[curfew]]s in [[Cali]] and [[Bogot\u00e1]]. It is \"one of the largest mass demonstrations Colombia has witnessed in recent years\".<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5737190/colombia-protests/|title=Hundreds of Thousands Protested Colombia's Conservative Government. Here's What to Know|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref>\n\n====Peru====\n{{see also|2017\u201320 Peruvian political crisis|2020 Peruvian parliamentary election}} \n\nThe fallout from the [[Operation Car Wash|Odebrecht scandal]] and corruption investigations into opposition leader [[Keiko Fujimori]] and past presidents [[Pedro Pablo Kuczynski]] (2016\u201318), [[Ollanta Humala]] (2011\u201316), [[Alejandro Toledo]] (2001\u201306), and the late [[Alan Garcia]] (1985\u201390 and 2006\u201311) continue.<ref name=al_stories />\n\nEarly parliamentary elections were held in [[Peru]] on 26 January 2020.<ref name=LAT>[https://latinamericareports.com/perus-political-storm-a-timeline-of-events/3375/ Peru\u2019s political storm: a timeline of events] Los Angeles Times, 4 October 2019</ref> The elections were called after President [[Mart\u00edn Vizcarra]] dissolved the [[Congress of the Republic of Peru|Congress of the Republic]] on 30 September 2019.<ref name=LAT/>\n\nAll 130 congressmen corresponding to the 26 electoral districts will be elected to office for the remainder of the 2016\u20132021 congressional period. It was the seventh parliamentary election under the 1993 Constitution, which created the current Congress of the Republic of Peru.\n\n====Venezuela====\n{{see also|2020 Venezuelan presidential crisis}}\n\n[[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] or [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]]? Two leaders struggle for the leadership of beleaguered Venezuela. No matter the political solution, the winner will have to deal with a devastated economy.<ref name=al_stories />\n<!----\n{{collapse bottom}}\n--->\n\n===Oceania and Australia===\n====Australia====\nThe [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season]] was particularly destructive, killing at least 28 and destroying no fewer than 3,000 homes. The fires were widespread, but [[New South Wales|New South Wales (NSW)]] was the hardest hit. In December 2019 the smoke around [[Sydney]] was so bad that air quality was 11 times the \"hazardous\" level and temperatures were over 40&nbsp;\u00b0C (113\u00b0-120&nbsp;\u00b0F). Natural causes such as [[lightning strike]]s started most of the fires, which were exasperated by dry conditions and [[Drought in Australia|drought]], although police in NSW arrested at least 24 people for deliberately starting fires. In total, 7.3 million hectares (17.9 million acres) have burned across Australia's six states\u2014an area larger than [[Belgium]] and [[Denmark]] combined. Experts estimate 500 million animals died, not including bats, frogs, or insects; one-third of Australia's [[koala]]s were killed, according to [[Minister for the Environment (Australia)|Minister for the Environment]] [[Sussan Ley]].<ref>{{cite web|website=CNN World|title=Australia's deadly wildfires are showing no signs of stopping. Here's what you need to know |date=Jan 14, 2020|accessdate=Feb 8, 2020|author=Jessie Yeung|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/01/australia/australia-fires-explainer-intl-hnk-scli/index.html}}</ref>\n\n==History by issues and global trends ==\n\n===Climate change===\n{{See also|2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season}}\nThe [[United Nations]] calls climate change \"the defining issue of our time\",<ref>[https://www.un.org/en/sections/issues-depth/climate-change/ Climate Change] United Nations, retrieved 14 Jan 2020</ref> and the [[World Health Organization]] says it \"threatens the essential ingredients of good health - clean air, safe drinking water, nutritious food supply, and safe shelter - and has the potential to undermine decades of progress in global health\".<ref>[https://www.who.int/health-topics/climate-change#tab=tab_1 Climate change] World Health Organization, 14 Jan 2020</ref> 55% of American adult voters consider climate change an important issue in the [[2020 United States presidential election]].<ref>[https://news.gallup.com/poll/276932/several-issues-tie-important-2020-election.aspx Several Issues Tie as Most Important in 2020 Election] [[Gallup (company)|Gallup]], 13 January 2020</ref>\n\nThe environmental website ''Business Green'' predicts that the [[2020 United States presidential election]] will be crucial to action on climate change. Incumbent Republican President [[Donald Trump]] has already pulled out of the [[Paris Agreement]] and he continues to deny climate change,<ref>[https://insideclimatenews.org/news/19122019/trump-climate-policy-record-rollback-fossil-energy-history-candidate-profile Donald Trump's Record on Climate Change] by Stacey Feldman & Marianne Lavelle, Inside Climate News, 19 Dec 2019</ref> but his [[2020 Democratic Party presidential candidates|various Democratic opponents]] all support some kind of action on the issue.<ref>[https://www.vox.com/2019/9/10/20851109/2020-democrats-climate-change-plan-president A guide to how 2020 Democrats plan to fight climate change] By Umair Irfan, [[Vox (website)|Vox]], 19 Dec 2019</ref> The [[2019 United Nations Climate Change Conference|2019 United Nations Climate Change Conference (COP25)]] was not seen as successful, and COP26 may be just as fruitless. Electric vehicles are likely to offer the cheapest option in a few years, and many energy-inefficient businesses will probably go bankrupt. \"Peak meat\" may come about in the middle of the decade as consumers look for vegetarian alternatives. As renewable energy becomes less expensive, the demand for new technologies, such as long-lasting batteries and carbon storage will soar. Solid, particularly plastic, waste disposal will become a greater problem as many countries ban plastic waste imports and the petroleum industry changes from energy production to [https://webstore.iea.org/download/summary/190?fileName=English-WEO-2018-ES.pdf other uses of petrochemicals.pdf].<ref>{{cite web|website=GreenBiz|title=10 key trends to watch for the 2020s|author=Madeline Cuff|date=Jan 6, 2020|accessdate=Feb 1, 2020 |url=https://www.greenbiz.com/article/10-key-trends-watch-2020s}}</ref>\n\nA February 2020 study at the [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]] predicts that 70% to 90% of [[coral]] habitats will be destroyed by 2100.<ref>[https://www.theinertia.com/environment/scientists-predict-90-of-coral-reefs-will-disappear-by-2100/ Scientists Predict 90% of Coral Reefs Will Disappear By 2100] by Juan Hernandez, The Inertia, 18 Feb 2020</ref> The United Nations issued a statement in March 2020 stating that climate change is more mortal than [[COVID-19]], pointing out the loss of farmland, the effect of hurricanes and heatwaves, and the increase in diseases such as dengue. 100 people died and 18,000 were hospitalized in Japan while France reported 1,462 heat-related deaths in 2019. 2,800,000 people came down with dengue, leading to 1,250 deaths.<ref>[https://news.un.org/es/story/2020/03/1470901?fbclid=IwAR21rjJt1o_f8bsadkE61qoCzaqnkp3CRqBNIygsgBRHf0OCLbgXffn7Ins Climate change is more deadly than coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} United Nations News, 10 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n===Human rights===\n[[Heidi Hautala]], a [[member of the European Parliament]], writes that [[Slavery in the 21st century|40 million slaves]] in the world generate an estimated US$150 billion in profits a year and that purchasing products made with slave labor is legal in most European markets. She called upon the EU to lead in ending child labor and slave labor.<ref>[https://www.business-humanrights.org/en/responsible-business-conduct-the-european-business-model-of-the-2020s Responsible Business Conduct - the European Business model of the 2020s] Business & Human Rights Resource Centre, retrieved 1 Feb 2020</ref> [[Craig Kielburger]], founder of [[WE (organization)|WE]], sees mental health, data and privacy issues, and corporate social responsibility as human rights issues of the 2020s.<ref>[https://www.we.org/en-CA/we-stories/opinion/craig-kielburger-issues-that-will-define-the-next-decade-2020s What will define the next decade?] by Craig Kielburger, WE.org, retrieved 1 Feb 2020</ref> [[Alex Neve]] of [[Amnesty International|Amnesty International Canada]] and [[June Oscar]], a [[Bunuba|Bunuba aboriginal woman from Australia]] make the case for increased attention to indigenous rights in the 2020s.<ref>[https://www.thestar.com/opinion/contributors/2020/01/07/canada-human-rights-and-a-new-decade-time-to-dig-deeper-than-ever.html Canada, human rights and a new decade: time to dig deeper than ever] By Alex Neve, The Star (Toronto, Canada), 7 Jan 2020  [https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/31/june-oscars-2020s-vision-reaching-our-potential-as-a-nation-begins-with-truth-telling June Oscar's 2020s vision: Reaching our potential as a nation begins with truth-telling] by June Oscar, The Guardian (Australia), 30 Jan 2020</ref>\n\nThe [[Human Rights Watch]] [https://www.hrw.org/sites/default/files/supporting_resources/hrw_world_report_2019_etr_0.pdf World Report 2019.pdf] addresses human rights issues in [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemen]], Hungary, Syria, Venezuela, Philippines, Democratic Republic of Congo, China, United States, Myanmar, Turkey, Egypt, and Russia. They highlight immigration (including [[Trump administration family separation policy|family separation]]), religious oppression, food and medicine shortages, war and [[Chemical weapon proliferation|chemical weapons]], and a lack of democracy.<ref>[https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2019# WORLD REPORT 2019] by Kenneth Roth, Executive Director, Human Rights Watch, retrieved 1 Feb 2020</ref> [[Amnesty International|Amnesty International's]] top goals are to make [[same-sex relationship]]s legal, [[Abortion-rights movements|legalize abortion]], and [[Capital punishment by country|abolish the death penalty]] in all countries.'''\n\n====Women's rights====\nThe [[World Economic Forum]] published a report on the global gender gap in January 2020 that concludes gender parity will not be reached for 99.5 years. The report benchmarks 153 countries in four dimensions: Economic Participation and Opportunity, Educational Attainment, Health and Survival, and Political Empowerment. The top-ranking country for parity is [[Iceland]], and [[Albania]], [[Ethiopia]], [[Mali]], [[Mexico]], and [[Spain]] are the most improved. At least 35 countries have achieved gender parity in education, and 71 have closed at least 97% of the gap in health. Political empowerment remains poor\u201485 countries have never had a female head of state and women hold only 25% of all available positions, while eight countries have no women in government at all. Globally, only 55% of women (ages 15\u201364) are economically active, compared to 78% of men. 72 countries do not allow women to open bank accounts or obtain credit.<ref>{{cite web|website=World Economic Forum|title=Report: Mind the 100 Year Gap|accessdate=25 Jan 2020|language=en|url=https://www.weforum.org/reports/gender-gap-2020-report-100-years-pay-equality}}</ref>\n\nWriting on ''The European Sting,'' [[Saadia Zahidi]] writes there are three areas where the most can be done to close the gender gap. She says that businesses must take the lead, claiming that the most diverse companies are ones that have the best long-term performance. Second, she calls for both policy incentives and political role-models. \"As more women reach visible positions of power, it creates a virtuous cycle, normalizing the association of women and leadership for future generations. The role-model effect is already visible: countries with higher levels of women in political power also tend to have higher levels of women in business leadership,\" she writes. Third, she says we have a unique window to use education to train [[women in STEM fields]].<ref>{{cite web|website=European Sting|title=3 ways to make the 2020s the decade we close the gender gap|date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://europeansting.com/2019/12/18/3-ways-to-make-the-2020s-the-decade-we-close-the-gender-gap/}}</ref>\n\n===Technology===\nTrends in technology include greater use of [[Artificial intelligence|artificial intelligence (AI)]], [[Self-driving car|autonomous vehicles (AV)]], [[virtual reality]], a ten-year human [[Life expectancy|lifespan]] increase (due to better drugs, stem cell manipulation, and gene therapy), renewable and [[sustainable energy]], and space (commercialization, weaponization, and exploration).<ref>[http://connectedfuture.economist.com/connecting-capabilities/article/five-technologies-youll-use-2020s/ Five technologies you\u2019ll use in the 2020s] The Economist, Retrieved 16 Jan 2020  [https://singularityhub.com/2020/01/10/20-tech-metatrends-to-look-out-for-in-the-2020s/ 20 Technology Metatrends That Will Define the Next Decade] By Peter H. Diamandis, MD, Singularity Hub, 16 Jan 2020  [https://www.prweek.com/article/1670682/20-trends-2020s 20 trends for the 2020s] by Robert Moran, Brunswick Group, PR Week, 14 January 2020</ref>\n\nIn a January 2020 interview with ''[[Financial Times|the Financial Times]]'', German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] urged Europe to develop its own technology, such as [[List of battery types|manufacturing of batteries]], electric cars, and [[cloud computing]]. Europe depends mostly on Asia for electric car batteries, and it has no [[hyperscale computing]] companies to support companies like [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] and [[Facebook Platform|Facebook]].<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/16/tech/angela-merkel-tech-europe/index.html Angela Merkel: Europe should make its own chips and electric car batteries] By Charles Riley, CNN Business, 16 Jan 2020</ref>\n\n[[Switzerland|Switzerland's]] neutrality was called into question when it was in revealed in February 2020 that German and U.S. intelligence services had been using coding devices manufactured by [[Crypto AG]] to spy on other countries.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51487856 Swiss Crypto AG spying scandal shakes reputation for neutrality] BBC World, 16 Feb 2020</ref>\n\n===World banking and finance===\n====trends====\n[[BofA Securities]] analysts say a range of economic and social challenges are \"all heading to a boiling point\" in the 2020s. They predict peak [[globalization]] (including the trade wars between China and the U.S. and between [[2019 Japan\u2013South Korea trade dispute|South Korea and Japan]]), disruptive [[Demography|demographics]] (as people over-65 outnumber children under-5 for the first time), rising interest rates, and [[global warming]]. They predict that automation will return manufacturing away from low-income countries to countries of consumption. They predict higher inflation and outperformance by global equities and commodities versus bonds. They note that during the 2010s the \"economic spoils went to holders of capital, not workers,\" which is why interest rates will increase. The investment bank says that climate action could be transformative in energy, farming, transportation, and even globalization, adding \"Bold climate action could yield a direct economic gain of $US26 trillion through to 2030 compared with business as usual.\" Retailers may be hit hard as [[conspicuous consumption]] ends and sharing and [[Circular economy|circular economies]] become more popular.<ref>[https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-13/the-2020s-set-to-be-an-economic-turning-point/11699386 The 2020s are set to be an economic turning point, says global banking giant] By business reporter Michael Janda, ABC.net.au, 13 Nov 2019</ref>\n====history====\nIn 2020, concerns about corona virus caused major downturns in economic stock indexes.\n\n===World trade===\n[[Trump tariffs|Trump's trade wars]] appear to be drawing to a close as an agreement with [[China\u2013United States trade war|China]] and the ratification of the [[United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement]] approach.  Tomasz Brodzicki of [[IHS Markit]] predicts that world merchandise trade volume will increase by 2.7% to 14.175 billion tons (US$18.870 trillion) in 2020 and by 5% to 14.881 billion tons (US$19.795 trillion) in 2021. He forecasts the highest growth rates in 2020 for South and North America and the lowest for Africa. He predicts low trade growth for the U.S. and Canada and continuing conflicts with China, which should benefit [[Taiwan]], [[Vietnam]], and other parts of the [[ASEAN Free Trade Area]]. He also says the paralysis of the multilateral dispute settlement system in the [[World Trade Organization|World Trade Organization (WTO)]] will probably last.<ref name=tomasz>[https://ihsmarkit.com/research-analysis/outlook-for-global-trade-in-2020.html Outlook for Global Trade in 2020] Author: Tomasz Brodzicki, Ph.D., Senior Economist II, IHS Markit Maritime & Trade, 2 Jan 2020</ref>\n\nThe [[African Continental Free Trade Area |African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCTA)]] will go fully into effect on July 1, 2020, abolishing 90% of tariffs between member states and bringing a 50% increase in trade in the next few years.<ref name=hammond /> In June 2019 the [[Mercosur]] (Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay, and Uruguay) reached a [https://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2019/640138/EPRS_BRI(2019)640138_EN.pdf tentative agreement.pdf] with the [[European Union]]. They are also looking forward to similar agreements with the United States, Canada, and the EFTA bloc\u2014made up of [[Iceland]], [[Norway]], [[Liechtenstein]], and [[Switzerland]].<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mercosur-summit-argentina/south-american-bloc-eyes-fast-track-for-eu-trade-deal-idUSKCN1UC1PL South American bloc eyes fast-track for EU trade deal] by Maximilian Heath, Reuters Business News, 17 July 2019</ref>\n\nVarious analysts focused on the preservation and expansion of free trade; e.g., [[Michael Hirsh (journalist)|Michael Hirsh]] at ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' asserted that globalism and free trade would expand, despite the efforts of [[Donald Trump]] and other opponents of free trade.<ref>[https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/12/27/why-liberal-international-order-will-endure-next-decade-2020-democracy/ Why the Liberal International Order Will Endure Into the Next Decade] By Michael Hirsh, Foreign Policy, 27 Dec 2019, retrieved 2 March 2020</ref> Hirsh notes that despite Brexit, UK Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] remains committed to [[free trade]]. He also notes that other countries are expanding their efforts to increase trade.<ref>{{cite web|website=Foreign Policy|title=Why the Liberal International Order Will Endure Into the Next Decade|date=Dec 27, 2019|author=Michael Hirsh|accessdate=Feb 1, 2020|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/12/27/why-liberal-international-order-will-endure-next-decade-2020-democracy/}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{collapse top|See also}}\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n\n;General overviews\n* [[2020s]]\n* [[21st century]]\n* [[List of protests in the 21st century]]\n\n;Timeline articles for current year\n* [[2020]]\n* [[2020 in politics and government]]\n* [[2020 in science]]\n;Specific issues and topics\n* [[Brexit negotiations]]\n* [[Coronavirus disease 2019]]\n\n;Overviews and historical topics for this period\n* [[Premiership of Boris Johnson]]\n* [[Presidency of Donald Trump]]\n{{Col-break}}\n;Country and regional entries and timelines\n* [[2020 in the United States]]\n* [[2020 in United States politics and government]]\n* [[2020 in the Caribbean]]\n* [[2020 in Central America]]\n* [[2020 in East Africa]]\n* [[2020 in West Africa]]\n{{cat see also|2020 by country}}\n\n;Related decade overviews\n* 2020s decade overviews:\n**[[2020s in United Kingdom political history]]\n**[[Draft:2020s in United States political history]]\n* Related decade overviews: \n**[[2010s political history]]\n**[[2010s in United Kingdom political history]]\n**[[Draft:2010s in United States political history]]\n;Categories\n{{cat see also|21st-century social movements|Category:21st-century conflicts}}\n{{cat see also|2020s|2020s in politics|2020s economic history}}\n{{cat see also|2020|2020 in politics|2020 by country|2020 in law}}\n\n\n{{Col-break}}\n{{portal|Current events|Countries|Modern history|Africa|Asia|Europe|North America|South America|Oceania}}\n{{col end}}\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Collapse top|News outlets and informational sites}}\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n;World news sites\n*[https://www.realclearworld.com/ Real Clear World], news and commentary items from publications around the world\n*[https://twitter.com/ Twitter]\n\n;Europe\nChris Edwards of ''Global Horizons'' recommends eight international news sources:<ref>[http://natoassociation.ca/8-useful-world-news-sources/ 8 Useful World News Sources] Chris Edwards of global Horizons, NATO Association, 29 Aug 2013</ref>\n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/world BBC World News page], world news with a British/Western perspective\n*[https://www.economist.com/ The Economist], London-based economics news\nIn addition to the [[BBC World Service]], ''[[Esquire (magazine)]]'' recommends:<ref>[https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a5800/world-news-032509/ The Foreign Media: Four Sites That Do It Better Than We Do] BY TIM HEFFERNAN, Esquire, 25 Mar 2009</ref>\n*[https://www.spiegel.de/international/ Der Spiegel International (in English)], a European perspective\n*[https://iwpr.net/ The Institute for War and Peace Reporting]\n*[https://www.crisisgroup.org/ International Crisis Group]\n*[https://www.france24.com/en/ France 24 (TV network)], owned by the government of [[France 24|France]]\n\n;North America\n;;Wire services and capsulized news sites\n*[https://www.reuters.com/ Reuters wire service], New York City-based with mostly international and financial news\n*[https://www.ap.org/en-us/ The Associated Press wire service], New York-based wire service\n*[https://www.bloomberg.com/ Bloomberg News], financial and general news (paywall)\n*[https://edition.cnn.com/world CNN world news (TV network)], Atlanta-based with wide coverage, [[CNN International]]\n;Conventional newspaper and magazine websites\n*[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/ The Globe and Mail], Canadian and international news\n*[https://www.wsj.com/ The Wall Street Journal], business and general news (paywall)\n*[https://www.washingtonpost.com/ The Washington Post], U.S. political and general news (paywall)\n*[https://www.newyorker.com/ The New Yorker], in-depth reporting on news; also includes fiction (paywall)\n*[https://www.foreignaffairs.com/ Foreign Affairs magazine], premier U.S. magazine for foreign affairs (paywall)\n*[https://www.theatlantic.com/world/ The Atlantic magazine], Washington-based with long feature articles and analysis\n*[https://www.politico.com/ Politico], politics\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/ New York Times] U.S. and world news (paywall)\n*[https://mexiconewsdaily.com/about/ Mexico News Daily], world news from Mexico\n{{Col-break}}\n;Africa\n*[https://allafrica.com/ allAfrica]\n\n;Asia/Mideast\n*[https://www.aljazeera.com/ Al Jazeera], the Middle East and world news\n* [https://www.arabnews.com/world Arab News world news page]\n*[https://www.scmp.com/news/china South China Morning Post]\n*[https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia Channel News Asia (CNA)], world news from [[CNA (news channel)|Singapore]]\n*[https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/index.html China Daily], owned by the government of [[China Daily|China]]\n*[https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-international/ The Hindu], world news from [[The Hindu|India]]\n*[https://www.rt.com/news/ RT (TV network)], owned by the government of [[RT (TV network)|Russia]]\n\n;South America\n* [https://brazilian.report/ The Brazilian Report].\n*[https://latinamericanpost.com/ Latin American Post], world news from Colombia\n\n;General recommendations\n''[[Forbes]]'' recommends:<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/berlinschoolofcreativeleadership/2017/02/01/10-journalism-brands-where-you-will-find-real-facts-rather-than-alternative-facts/#406355f9e9b5 10 Journalism Brands Where You Find Real Facts Rather Than Alternative Facts] By Paul Glader of The Berlin School of Creative Leadership, Forbes, retrieved 1 Feb 2020</ref>\n*''[[The New York Times]]'', the BBC, and [[Reuters]]\n\n;UN informational websites\n* [https://unstats.un.org/unsd/dnss/cp/searchcp.aspx United Nations Country Profiles website]\n* [https://data.un.org/en/index.html UN Data website, index by individual countries]\n* [http://hdr.undp.org/en/content/country-profiles Country Profiles] at website for [[UN Development Program (UNDP)]], Human Development Reports\n* [http://countrystudies.us/ Coun