n 11-month transition period, during which they remain in the Single Market and Customs Union.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Edgington|first=Tom|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50838994|title=Brexit: What happens next?|date=2020-01-31|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-26|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Climate change===\nIn December 2019, the [[World Meteorological Organization]] released its annual climate report revealing that climate impacts are worsening.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/04/climate/climate-change-acceleration.html Climate Change Is Accelerating, Bringing World \u2018Dangerously Close\u2019 to Irreversible Change], By Henry Fountain, Dec. 4, 2019, NY Times.</ref> They found the global sea temperatures are rising as well as land temperatures worldwide. 2019 is the last year in a decade that is the warmest on record.<ref>[https://www.iflscience.com/environment/2019-ends-warmest-decade-on-record-state-of-the-global-climate-report-warns/ 2019 Ends Warmest Decade On Record, State Of The Global Climate Report Warns], iflscience.com</ref>\n\nGlobal carbon emissions hit a record high in 2019, even though the rate of increase slowed somewhat, according to a report from [[Global Carbon Project]].<ref>[https://phys.org/news/2019-12-global-carbon-emissions-growth-high.html Global carbon emissions growth slows, but hits record high], December 3, 2019, Stanford University via phys.org.</ref>\n\n=== COVID-19 ===\n{{see also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom||}}\n[[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] (though it was not yet named) was first reported to the [[World Health Organization|World Health Organisation]]'s Chinese office at the end of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/events-as-they-happen|title=Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19) - events as they happen|website=www.who.int|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> It spread rapidly around the world and the first  confirmed cases in the United kingdom were discovered in late January 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Brown|first=Tom Ball, Charlotte Wace {{!}} Chris Smyth, Whitehall Editor {{!}} David|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/hunt-for-contacts-of-coronavirus-stricken-pair-in-york-dh363qf8k|title=Hunt for contacts of coronavirus-stricken pair in York|access-date=2020-04-17|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 March, Boris Johnson announced the Coronavirus Action Plan and declared COVID-19 a \u2018level 4 outbreak\u2019. On 6 March he announced \u00a346 million in funding was to go to research to develop a vaccine and rapid diagnostic tests.\n\nThe government recommended that people practiced social distancing and avoid \u201cnon-essential travel,\u201d especially pregnant women, those with health conditions, or those over the age of 70. Vulnerable groups were encouraged to self-isolate. Johnson announced that the majority of UK schools would be closed starting 20 March.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51952314|title=UK schools to close from Friday|date=2020-03-18|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, Johnson announced that restrictions would be placed on freedom of movement within the UK, which would be enforceable by law.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52012432|title=Strict new curbs on life in UK announced by PM|date=2020-03-24|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== History by major political party ==\n{{See also|Political parties in the UK}}\n\n=== Conservatives ===\n{{Empty section|date=February 2020}}\n\n=== Labour ===\nAs both [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]'s leader ([[Jeremy Corbyn]]) and deputy leader ([[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]]) had resigned or announced their intention to do so in late 2019,<ref>{{Cite news|last=editor|first=Heather Stewart Political|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/06/tom-watson-to-quit-as-labour-deputy-leader-and-stand-down-as-mp|title=Tom Watson quits as Labour deputy leader and steps down as MP|date=2019-11-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/jeremy-corbyn-resigns-as-labour-party-leader-after-election-defeat-2019-12|title=Jeremy Corbyn announces he will resign as Labour Party leader|last=Bienkov|first=Thomas Colson, Adam|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> the party had both a [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|leadership]] and [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election|deputy leadership]] contest in early 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2020/01/5-leadership-and-5-deputy-candidates-through-to-next-stage-of-contests/|title=5 leadership and 5 deputy candidates through to next stage of contests|last=Chappell|first=Elliot|last2=Rodgers|first2=Sienna|date=2020-01-13|website=LabourList|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> The leadership contest was won by [[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|Shadow secretary of state for exiting the European Union]] [[Keir Starmer|Kier Starmer]] with 275,780 votes (56.2% of the vote share).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52164589|title=Keir Starmer elected as new Labour leader|date=2020-04-04|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-GB}}</ref> [[Angela Rayner]] became the deputy leader, achieving 192,168 first preference votes (41.7% of the vote share) and winning a majority on the second preference votes of weaker candidates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://labour.org.uk/people/leadership-elections-hub-2020/leadership-elections-2020-results/|title=Leaderhip Elections 2020 Results|website=The Labour Party|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Liberal Democrats ===\nAs their leader ([[Jo Swinson]]) lost her seat at the 2019 general election, the liberal democrats announced early in 2020 that they planned to have [[2020 Liberal Democrats leadership election|new leader]] in place by the middle of July that year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51164894|title=New Liberal Democrat leader in place by mid-July|date=2020-01-18|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-11|language=en-GB}}</ref> The contest was later suspended to 2021 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|global coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52062239|title=Lib Dems suspend leadership contest until 2021|date=2020-03-27|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== Scottish National Party ===\n{{Empty section|date=February 2020}}\n\n== History by devolved administration ==\n{{See also|Devolution in the United Kingdom}}\n\n=== Scottish Government ===\n{{Empty section|date=February 2020}}\n\n=== Greater London Authority ===\nThe [[2021 London mayoral election|London mayoral election]] originally due to take place in May 2020 was suspended for a year due to the global [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51876269|title=English local elections postponed over coronavirus|date=2020-03-13|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-21|language=en-GB}}</ref><br />\n=== Welsh Government ===\n{{Empty section|date=February 2020}}\n\n=== Northern Irish Executive  ===\nThe northern Irish assembly returned to business in January 2020 after a three-year hiatus with a new power sharing agreement between [[Sinn F\u00e9in|Sinn F\u00e9in]] and the [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/northern-ireland-devolution-formally-restored-as-power-sharing-resumes-at-stormont-11906096|title=Northern Ireland: Devolution formally restored as power-sharing resumes at Stormont|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\n== History by local government ==\n{{See also|Local government in the United Kingdom}}[[2021 United Kingdom local elections|Local elections in England]] as well as [[2021 England and Wales police and crime commissioner elections|police and crime commissioner elections in England and Wales]] were postponed from May 2020 to 2021 due to the global 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51876269|title=English local elections postponed over coronavirus|date=2020-03-13|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-21|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n===Timeline articles===\n*Timelines articles\n** [[2020]]\n** [[2020 in politics and government]]\n*Other UK timelines \n**[[2020 in the United Kingdom]]\n*2010s decade articles\n**[[2010s in political history]]\n**[[2010s in United Kingdom political history]]\n\n===UK articles===\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|England|Northern Ireland|Scotland|Wales}}\n* [[Countries of the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Outline of the United Kingdom]]\n** [[Outline of England]]\n** [[Outline of Northern Ireland]]\n** [[Outline of Scotland]]\n** [[Outline of Wales]]\n* [[Index of United Kingdom-related articles]]\n* [[International rankings of the United Kingdom]]\n{{books-inline|United Kingdom}}\n\n\n{{cat see also|politics overviews by decade}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|n=Category:United Kingdom|voy=United Kingdom|d=Q145}}\n; Government\n* [http://www.gov.uk/ Official website of HM Government]\n* [http://www.royal.gov.uk/ Official website of the British Monarchy]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131210042804/http://ons.gov.uk/ons/index.html Official Yearbook of the United Kingdom] statistics\n* [http://www.number10.gov.uk/ The official site of the British Prime Minister's Office]\n\n; General information\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-18023389 United Kingdom] from the [[BBC News]]\n* {{CIA World Factbook link|uk|United Kingdom}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090406224510/http://ucblibraries.colorado.edu/govpubs/for/british.htm United Kingdom] from ''UCB Libraries GovPubs''\n* {{curlie|Regional/Europe/United_Kingdom}}\n* [http://www